{"title_page": "Patric Knowles", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Patric Knowles\n| image        = Patric Knowles.jpg\n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1911|11|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Horsforth]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1995|12|23|1911|11|11|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Woodland Hills, California]], U.S.\n| birth_name   = Reginald Lawrence Knowles\n| parents      = Lawrence Knowles, Nellie Knowles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gss=angs-c&new=1&rank=1&mst...|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n| known_for    = \n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1932\u20131973\n| spouse       = Enid Percival (1935\u20131995; his death) 2 children: Michael Knowles (born 5/11/1938), Antonia Knowles (12/7/1942)}}\n\n'''Reginald Lawrence Knowles''' (11 November 1911 \u2013 23 December 1995) was an English film [[actor]] who renamed himself '''Patric Knowles'''. Born in [[Horsforth]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], he made his film debut in 1932, and played either first or second film leads throughout his career. He appeared in films from the 1930s to the 1970s.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early Life===\nOn 11 November 1911, Reginald Lawrence Knowles was born in Milton College, Horsforth.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Yorkshire evening post|date=1984-01-27}}</ref> His father, Lawrence Knowles, was  age 22 and was working as an accountant clerk. Reginald's mother, Nellie Knowles, was age 19 and working as a dressmaker. The couple had only been married for under a year at the time of Knowles birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interactive.ancestrylibrary.com/Print/2352/rg14_25925_0317_03/26623060?landscape+true&sourcePlacement=0&query+backurl}}</ref> He also had two brothers, Phillip and William Knowles.\n\nFrom the age of 14, Knowles left school and was being groomed to take his place alongside other relatives in the family bookbinding business in Leeds.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mcpeak|first1=William|title=Patric Knowles Biography|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0461549/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|website=IMDB|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> However, Knowles was persistent in following his dreams as an actor and ran away from home at the age of 14, but was brought back. He ran away again in later years, which proved to be more successful.\n\n===British Acting Career===\nKnowles began his acting career with the British sound films early in 1932, calling himself, Patric Knowles. He made his film debut in ''[[Men of Tomorrow]]'' (1932), produced by [[Alexander Korda]].\n\nHe later joined the repertory group of the Playhouse Theater in Oxford and began touring with various companies and was involved in some seasons in regional theater, being featured in 14 British films, including ''[[The Poisoned Diamond]]'' (1933), directed by [[W. P. Kellino]]; ''[[Norah O'Neale]]'' (1934), directed by [[Brian Desmond Hurst]]; ''[[Regal Cavalcade]]'' (1935); and ''[[The Girl in the Crowd]]'' (1935), directed by [[Michael Powell]]. \n\nHe had the male lead in ''[[The Student's Romance]]'' (1935) with [[Grete Natzler]] and ''[[Honours Easy]]'' (1935) with [[Greta Nissen]] and was in ''[[Abdul the Damned (film)|Abdul the Damned]]'' (1935), ''[[Mister Hobo]]'' (1935) with [[George Arliss]], ''[[Wrath of Jealousy]]'' (1936), and ''[[Two's Company (film)|Two's Company]]'' (1936).<ref>The Life Story of PATRIC KNOWLES\nPicture Show; London Vol. 40, Iss. 1,039,  (Mar 25, 1939): 18.</ref>\n\nDuring the same time, Knowles met Gladys Enid Percival, an actress and homemaker, and married the 23 year old on 3 October 1935.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trees.ancestrylibrary.com/tree/65760458/person/46144476336/print}}</ref>\n\nAfter a few tours Knowles went to London and appeared in \"By Appointment\" in 1936, where he was spotted by Irving Asher of Warner Bros. and got a Hollywood contract for more than 2 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1995-12-27/local/me-18313_1_patric-knolwes}}</ref> He had the lead in his final British films, ''[[The Brown Wallet]]'' (1936), directed by Powell; ''[[Fair Exchange (film)|Fair Exchange]]'' (1936),directed by [[Ralph Ince]]; and ''[[Crown v. Stevens]]'' (1936), directed by Powell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27989252 |title=YOUNG MEN WHO WERE \"DISCOVERED\" IN LONDON. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=30,933 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1937 |accessdate=3 October 2018 |page=9 (Women's Supplement) |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\n===Warner Bros===\nIn 1936 he arrived in New York alongside his wife and appeared in his first [[United States|American]] film, ''[[Give Me Your Heart (film)|Give Me Your Heart]]'' (1936) with [[Kay Francis]], released in [[UK|Great Britain]] as ''Sweet Aloes'', Knowles was cast as a titled Englishman of means. \n\nIn 1939 and at the age of 27, Knowles moved to his new residence with his wife in Tarzana, Los Angeles, California, USA. During his free time Knowles became a licensed private pilot in the late 1930s.\n\nHis second film for Warners was ''[[The Charge of the Light Brigade (1936 film)|The Charge of the Light Brigade]]'' (1936), where he played the younger brother of [[Errol Flynn]], who was loved by [[Olivia de Havilland]].<ref>Irvin Cobb, Film Future Secure, to Star in \"Gentleman From Mississippi\": Writer's Thespianic Adventure Proceeds Claude Rains and Charles Boyer Both Will Have Fling at Napoleon Interpretation; Choir Singer in \"Stagestruck\"\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 9 Mar 1936: 15.</ref> Knowles returned to England to make ''[[Irish for Luck]]'' (1936), and then supported [[Bette Davis]] in ''[[It's Love I'm After]]'' (1937).\n\nKnowles was top billed in some B pictures at Warners, ''[[Expensive Husbands]]'' (1937) and ''[[The Patient in Room 18]]'' (1938). He was reteamed with Flynn and De Havilland in ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1938), playing [[Will Scarlett]], and ''[[Four's a Crowd]]'' (1938). He supported Flynn and Davis in ''[[The Sisters (1938 film)|The Sisters]]'' (1938).<ref>More than two [[decades]] after Flynn's death, biographer [[Charles Higham (biographer)|Charles Higham]] accused Flynn of having been a [[fascist]] sympathizer and [[Nazi]] [[spy]]. Knowles, who had served in [[World War II]] as a flying instructor in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]], came to Flynn's defense, writing ''Rebuttal for a Friend'' as an [[epilogue]] to Tony Thomas' ''Errol Flynn: The Spy Who Never Was'' (Citadel Press, 1990) {{ISBN|0-8065-1180-X}}.</ref>\n\nRepublic borrowed Knowles to play the lead in ''[[Storm Over Bengal]]'' (1938). <ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article143835960 |title=FILM FLASHES |newspaper=[[The Broadcaster]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=17 August 1939 |accessdate=3 October 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nAt Warners he had support roles in two B pictures, ''[[Heart of the North]]'' (1938) and ''[[Torchy Blane in Chinatown]]'' (1939), then he left the studio.\n\n===RKO===\nKnowles signed a contract at RKO, for whom he made ''[[Beauty for the Asking]]'' (1939) with Lucille Ball; ''[[Five Came Back]]'' (1939) also with Ball, directed by [[John Farrow]]; and ''[[The Spellbinder]]'' (1939).\n\nHe went to MGM for ''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939) and Fox for ''[[The Honeymoon's Over (film)|The Honeymoon's Over]]'' (1939) then went back to RKO for two more with John Farrow, ''[[Married and in Love]]'' (1940) and ''[[A Bill of Divorcement (1940 film)|A Bill of Divorcement]]'' (1940), then ''[[Anne of Windy Poplars (film)|Anne of Windy Poplars]]'' (1941), playing [[Gilbert Blythe]]. \n\nIn 1940 a limerick circulated about Knowles:  How pleasant to know Patric Knowles/ Who is the kindest of souls/ But being handsome and a British swell/ Nobody expects him to act very well/ Which is why he never gets good roles. <ref>Obituary: Patric Knowles Secondary panache\nBergan, Ronald. The Guardian 2 Jan 1996: 013. </ref>\n\n===World War Two===\nIn 1940 Knowles left Hollywood and travelled to Canada to enlist in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]]. He had hundreds of hours of flying experience but an eye ailment meant he became an instructor.<ref name=\"air\">Sergeant-Pilot Pat Knowles Pays Visit to Hollywood: Actor on Leave From Training Post With Canadian Air Force\nLos Angeles Times 19 Mar 1941: 3. </ref>\n\nAt Fox he was in ''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1941) for John Ford.<ref name=\"los\">Patric Knowles; British Actor\nLos Angeles Times 27 Dec 1995: VYB5. </ref>\n\n===Universal===\nKnowles went to Universal for a support part in ''[[The Wolf Man (1941 film)|The Wolf Man]]'' (1941). He went to Republic for ''[[Women in War]]'' (1941) then was top billed in Universal's ''[[The Strange Case of Doctor Rx]]'' (1942), and ''[[Mystery of Marie Roget]]'' (1942) with [[Maria Montez]]. \n\nHe supported [[Irene Dunne]] in ''[[Lady in a Jam]]'' (1942), [[Constance Bennett]] in ''[[Sin Town (1942 film)|Sin Town]]'' (1942), [[Abbott and Costello]] in ''[[Who Done It? (1942 film)|Who Done It?]]'' (1942) and ''[[Hit the Ice (film)|Hit the Ice]]'' (1943), [[Ilona Massey]] in ''[[Frankenstein Meets the Wolf Man]]'' (1943), [[Lane Sisters|Rosemary Lane]] in ''[[All by Myself (film)|All by Myself]]'' (1943), [[The Andrews Sisters]] in ''[[Always a Bridesmaid (1943 film)|Always a Bridesmaid]]'' (1943), [[Olsen and Johnson]] in ''[[Crazy House (1943 film)|Crazy House]]'' (1943), [[Donald O'Connor]] and Peggy Ryan in ''[[Chip Off the Old Block]]'' (1944) and ''[[This Is the Life (1944 film)|This Is the Life]]'' (1944), and [[Gloria Jean]] in ''[[Pardon My Rhythm]]'' (1944).<ref>Patric Knowles Has Schedule Of Farm Chores\nThe Washington Post 13 Dec 1942: L3. </ref>\n\nDuring this time he continued to serve as a flying instructor with the US Air Force.<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n===Paramount===\nKnowles went to Paramount where he supported [[Paulette Goddard]] in ''[[Kitty (1945 film)|Kitty]]'' (1945), [[Dorothy Lamour]] in ''[[Masquerade in Mexico]]'' (1945), [[Barbara Stanwyck]] in ''[[The Bride Wore Boots]]'' (1946), and [[Alan Ladd]] in ''[[O.S.S. (film)|O.S.S.]]'' (1946).<ref>obituaries: Patric Knowles: [FINAL Edition]\nShipman, David. The Independent30 Dec 1995: 14. </ref>\n\nHe went to Warners for ''[[Of Human Bondage (1946 film)|Of Human Bondage]]'' (1946) and Universal borrowed him to play [[Joan Fontaine]]'s leading man in the thriller ''[[Ivy (1947 film)|Ivy]]'' (1947).<ref>MISS DURBIN TO DO 'FOR LOVE OF MARY': Actress Is Named for Comedy by Universal-International-- 'Central Park' Postponed Buchman Buys \"Dark Page\"\nSpecial to THE NEW YORK TIMES.. New York Times (1923-Current file); New York, N.Y. [New York, N.Y]07 Dec 1946: 27</ref> He went back to Paramount for ''[[Monsieur Beaucaire (1946 film)|Monsieur Beaucaire]]'' (1946) with [[Bob Hope]], ''[[Variety Girl]]'' (1947), ''[[Dream Girl (1948 film)|Dream Girl]]'' (1948), and ''[[Isn't It Romantic? (1948 film)|Isn't It Romantic?]]'' (1949).<ref>Patric Knowles Winds Up Tribute to St. Patrick in Jail\nLos Angeles Times 19 Mar 1947: 2. </ref>\n\nKnowles went to RKO for ''[[The Big Steal (1949 film)|The Big Steal]]'' (1949), and Fox for ''[[Three Came Home]]'' (1950), second billed, playing [[Claudette Colbert]]'s husband.<ref>Secondary panache\nKnowles, Patric. The Guardian 2 Jan 1996: 13. </ref>\n\n===Television===\nKnowles began appearing on TV shows such as ''[[The Bigelow Theatre]]'', ''[[Studio One in Hollywood]]'', ''[[Lights Out (1946 TV series)|Lights Out]]'', ''[[Hollywood Opening Night]]'', ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]'', ''[[The Revlon Mirror Theater]]'', ''[[The United States Steel Hour]]'', ''[[The Whistler (TV series)|The Whistler]]'', ''[[Studio 57]]'', ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'', and ''[[Jane Wyman Presents The Fireside Theatre]]''.\n\nHe still appeared in features such as ''[[Quebec (1951 film)|Quebec]]'' (1951), ''[[Mutiny (1952 film)|Mutiny]]'' (1952), ''[[Tarzan's Savage Fury]]'' (1952) (as the villain), ''[[Jamaica Run]]'' (1953), ''[[Flame of Calcutta]]'' (1953) for [[Sam Katzman]] (second billed to [[Denise Darcel]]), ''[[World for Ransom]]'' (1954), ''[[Khyber Patrol]]'' (1954) and ''[[No Man's Woman (film)|No Man's Woman]]'' (1955).<ref>Drama: Rooney Would Do Caddy Sleuth; Patric Knowles Plays Rebel in 'Quebec'\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 27 May 1950: 9. </ref>\n\nFrom the late 1950s Knowles became an almost exclusively television actor appearing in ''[[Star Stage]]'', ''[[The 20th Century-Fox Hour]]'', ''[[Tales of the 77th Bengal Lancers ]]'', ''[[Ethel Barrymore Theatre (TV series)|Ethel Barrymore Theater]]'', ''[[Lux Video Theatre]]'', ''[[Matinee Theatre]]'', ''[[Schlitz Playhouse]]'', ''[[The Millionaire (TV series)|The Millionaire]]'', ''[[Lux Playhouse]]'', ''[[Walt Disney's Wonderful World of Color]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Tightrope (TV series)|Tightrope]]'', ''[[Maverick (TV series)|Maverick]]'', ''[[The Barbara Stanwyck Show]]'', ''[[Klondike (TV series)|Klondike]]'', ''[[The Jim Backus Show]]'', ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', ''[[The Islanders (TV series)|The Islanders]]'', ''[[Checkmate (TV series)|Checkmate]]'', ''[[Peter Gunn]]'', ''[[Whispering Smith (TV series)|Whispering Smith]]'', ''[[Hawaiian Eye]]'', ''[[Have Gun - Will Travel]]'' (as [[Phileas Fogg]] in the episode \"Foggbound\"), ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[The Rogues (TV series)|The Rogues]]'', ''[[Mickey (TV series)|Mickey]]'', and ''[[Jericho (1966 TV series)|Jericho]]''.\n\nHe had a small role in the feature ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957), ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (film)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1958) and ''[[Auntie Mame (film)|Auntie Mame]]'' (1958).\n\nHe wrote a novel, ''Even Steven'' (Vantage Press, 1960, [[ASIN]] B0006RMC2G).\n\n===Later Career===\nKnowles' later appearances included ''[[The Way West (film)|The Way West]]'' (1967) for director [[Andrew McLaglen]] ''[[Family Affair]]'', ''[[Garrison's Gorillas]]'', ''[[The Devil's Brigade (film)|The Devil's Brigade]]'' (1968) for McLaglen, ''[[In Enemy Country]]'' (1968), ''[[D.A.: Murder One]]'' (1969), ''[[Chisum]]'' (1970) with John Wayne for McLaglen as [[John Tunstall]], ''[[Getting Together]]'', ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]'', ''[[The Man (1972 film)|The Man]]'' (1972), ''[[Terror in the Wax Museum]]'' (1973) and ''[[Arnold (film)|Arnold]]'' (1973).\n\nKnowles was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n\n===Death===\nKnowles died from a brain hemorrhage at West Hills Hospital in [[West Hills, California]] on 23 December 1995, where he was cremated and his ashes distributed to family and friends.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mcpeak|first1=William|title=Patric Knowles Biography|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0461549/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|website=IMDB|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> At the point of his death, Knowles left behind his wife Gladys, his 2 children as well as four grandchildren.<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[Men of Tomorrow]]'' (1932)\n*''[[The Poisoned Diamond]]'' (1933) as Jack Dane\n*''[[Irish Hearts]]'' (1934) as Pip Fitzgerald\n*''[[Royal Cavalcade]]'' (1935) as Army Officer\n*''[[The Girl in the Crowd]]'' (1935) as Tom Burrows\n*''[[The Student's Romance]]'' (1935) as Max Brandt\n*''[[Honours Easy]]'' (1935) as Harry Markham\n*''[[Abdul the Damned]]'' (1935) as Omar - Hilmi's Attache\n*''[[The Guv'nor (film)|The Guv'nor]]'' (1935) as Paul\n*''[[Wedding Group]]'' (1936) as Robert Smith\n*''[[Two's Company (film)|Two's Company]]'' (1936) as Lord Jerry Wendower\n*''[[Fair Exchange (film)|Fair Exchange]]'' (1936) as Tony Meredith\n*''[[The Brown Wallet]]'' (1936) as John Gillespie\n*''[[Crown v. Stevens]]'' (1936) as Chris Jensen\n*''[[Give Me Your Heart (film)|Give Me Your Heart]]'' (1936) as Robert Melford\n*''[[The Charge of the Light Brigade (1936 film)|The Charge of the Light Brigade]]'' (1936) as Captain Perry Vickers\n*''[[Irish for Luck]]'' (1936) as Terry O'Ryan\n*''[[It's Love I'm After]]'' (1937) as Henry Grant\n*''[[Expensive Husbands]]'' (1937) as Prince Rupert Heinrich Franz Von Rentzau\n*''[[The Patient in Room 18 (film)|The Patient in Room 18]]'' (1938) as Lance O'Leary\n*''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1938) as Will Scarlett\n*''[[Four's a Crowd]]'' (1938) as Patterson Buckley\n*''[[The Sisters (1938 film)|The Sisters]]'' (1938) as Norman French\n*''[[Storm Over Bengal]]'' (1938) as Capt. Jeffrey Allison\n*''[[Heart of the North]]'' (1938) as Corporal Jim Montgomery\n*''[[Torchy Blane in Chinatown]]'' (1939) as Captain Condon\n*''[[Beauty for the Asking]]'' (1939) as Denny Williams\n*''[[Five Came Back]]'' (1939) as Judson Ellis\n*''[[The Spellbinder]]'' (1939) as Tom Dixon\n*''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939) as Dudley Horn\n*''[[The Honeymoon's Over (film)|The Honeymoon's Over]]'' (1939) as Pat Shields\n*''[[Married and in Love]]''(1940) as Paul Wilding\n*''[[A Bill of Divorcement (1940 film)|A Bill of Divorcement]]'' (1940) as John Storm\n*''[[Women in War]]'' (1940) as Lt. Larry Hall\n*''[[Anne of Windy Poplars (film)|Anne of Windy Poplars]]'' (1940) as Gilbert Blythe\n*''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1941) as Ivor\n*''[[The Wolf Man (1941 film)|The Wolf Man]]'' (1941) as Frank Andrews\n*''[[The Strange Case of Doctor Rx]]'' (1942) as Jerry Church\n*''[[The Mystery of Marie Roget (film)|The Mystery of Marie Roget]]'' (1942) as Dr. Paul Dupin\n*''[[Lady in a Jam]]'' (1942) as Doctor Enright\n*''[[Sin Town (1942 film)|Sin Town]]'' (1942) as Wade Crowell\n*''[[Who Done It? (1942 film)|Who Done It?]]'' (1942) as Jimmy Turner\n*''[[Forever and a Day (1943 film)|Forever and a Day]]'' (1943) as Trimble-Pomfret Son\n*''[[Frankenstein Meets the Wolf Man]]'' (1943) as Dr. Mannering\n*''[[Hit the Ice (film)|Hit the Ice]]'' (1943) as Dr. Bill Elliot (Credits) / Dr. William 'Bill' Burns (in Film)\n*''All by Myself'' (1943) as Dr. Bill Perry\n*''[[Always a Bridesmaid (1943 film)|Always a Bridesmaid]]'' (1943) as Tony Warren\n*''[[Crazy House (1943 film)|Crazy House]]'' (1943) as Edmund 'Mac' MacLean\n*''[[Chip Off the Old Block]]'' (1944) as Commander Judd Corrigan\n*''[[This Is the Life (1944 film)|This Is the Life]]'' (1944) as Maj. Hilary Jarret\n*''[[Pardon My Rhythm]]'' (1944) as Tony Page\n*''[[Kitty (1945 film)|Kitty]]'' (1945) as Brett Harwood Earl of Carstairs\n*''[[Masquerade in Mexico]]'' (1945) as Thomas Grant\n*''[[The Bride Wore Boots]]'' (1946) as Lance Gale\n*''[[O.S.S. (film)|O.S.S.]]'' (1946) as Cmdr. Brady\n*''[[Of Human Bondage (1946 film)|Of Human Bondage]]'' (1946) as Harry Griffiths\n*''[[Monsieur Beaucaire (1946 film)|Monsieur Beaucaire]]'' (1946) as Duc le Chandre\n*''[[Ivy (1947 film)|Ivy]]'' (1947) as Roger Gretorex\n*''[[Variety Girl]]'' (1947) as Patric KInowles\n*''[[Dream Girl (1948 film)|Dream Girl]]'' (1948) as Jim Lucas\n*''[[Isn't It Romantic? (1948 film)|Isn't It Romantic?]]'' (1948) as Richard 'Rick' Brannon\n*''[[The Big Steal]]'' (1949) as Jim Fiske\n*''[[Three Came Home]]'' (1950) as Harry Keith\n*''[[Quebec (1951 film)|Quebec]]'' (1951) as Charles Douglas\n*''[[Mutiny (1952 film)|Mutiny]]'' (1952) as Capt. Ben Waldridge\n*''[[Tarzan's Savage Fury]]'' (1952) as Edwards, English Traitor\n*''[[Jamaica Run]]'' (1953) as William Montague\n*''[[Flame of Calcutta]]'' (1953) as Capt. Keith Lambert\n*''[[World for Ransom]]'' (1954) as Julian March\n*''[[Khyber Patrol]]'' (1954) as Lt. George Kennedy\n*''[[No Man's Woman (film)|No Man's Woman]]'' (1955) as Wayne Vincent\n*''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957) as Charles de Marigny\n*''[[From the Earth to the Moon (film)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1958) as Josef Cartier\n*''[[Auntie Mame (film)|Auntie Mame]]'' (1958) as Lindsay Woolsey\n*''[[The Way West (film)|The Way West]]'' (1967) as Captain Grant\n*''[[The Devil's Brigade (film)|The Devil's Brigade]]'' (1968) as Adm. Lord Mountbatten\n*''[[In Enemy Country]]'' (1968) as General Lloyd-Griffis\n*''[[Chisum]]'' (1970) as Henry Tunstall\n*''[[The Man (1972 film)|The Man]]'' (1972) as South African Consul\n*''[[Terror in the Wax Museum]]'' (1973) as Mr. Southcott\n*''[[Arnold (film)|Arnold]]'' (1973) as Douglas Whitehead (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Alistair |first= Rupert |title= The Name Below the Title : 65 Classic Movie Character Actors from Hollywood's Golden Age |chapter= Patric Knowles |pages= 137-139 |date= 2018 |edition= First |type= softcover |publisher= Independently published |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-7200-3837-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|0461549}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knowles, Patric}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Horsforth]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Patric Knowles\n| image        = Patric Knowles.jpg\n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1911|11|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Horsforth]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1995|12|23|1911|11|11|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Woodland Hills, California]], U.S.\n| birth_name   = Reginald Lawrence Knowles\n| parents      = Lawrence Knowles, Nellie Knowles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gss=angs-c&new=1&rank=1&mst...|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n| known_for    = \n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1932\u20131973\n| spouse       = Enid Percival (1935\u20131995; his death) 2 children: Michael Knowles (born 5/11/1938), Antonia Knowles (12/7/1942)}}\n\n'''Reginald Lawrence Knowles''' (11 November 1911 \u2013 23 December 1995) was an English film [[actor]] who renamed himself '''Patric Knowles'''. Born in [[Horsforth]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], he made his film debut in 1932, and played either first or second film leads throughout his career. He appeared in films from the 1930s to the 1970s.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early Life===\nOn 11 November 1911, Reginald Lawrence Knowles was born in Milton College, Horsforth.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Yorkshire evening post|date=1984-01-27}}</ref> His father, Lawrence Knowles, was  age 22 and was working as an accountant clerk. Reginald's mother, Nellie Knowles, was age 19 and working as a dressmaker. The couple had only been married for under a year at the time of Knowles birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interactive.ancestrylibrary.com/Print/2352/rg14_25925_0317_03/26623060?landscape+true&sourcePlacement=0&query+backurl}}</ref> He also had two brothers, Phillip and William Knowles.\n\nFrom the age of 14, Knowles left school and was being groomed to take his place alongside other relatives in the family bookbinding business in Leeds.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mcpeak|first1=William|title=Patric Knowles Biography|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0461549/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|website=IMDB|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> However, Knowles was persistent in following his dreams as an actor and ran away from home at the age of 14, but was brought back. He ran away again in later years, which proved to be more successful.\n\n===British Acting Career===\nKnowles began his acting career with the British sound films early in 1932, calling himself, Patric Knowles. He made his film debut in ''[[Men of Tomorrow]]'' (1932), produced by [[Alexander Korda]].\n\nHe later joined the repertory group of the Playhouse Theater in Oxford and began touring with various companies and was involved in some seasons in regional theater, being featured in 14 British films, including ''[[The Poisoned Diamond]]'' (1933), directed by [[W. P. Kellino]]; ''[[Norah O'Neale]]'' (1934), directed by [[Brian Desmond Hurst]]; ''[[Regal Cavalcade]]'' (1935); and ''[[The Girl in the Crowd]]'' (1935), directed by [[Michael Powell]]. \n\nHe had the male lead in ''[[The Student's Romance]]'' (1935) with [[Grete Natzler]] and ''[[Honours Easy]]'' (1935) with [[Greta Nissen]] and was in ''[[Abdul the Damned (film)|Abdul the Damned]]'' (1935), ''[[Mister Hobo]]'' (1935) with [[George Arliss]], ''[[Wrath of Jealousy]]'' (1936), and ''[[Two's Company (film)|Two's Company]]'' (1936).<ref>The Life Story of PATRIC KNOWLES\nPicture Show; London Vol. 40, Iss. 1,039,  (Mar 25, 1939): 18.</ref>\n\nDuring the same time, Knowles met Gladys Enid Percival, an actress and homemaker, and married the 23 year old on 3 October 1935.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trees.ancestrylibrary.com/tree/65760458/person/46144476336/print}}</ref>\n\nAfter a few tours Knowles went to London and appeared in \"By Appointment\" in 1936, where he was spotted by Irving Asher of Warner Bros. and got a Hollywood contract for more than 2 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1995-12-27/local/me-18313_1_patric-knolwes}}</ref> He had the lead in his final British films, ''[[The Brown Wallet]]'' (1936), directed by Powell; ''[[Fair Exchange (film)|Fair Exchange]]'' (1936),directed by [[Ralph Ince]]; and ''[[Crown v. Stevens]]'' (1936), directed by Powell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27989252 |title=YOUNG MEN WHO WERE \"DISCOVERED\" IN LONDON. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=30,933 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1937 |accessdate=3 October 2018 |page=9 (Women's Supplement) |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\n===Warner Bros===\nIn 1936 he arrived in New York alongside his wife and appeared in his first [[United States|American]] film, ''[[Give Me Your Heart (film)|Give Me Your Heart]]'' (1936) with [[Kay Francis]], released in [[UK|Great Britain]] as ''Sweet Aloes'', Knowles was cast as a titled Englishman of means. \n\nIn 1939 and at the age of 27, Knowles moved to his new residence with his wife in Tarzana, Los Angeles, California, USA. During his free time Knowles became a licensed private pilot in the late 1930s.\n\nHis second film for Warners was ''[[The Charge of the Light Brigade (1936 film)|The Charge of the Light Brigade]]'' (1936), where he played the younger brother of [[Errol Flynn]], who was loved by [[Olivia de Havilland]].<ref>Irvin Cobb, Film Future Secure, to Star in \"Gentleman From Mississippi\": Writer's Thespianic Adventure Proceeds Claude Rains and Charles Boyer Both Will Have Fling at Napoleon Interpretation; Choir Singer in \"Stagestruck\"\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 9 Mar 1936: 15.</ref> Knowles returned to England to make ''[[Irish for Luck]]'' (1936), and then supported [[Bette Davis]] in ''[[It's Love I'm After]]'' (1937).\n\nKnowles was top billed in some B pictures at Warners, ''[[Expensive Husbands]]'' (1937) and ''[[The Patient in Room 18]]'' (1938). He was reteamed with Flynn and De Havilland in ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1938), playing [[Will Scarlett]], and ''[[Four's a Crowd]]'' (1938). He supported Flynn and Davis in ''[[The Sisters (1938 film)|The Sisters]]'' (1938).<ref>More than two [[decades]] after Flynn's death, biographer [[Charles Higham (biographer)|Charles Higham]] accused Flynn of having been a [[fascist]] sympathizer and [[Nazi]] [[spy]]. Knowles, who had served in [[World War II]] as a flying instructor in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]], came to Flynn's defense, writing ''Rebuttal for a Friend'' as an [[epilogue]] to Tony Thomas' ''Errol Flynn: The Spy Who Never Was'' (Citadel Press, 1990) {{ISBN|0-8065-1180-X}}.</ref>\n\nRepublic borrowed Knowles to play the lead in ''[[Storm Over Bengal]]'' (1938). <ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article143835960 |title=FILM FLASHES |newspaper=[[The Broadcaster]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=17 August 1939 |accessdate=3 October 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nAt Warners he had support roles in two B pictures, ''[[Heart of the North]]'' (1938) and ''[[Torchy Blane in Chinatown]]'' (1939), then he left the studio.\n\n===RKO===\nKnowles signed a contract at RKO, for whom he made ''[[Beauty for the Asking]]'' (1939) with Lucille Ball; ''[[Five Came Back]]'' (1939) also with Ball, directed by [[John Farrow]]; and ''[[The Spellbinder]]'' (1939).\n\nHe went to MGM for ''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939) and Fox for ''[[The Honeymoon's Over (film)|The Honeymoon's Over]]'' (1939) then went back to RKO for two more with John Farrow, ''[[Married and in Love]]'' (1940) and ''[[A Bill of Divorcement (1940 film)|A Bill of Divorcement]]'' (1940), then ''[[Anne of Windy Poplars (film)|Anne of Windy Poplars]]'' (1941), playing [[Gilbert Blythe]]. \n\nIn 1940 a limerick circulated about Knowles:  How pleasant to know Patric Knowles/ Who is the kindest of souls/ But being handsome and a British swell/ Nobody expects him to act very well/ Which is why he never gets good roles. <ref>Obituary: Patric Knowles Secondary panache\nBergan, Ronald. The Guardian 2 Jan 1996: 013. </ref>\n\n===World War Two===\nIn 1940 Knowles left Hollywood and travelled to Canada to enlist in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]]. He had hundreds of hours of flying experience but an eye ailment meant he became an instructor.<ref name=\"air\">Sergeant-Pilot Pat Knowles Pays Visit to Hollywood: Actor on Leave From Training Post With Canadian Air Force\nLos Angeles Times 19 Mar 1941: 3. </ref>\n\nAt Fox he was in ''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1941) for John Ford.<ref name=\"los\">Patric Knowles; British Actor\nLos Angeles Times 27 Dec 1995: VYB5. </ref>\n\n===Universal===\nKnowles went to Universal for a support part in ''[[The Wolf Man (1941 film)|The Wolf Man]]'' (1941). He went to Republic for ''[[Women in War]]'' (1941) then was top billed in Universal's ''[[The Strange Case of Doctor Rx]]'' (1942), and ''[[Mystery of Marie Roget]]'' (1942) with [[Maria Montez]]. \n\nHe supported [[Irene Dunne]] in ''[[Lady in a Jam]]'' (1942), [[Constance Bennett]] in ''[[Sin Town (1942 film)|Sin Town]]'' (1942), [[Abbott and Costello]] in ''[[Who Done It? (1942 film)|Who Done It?]]'' (1942) and ''[[Hit the Ice (film)|Hit the Ice]]'' (1943), [[Ilona Massey]] in ''[[Frankenstein Meets the Wolf Man]]'' (1943), [[Lane Sisters|Rosemary Lane]] in ''[[All by Myself (film)|All by Myself]]'' (1943), [[The Andrews Sisters]] in ''[[Always a Bridesmaid (1943 film)|Always a Bridesmaid]]'' (1943), [[Olsen and Johnson]] in ''[[Crazy House (1943 film)|Crazy House]]'' (1943), [[Donald O'Connor]] and Peggy Ryan in ''[[Chip Off the Old Block]]'' (1944) and ''[[This Is the Life (1944 film)|This Is the Life]]'' (1944), and [[Gloria Jean]] in ''[[Pardon My Rhythm]]'' (1944).<ref>Patric Knowles Has Schedule Of Farm Chores\nThe Washington Post 13 Dec 1942: L3. </ref>\n\nDuring this time he continued to serve as a flying instructor with the US Air Force.<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n===Paramount===\nKnowles went to Paramount where he supported [[Paulette Goddard]] in ''[[Kitty (1945 film)|Kitty]]'' (1945), [[Dorothy Lamour]] in ''[[Masquerade in Mexico]]'' (1945), [[Barbara Stanwyck]] in ''[[The Bride Wore Boots]]'' (1946), and [[Alan Ladd]] in ''[[O.S.S. (film)|O.S.S.]]'' (1946).<ref>obituaries: Patric Knowles: [FINAL Edition]\nShipman, David. The Independent30 Dec 1995: 14. </ref>\n\nHe went to Warners for ''[[Of Human Bondage (1946 film)|Of Human Bondage]]'' (1946) and Universal borrowed him to play [[Joan Fontaine]]'s leading man in the thriller ''[[Ivy (1947 film)|Ivy]]'' (1947)<ref>MISS DURBIN TO DO 'FOR LOVE OF MARY': Actress Is Named for Comedy by Universal-International-- 'Central Park' Postponed Buchman Buys \"Dark Page\"\nSpecial to THE NEW YORK TIMES.. New York Times (1923-Current file); New York, N.Y. [New York, N.Y]07 Dec 1946: 27</ref>. He went back to Paramount for ''[[Monsieur Beaucaire (1946 film)|Monsieur Beaucaire]]'' (1946) with [[Bob Hope]], ''[[Variety Girl]]'' (1947), ''[[Dream Girl (1948 film)|Dream Girl]]'' (1948), and ''[[Isn't It Romantic? (1948 film)|Isn't It Romantic?]]'' (1949).<ref>Patric Knowles Winds Up Tribute to St. Patrick in Jail\nLos Angeles Times 19 Mar 1947: 2. </ref>\n\nKnowles went to RKO for ''[[The Big Steal (1949 film)|The Big Steal]]'' (1949), and Fox for ''[[Three Came Home]]'' (1950), second billed, playing [[Claudette Colbert]]'s husband.<ref>Secondary panache\nKnowles, Patric. The Guardian 2 Jan 1996: 13. </ref>\n\n===Television===\nKnowles began appearing on TV shows such as ''[[The Bigelow Theatre]]'', ''[[Studio One in Hollywood]]'', ''[[Lights Out (1946 TV series)|Lights Out]]'', ''[[Hollywood Opening Night]]'', ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]'', ''[[The Revlon Mirror Theater]]'', ''[[The United States Steel Hour]]'', ''[[The Whistler (TV series)|The Whistler]]'', ''[[Studio 57]]'', ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'', and ''[[Jane Wyman Presents The Fireside Theatre]]''.\n\nHe still appeared in features such as ''[[Quebec (1951 film)|Quebec]]'' (1951), ''[[Mutiny (1952 film)|Mutiny]]'' (1952), ''[[Tarzan's Savage Fury]]'' (1952) (as the villain), ''[[Jamaica Run]]'' (1953), ''[[Flame of Calcutta]]'' (1953) for [[Sam Katzman]] (second billed to [[Denise Darcel]]), ''[[World for Ransom]]'' (1954), ''[[Khyber Patrol]]'' (1954) and ''[[No Man's Woman (film)|No Man's Woman]]'' (1955).<ref>Drama: Rooney Would Do Caddy Sleuth; Patric Knowles Plays Rebel in 'Quebec'\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 27 May 1950: 9. </ref>\n\nFrom the late 1950s Knowles became an almost exclusively television actor appearing in ''[[Star Stage]]'', ''[[The 20th Century-Fox Hour]]'', ''[[Tales of the 77th Bengal Lancers ]]'', ''[[Ethel Barrymore Theatre (TV series)|Ethel Barrymore Theater]]'', ''[[Lux Video Theatre]]'', ''[[Matinee Theatre]]'', ''[[Schlitz Playhouse]]'', ''[[The Millionaire (TV series)|The Millionaire]]'', ''[[Lux Playhouse]]'', ''[[Walt Disney's Wonderful World of Color]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Tightrope (TV series)|Tightrope]]'', ''[[Maverick (TV series)|Maverick]]'', ''[[The Barbara Stanwyck Show]]'', ''[[Klondike (TV series)|Klondike]]'', ''[[The Jim Backus Show]]'', ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', ''[[The Islanders (TV series)|The Islanders]]'', ''[[Checkmate (TV series)|Checkmate]]'', ''[[Peter Gunn]]'', ''[[Whispering Smith (TV series)|Whispering Smith]]'', ''[[Hawaiian Eye]]'', ''[[Have Gun - Will Travel]]'' (as [[Phileas Fogg]] in the episode \"Foggbound\"), ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[The Rogues (TV series)|The Rogues]]'', ''[[Mickey (TV series)|Mickey]]'', and ''[[Jericho (1966 TV series)|Jericho]]''.\n\nHe had a small role in the feature ''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957), ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (film)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1958) and ''[[Auntie Mame (film)|Auntie Mame]]'' (1958).\n\nHe wrote a novel, ''Even Steven'' (Vantage Press, 1960, [[ASIN]] B0006RMC2G).\n\n===Later Career===\nKnowles' later appearances included ''[[The Way West (film)|The Way West]]'' (1967) for director [[Andrew McLaglen]] ''[[Family Affair]]'', ''[[Garrison's Gorillas]]'', ''[[The Devil's Brigade (film)|The Devil's Brigade]]'' (1968) for McLaglen, ''[[In Enemy Country]]'' (1968), ''[[D.A.: Murder One]]'' (1969), ''[[Chisum]]'' (1970) with John Wayne for McLaglen as [[John Tunstall]], ''[[Getting Together]]'', ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]'', ''[[The Man (1972 film)|The Man]]'' (1972), ''[[Terror in the Wax Museum]]'' (1973) and ''[[Arnold (film)|Arnold]]'' (1973).\n\nKnowles was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n\n===Death===\nKnowles died from a brain hemorrhage at West Hills Hospital in [[West Hills, California]] on 23 December 1995, where he was cremated and his ashes distributed to family and friends.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mcpeak|first1=William|title=Patric Knowles Biography|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0461549/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|website=IMDB|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> At the point of his death, Knowles left behind his wife Gladys, his 2 children as well as four grandchildren.<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[Men of Tomorrow]]'' (1932)\n*''[[The Poisoned Diamond]]'' (1933) as Jack Dane\n*''[[Irish Hearts]]'' (1934) as Pip Fitzgerald\n*''[[Royal Cavalcade]]'' (1935) as Army Officer\n*''[[The Girl in the Crowd]]'' (1935) as Tom Burrows\n*''[[The Student's Romance]]'' (1935) as Max Brandt\n*''[[Honours Easy]]'' (1935) as Harry Markham\n*''[[Abdul the Damned]]'' (1935) as Omar - Hilmi's Attache\n*''[[The Guv'nor (film)|The Guv'nor]]'' (1935) as Paul\n*''[[Wedding Group]]'' (1936) as Robert Smith\n*''[[Two's Company (film)|Two's Company]]'' (1936) as Lord Jerry Wendower\n*''[[Fair Exchange (film)|Fair Exchange]]'' (1936) as Tony Meredith\n*''[[The Brown Wallet]]'' (1936) as John Gillespie\n*''[[Crown v. Stevens]]'' (1936) as Chris Jensen\n*''[[Give Me Your Heart (film)|Give Me Your Heart]]'' (1936) as Robert Melford\n*''[[The Charge of the Light Brigade (1936 film)|The Charge of the Light Brigade]]'' (1936) as Captain Perry Vickers\n*''[[Irish for Luck]]'' (1936) as Terry O'Ryan\n*''[[It's Love I'm After]]'' (1937) as Henry Grant\n*''[[Expensive Husbands]]'' (1937) as Prince Rupert Heinrich Franz Von Rentzau\n*''[[The Patient in Room 18 (film)|The Patient in Room 18]]'' (1938) as Lance O'Leary\n*''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1938) as Will Scarlett\n*''[[Four's a Crowd]]'' (1938) as Patterson Buckley\n*''[[The Sisters (1938 film)|The Sisters]]'' (1938) as Norman French\n*''[[Storm Over Bengal]]'' (1938) as Capt. Jeffrey Allison\n*''[[Heart of the North]]'' (1938) as Corporal Jim Montgomery\n*''[[Torchy Blane in Chinatown]]'' (1939) as Captain Condon\n*''[[Beauty for the Asking]]'' (1939) as Denny Williams\n*''[[Five Came Back]]'' (1939) as Judson Ellis\n*''[[The Spellbinder]]'' (1939) as Tom Dixon\n*''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939) as Dudley Horn\n*''[[The Honeymoon's Over (film)|The Honeymoon's Over]]'' (1939) as Pat Shields\n*''[[Married and in Love]]''(1940) as Paul Wilding\n*''[[A Bill of Divorcement (1940 film)|A Bill of Divorcement]]'' (1940) as John Storm\n*''[[Women in War]]'' (1940) as Lt. Larry Hall\n*''[[Anne of Windy Poplars (film)|Anne of Windy Poplars]]'' (1940) as Gilbert Blythe\n*''[[How Green Was My Valley (film)|How Green Was My Valley]]'' (1941) as Ivor\n*''[[The Wolf Man (1941 film)|The Wolf Man]]'' (1941) as Frank Andrews\n*''[[The Strange Case of Doctor Rx]]'' (1942) as Jerry Church\n*''[[The Mystery of Marie Roget (film)|The Mystery of Marie Roget]]'' (1942) as Dr. Paul Dupin\n*''[[Lady in a Jam]]'' (1942) as Doctor Enright\n*''[[Sin Town (1942 film)|Sin Town]]'' (1942) as Wade Crowell\n*''[[Who Done It? (1942 film)|Who Done It?]]'' (1942) as Jimmy Turner\n*''[[Forever and a Day (1943 film)|Forever and a Day]]'' (1943) as Trimble-Pomfret Son\n*''[[Frankenstein Meets the Wolf Man]]'' (1943) as Dr. Mannering\n*''[[Hit the Ice (film)|Hit the Ice]]'' (1943) as Dr. Bill Elliot (Credits) / Dr. William 'Bill' Burns (in Film)\n*''All by Myself'' (1943) as Dr. Bill Perry\n*''[[Always a Bridesmaid (1943 film)|Always a Bridesmaid]]'' (1943) as Tony Warren\n*''[[Crazy House (1943 film)|Crazy House]]'' (1943) as Edmund 'Mac' MacLean\n*''[[Chip Off the Old Block]]'' (1944) as Commander Judd Corrigan\n*''[[This Is the Life (1944 film)|This Is the Life]]'' (1944) as Maj. Hilary Jarret\n*''[[Pardon My Rhythm]]'' (1944) as Tony Page\n*''[[Kitty (1945 film)|Kitty]]'' (1945) as Brett Harwood Earl of Carstairs\n*''[[Masquerade in Mexico]]'' (1945) as Thomas Grant\n*''[[The Bride Wore Boots]]'' (1946) as Lance Gale\n*''[[O.S.S. (film)|O.S.S.]]'' (1946) as Cmdr. Brady\n*''[[Of Human Bondage (1946 film)|Of Human Bondage]]'' (1946) as Harry Griffiths\n*''[[Monsieur Beaucaire (1946 film)|Monsieur Beaucaire]]'' (1946) as Duc le Chandre\n*''[[Ivy (1947 film)|Ivy]]'' (1947) as Roger Gretorex\n*''[[Variety Girl]]'' (1947) as Patric KInowles\n*''[[Dream Girl (1948 film)|Dream Girl]]'' (1948) as Jim Lucas\n*''[[Isn't It Romantic? (1948 film)|Isn't It Romantic?]]'' (1948) as Richard 'Rick' Brannon\n*''[[The Big Steal]]'' (1949) as Jim Fiske\n*''[[Three Came Home]]'' (1950) as Harry Keith\n*''[[Quebec (1951 film)|Quebec]]'' (1951) as Charles Douglas\n*''[[Mutiny (1952 film)|Mutiny]]'' (1952) as Capt. Ben Waldridge\n*''[[Tarzan's Savage Fury]]'' (1952) as Edwards, English Traitor\n*''[[Jamaica Run]]'' (1953) as William Montague\n*''[[Flame of Calcutta]]'' (1953) as Capt. Keith Lambert\n*''[[World for Ransom]]'' (1954) as Julian March\n*''[[Khyber Patrol]]'' (1954) as Lt. George Kennedy\n*''[[No Man's Woman (film)|No Man's Woman]]'' (1955) as Wayne Vincent\n*''[[Band of Angels]]'' (1957) as Charles de Marigny\n*''[[From the Earth to the Moon (film)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1958) as Josef Cartier\n*''[[Auntie Mame (film)|Auntie Mame]]'' (1958) as Lindsay Woolsey\n*''[[The Way West (film)|The Way West]]'' (1967) as Captain Grant\n*''[[The Devil's Brigade (film)|The Devil's Brigade]]'' (1968) as Adm. Lord Mountbatten\n*''[[In Enemy Country]]'' (1968) as General Lloyd-Griffis\n*''[[Chisum]]'' (1970) as Henry Tunstall\n*''[[The Man (1972 film)|The Man]]'' (1972) as South African Consul\n*''[[Terror in the Wax Museum]]'' (1973) as Mr. Southcott\n*''[[Arnold (film)|Arnold]]'' (1973) as Douglas Whitehead (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Alistair |first= Rupert |title= The Name Below the Title : 65 Classic Movie Character Actors from Hollywood's Golden Age |chapter= Patric Knowles |pages= 137-139 |date= 2018 |edition= First |type= softcover |publisher= Independently published |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-7200-3837-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|0461549}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knowles, Patric}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Horsforth]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patric_Knowles"}
{"title_page": "Federico Quer\u00edn", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Federico Quer\u00edn\n| full_name      = Federico Luis Quer\u00edn\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|9|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Federico Luis Quer\u00edn''' (born 10 September 1966) is an Argentine [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/qu/federico-querin-1.html |title=Federico Quer\u00edn Olympic Results |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Querin, Federico}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Federico Quer\u00edn\n| full_name      = Federico Luis Quer\u00edn\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|9|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Federico Luis Quer\u00edn''' (born 10 September 1966) is an Argentine [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/qu/federico-querin-1.html |title=Federico Quer\u00edn Olympic Results |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Querin, Federico}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in rowing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federico_Quer%C3%ADn"}
{"title_page": "Pat Sharp", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n| name        = Pat Sharp\n| image       = PatSharp.jpg\n| caption     = Pat Sharp at Capital FM\n| birth_name  = Patrick Sharpin\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|10|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stanmore]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| country     = United Kingdom\n| prevshow    = [[BBC Radio 1]], [[Capital London|Capital FM]], [[Heart London|Heart 106.2]]\n| residence   = [[Bushey]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n}}\n'''Pat Sharp''' (born Patrick Sharpin; 25 October 1961)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpce.com/sharp.shtml|title=Pat Sharp (Agent's biography)|publisher=MPC Entertainment|accessdate=13 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927152327/http://www.mpce.com/sharp.shtml|archivedate=27 September 2007}}</ref> is an English [[radio presenter|radio]], [[television presenter]] and [[disc jockey|DJ]]. In the UK, he is known mainly for his work on the children's [[ITV (TV Network)|ITV]] programme ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'', and his extensive radio career. In mainland Europe, he was better known in the 1980s as one of the [[Sky 1|Sky Channel]]'s [[VJ (media personality)|VJs]] and for presenting [[Coca-Cola]] Eurochart Top 50 and [[Nescaf\u00e9]] UK Top 50.\n\n==Radio work==\nSharp worked as a presenter at [[BBC Radio 1]], mixing holiday cover for other radio presenters with a regular early Sunday morning slot and a number of television appearances hosting [[BBC1]]'s ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/pat_sharp.htm|title=People: Pat Sharp|publisher=Radio Rewind|accessdate=12 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626072316/http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/pat_sharp.htm|archivedate=26 June 2007}}</ref> He deputised for [[David Jensen]] on ''[[The Network Chart Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jinglemad.com/e107_plugins/forum/forum_viewtopic.php?3630|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on The Network Chart Show|publisher=jinglemad.com|accessdate=25 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226130206/http://www.jinglemad.com/e107_plugins/forum/forum_viewtopic.php?3630|archivedate=26 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he became a DJ for [[Radio Mercury]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercuryfm.co.uk/Article.asp?id=1533463|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on Radio Mercury|publisher=Mercury FM|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> and has also worked for the [[British Forces Broadcasting Service]]. For 10 years, starting in 1987, Sharp was a DJ on [[Capital London|Capital FM]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heartcambridge.co.uk/Article.asp?id=408331|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on Capital Radio for ten years!|publisher=Heart Cambridge|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> followed by another 11 years at Heart, both in London and [[Cambridge]].\n\nIn the late-1980s, Sharp teamed up with Mick Brown as the duo [[Pat and Mick]], to release the charity singles \"[[Let's All Chant]]\" and \"I Haven't Stopped Dancing Yet\". Both songs made the Top 20 of the UK singles chart. The duo released five hit singles making the Top 75, raising more than a million pounds for charity.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://weekenderinteractive.butlinsonline.co.uk/features/we-love-the-80s/pat-sharp | title = Reference to Pat & Mick raising over a million pounds for charity | publisher = Butlins | accessdate = 25 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he was voted as having the worst haircut (winning this accolade more than once) at the [[Smash Hits Poll Winners Party|''Smash Hits'' Poll Winners Party]] awards, where he was also in the top three DJs. He was awarded the [[Radio Academy Awards|Sony Award]] in 1992 for best DJ.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.100centuryfm.com/Article.asp?id=77431 | title = Pat Sharp | publisher = [[Century FM]] | accessdate = 12 June 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928165958/http://www.100centuryfm.com/Article.asp?id=77431 | archivedate = 28 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1997 and 2004, Sharp presented [[Heart London|Heart 106.2]]'s weekday morning ''Time Tunnel'' show. Following this, Sharp was a presenter on the [[Century Network|Century FM]] group of stations.  In December 2010, Sharp joined [[Smooth Radio]] to host Weekend Breakfast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2011/01/sharp-keeps-it-smooth/ |title=Pat Sharp keeps it Smooth |work=Radio Today |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> He was officially appointed as the station's Weekend Breakfast presenter in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.gmgradio.com/news/story/pat-sharp-to-join-smooth-radio-lineup/168|title= Pat Sharp to Join Smooth Radio Line-up|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= GMG Radio|date= 12 January 2011|accessdate= 27 March 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111219025421/http://www.gmgradio.com/news/story/pat-sharp-to-join-smooth-radio-lineup/168|archivedate= 19 December 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2013 Sharp became the station's weekday afternoon presenter after a major overhaul of the Smooth schedule, replacing [[Carlos (DJ)|Carlos]] who moved to weeknights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/01/pat-sharp-gets-daily-show-on-smooth-radio/ |title=Pat Sharp gets daily show on Smooth Radio|publisher= Radio Today |date= 7 January 2013|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSmooth Radio was acquired by Global Radio in 2013. Following a studio and business move to Global's headquarters in [[Leicester Square]], Pat Sharp and [[David Jensen]] were then dropped from the schedules on 19 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/12/kid-jensen-pat-sharp-leave-smooth-radio/ |title=Pat Sharp leaves Smooth |work=Radio Today |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> Sharp started broadcasting on the Breeze network New Year's Eve 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://portsmouth.thebreeze.com/on-air/pat-sharp/ |title=Pat Sharp Bio=Breeze |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140101092123/http://portsmouth.thebreeze.com/on-air/pat-sharp/ |archivedate=1 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He appears regularly on [[Sam FM (South Coast)|Sam FM]] south coast.\n\nIn 2018, Sharp covered the mid-morning show on Southampton-based Hampshire Hit Radio for a week. He\u2019s also appeared covering on Guildford-based Eagle Radio in recent years.\n\nSharp also fronts ''All The Hits'', a weekly syndicated radio show produced by [[Blue Revolution]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bluerevolution.com/all-the-hits|title=All The Hits|date=24 December 2012|website=Blue Revolution}}</ref>, which is broadcast on various stations around the world{{cn|date=January 2019}}.\n\nFrom February 2019, Sharp is presenting a radio show on [[Greatest Hits Radio]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/02/pat-sharp-joins-greatest-hits-radio-weekends/|title=Pat Sharp joins Greatest Hits Radio weekends|date=2019-02-19|website=Radio Today}}</ref>, as well as P8 Pop in Norway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2017/12/pat-sharp-joins-norwegian-radio-station-p8/|title=Pat Sharp joins Norwegian radio station P8|date=2017-12-07|website=Radio Today}}</ref>\n\n==Television work==\nSharp intermittently presented episodes of the music programme ''Top of the Pops'', including being one of the many presenters on the last programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/5228858.stm |title=Top of the Pops bids fond goodbye |date=31 July 2006 |accessdate=12 June 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> In 1987\u201388, he presented [[ITV Network|ITV]] show ''[[The Roxy (TV series)|The Roxy]]''. However, Sharp is best known on television for several children's television programmes aired on [[CITV]]. Most notable of these is ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'', a popular children's television programme running from 1989\u201399, Produced by [[Scottish Television]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0457240|title=\"Fun House\" (1990)|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=12 June 2007 }}</ref> which he presented along with [[Melanie and Martina Grant]]. Sharp presented alongside producer Matt Penn. Sharp was also one of the presenters of Saturday morning show ''[[What's Up Doc? (TV series)|What's Up Doc?]]'' (STV, 1992\u201394) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paulmorris.co.uk/satkids/whatsupdoc.htm | title = What's Up Doc details|publisher=paulmorris.co.uk|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> and presented phone-in quiz show ''Hang On!'' (LWT for ITV) in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Hang_On!|title=Hang On! |publisher=UK Gameshows |accessdate=12 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSharp appeared as a guest in many other television shows, including several episodes of ''[[You Bet!]]'', ''[[Surprise Surprise (TV series)|Surprise Surprise]]'', ''[[Celebrity Squares]]'' and [[The Weakest Link]]. In the [[2000s in television|2000s]], Sharp regularly appears on music TV channels presenting continuity in programmes looking back at 80s and 90s music hits, appearing on channels including [[The Hits]], [[NOW 80s]],  [[NOW 90s]] and others. He also appeared in episodes three and seven of the 24th series and episode four of the 26th series of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wh68x |title=Programmes \"Never Mind The Buzzcocks\"|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/leisure/tv/8632881.Review__Never_Mind_The_Buzzcocks__BBC2/?ref=rss|title=Review: Never Mind The Buzzcocks|author=Moseley, A|work=Lancashire Telegraph|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he participated in [[Channel 4]] sports reality show ''[[The Games (UK TV series)|The Games]]'' finishing last out of five contestants,<ref name=\"q103\">{{cite web|url=http://www.q103.co.uk/Article.asp?id=408331&spid=16160 |title=60 seconds with Pat Sharp |publisher=[[Heart Cambridge|Q103]] |accessdate=13 June 2007 }}</ref> but was proclaimed the People's Hero. Further [[Reality television|reality TV]] involvement came on 3 June 2006 when he appeared for a sketch on [[ITV2]]'s ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|X Factor]]'' spin-off show ''[[The X Factor: Battle of the Stars|X-Tra Factor: Battle Of The Stars]]''. He appeared briefly on 23 June 2007 on a ''[[Big Brother's Big Mouth]]'' phone-in. However he did appear on the show in person as a guest on 12 July 2007, then appeared four years later on ''[[Big Brother's Bit on the Side]]'' on 27 October 2011.\n\nIn May 2010, Sharp appeared on ''[[Come Dine with Me]]'' with [[Jenny Powell]], [[Michael Barrymore]] and [[Anthea Redfern]]. He also appeared on [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' twice in the same series in 2010, along with [[BBC One]]'s ''[[The One Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nIn November 2011, Sharp was a contestant on the [[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 11)|eleventh series]] of the [[ITV Network|ITV]] [[reality television]] show ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]''\n\nIn 2017 Sharp played a version of himself in online mockumentary Getting Back with [[Dave Benson Phillips]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLpNIvRaysNrKM2d69-Ovq5syzq6yURCZp|title=EPISODES - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettingbackdbp.com/credits/|title=Credits|website=Getting Back with Dave Benson Phillips|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/online/getting_back_with_dave_benson_phillips/episodes/|title=Getting Back With Dave Benson Phillips episode guide - British Comedy Guide|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1498031|name=Pat Sharp}}\n*[https://planetradio.co.uk/greatest-hits/shows/pat-sharp/ Pat Sharp on Greatest Hits Radio]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KlR0laKVGuI Pat Sharp presenting Coca-Cola Eurochart Top 50 in 1988 (programme open)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wl6abg9f8G0 Pat Sharp presenting Coca-Cola Eurochart Top 50 in 1988 (programme close)]\n*[http://www.denofgeek.com/television/13608/pat_sharp_interview.html Interview with Pat Sharp]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharp, Pat}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:English radio DJs]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:People educated at Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 1 presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n| name        = Pat Sharp\n| image       = PatSharp.jpg\n| caption     = Pat Sharp at Capital FM\n| birth_name  = Patrick Sharpin\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|10|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stanmore]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| country     = United Kingdom\n| prevshow    = [[BBC Radio 1]], [[Capital London|Capital FM]], [[Heart London|Heart 106.2]]\n| residence   = [[Bushey]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n}}\n'''Pat Sharp''' (born Patrick Sharpin; 25 October 1961)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpce.com/sharp.shtml|title=Pat Sharp (Agent's biography)|publisher=MPC Entertainment|accessdate=13 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927152327/http://www.mpce.com/sharp.shtml|archivedate=27 September 2007}}</ref> is an English [[radio presenter|radio]], [[television presenter]] and [[disc jockey|DJ]]. In the UK, he is known mainly for his work on the children's [[ITV (TV Network)|ITV]] programme ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'', and his extensive radio career. In mainland Europe, he was better known in the 1980s as one of the [[Sky 1|Sky Channel]]'s [[VJ (media personality)|VJs]] and for presenting [[Coca-Cola]] Eurochart Top 50 and [[Nescaf\u00e9]] UK Top 50.\n\n==Radio work==\nSharp worked as a presenter at [[BBC Radio 1]], mixing holiday cover for other radio presenters with a regular early Sunday morning slot and a number of television appearances hosting [[BBC1]]'s ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/pat_sharp.htm|title=People: Pat Sharp|publisher=Radio Rewind|accessdate=12 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626072316/http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/pat_sharp.htm|archivedate=26 June 2007}}</ref> He deputised for [[David Jensen]] on ''[[The Network Chart Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jinglemad.com/e107_plugins/forum/forum_viewtopic.php?3630|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on The Network Chart Show|publisher=jinglemad.com|accessdate=25 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226130206/http://www.jinglemad.com/e107_plugins/forum/forum_viewtopic.php?3630|archivedate=26 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he became a DJ for [[Radio Mercury]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercuryfm.co.uk/Article.asp?id=1533463|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on Radio Mercury|publisher=Mercury FM|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> and has also worked for the [[British Forces Broadcasting Service]]. For 10 years, starting in 1987, Sharp was a DJ on [[Capital London|Capital FM]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heartcambridge.co.uk/Article.asp?id=408331|title=Reference to Pat Sharp on Capital Radio for ten years!|publisher=Heart Cambridge|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> followed by another 11 years at Heart, both in London and [[Cambridge]].\n\nIn the late-1980s, Sharp teamed up with Mick Brown as the duo [[Pat and Mick]], to release the charity singles \"[[Let's All Chant]]\" and \"I Haven't Stopped Dancing Yet\". Both songs made the Top 20 of the UK singles chart. The duo released five hit singles making the Top 75, raising more than a million pounds for charity.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://weekenderinteractive.butlinsonline.co.uk/features/we-love-the-80s/pat-sharp | title = Reference to Pat & Mick raising over a million pounds for charity | publisher = Butlins | accessdate = 25 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he was voted as having the worst haircut (winning this accolade more than once) at the [[Smash Hits Poll Winners Party|''Smash Hits'' Poll Winners Party]] awards, where he was also in the top three DJs. He was awarded the [[Radio Academy Awards|Sony Award]] in 1992 for best DJ.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.100centuryfm.com/Article.asp?id=77431 | title = Pat Sharp | publisher = [[Century FM]] | accessdate = 12 June 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928165958/http://www.100centuryfm.com/Article.asp?id=77431 | archivedate = 28 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1997 and 2004, Sharp presented [[Heart London|Heart 106.2]]'s weekday morning ''Time Tunnel'' show. Following this, Sharp was a presenter on the [[Century Network|Century FM]] group of stations.  In December 2010, Sharp joined [[Smooth Radio]] to host Weekend Breakfast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2011/01/sharp-keeps-it-smooth/ |title=Pat Sharp keeps it Smooth |work=Radio Today |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> He was officially appointed as the station's Weekend Breakfast presenter in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.gmgradio.com/news/story/pat-sharp-to-join-smooth-radio-lineup/168|title= Pat Sharp to Join Smooth Radio Line-up|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= GMG Radio|date= 12 January 2011|accessdate= 27 March 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111219025421/http://www.gmgradio.com/news/story/pat-sharp-to-join-smooth-radio-lineup/168|archivedate= 19 December 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2013 Sharp became the station's weekday afternoon presenter after a major overhaul of the Smooth schedule, replacing [[Carlos (DJ)|Carlos]] who moved to weeknights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/01/pat-sharp-gets-daily-show-on-smooth-radio/ |title=Pat Sharp gets daily show on Smooth Radio|publisher= Radio Today |date= 7 January 2013|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSmooth Radio was acquired by Global Radio in 2013. Following a studio and business move to Global's headquarters in [[Leicester Square]], Pat Sharp and [[David Jensen]] were then dropped from the schedules on 19 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/12/kid-jensen-pat-sharp-leave-smooth-radio/ |title=Pat Sharp leaves Smooth |work=Radio Today |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> Sharp started broadcasting on the Breeze network New Year's Eve 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://portsmouth.thebreeze.com/on-air/pat-sharp/ |title=Pat Sharp Bio=Breeze |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140101092123/http://portsmouth.thebreeze.com/on-air/pat-sharp/ |archivedate=1 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He appears regularly on [[Sam FM (South Coast)|Sam FM]] south coast.\n\nIn 2018, Sharp covered the mid-morning show on Southampton-based Hampshire Hit Radio for a week. He\u2019s also appeared covering on Guildford-based Eagle Radio in recent years.\n\nSharp also fronts ''All The Hits'', a weekly syndicated radio show produced by [[Blue Revolution]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bluerevolution.com/all-the-hits|title=All The Hits|date=24 December 2012|website=Blue Revolution}}</ref>, which is broadcast on various stations around the world{{cn|date=January 2019}}.\n\nFrom February 2019, Sharp is presenting a radio show on [[Greatest Hits Radio]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/02/pat-sharp-joins-greatest-hits-radio-weekends/|title=Pat Sharp joins Greatest Hits Radio weekends|date=2019-02-19|website=Radio Today}}</ref>, as well as P8 Pop in Norway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2017/12/pat-sharp-joins-norwegian-radio-station-p8/|title=Pat Sharp joins Norwegian radio station P8|date=2017-12-07|website=Radio Today}}</ref>.\n\n==Television work==\nSharp intermittently presented episodes of the music programme ''Top of the Pops'', including being one of the many presenters on the last programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/5228858.stm |title=Top of the Pops bids fond goodbye |date=31 July 2006 |accessdate=12 June 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> In 1987\u201388, he presented [[ITV Network|ITV]] show ''[[The Roxy (TV series)|The Roxy]]''. However, Sharp is best known on television for several children's television programmes aired on [[CITV]]. Most notable of these is ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'', a popular children's television programme running from 1989\u201399, Produced by [[Scottish Television]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0457240|title=\"Fun House\" (1990)|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=12 June 2007 }}</ref> which he presented along with [[Melanie and Martina Grant]]. Sharp presented alongside producer Matt Penn. Sharp was also one of the presenters of Saturday morning show ''[[What's Up Doc? (TV series)|What's Up Doc?]]'' (STV, 1992\u201394) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paulmorris.co.uk/satkids/whatsupdoc.htm | title = What's Up Doc details|publisher=paulmorris.co.uk|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> and presented phone-in quiz show ''Hang On!'' (LWT for ITV) in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Hang_On!|title=Hang On! |publisher=UK Gameshows |accessdate=12 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSharp appeared as a guest in many other television shows, including several episodes of ''[[You Bet!]]'', ''[[Surprise Surprise (TV series)|Surprise Surprise]]'', ''[[Celebrity Squares]]'' and [[The Weakest Link]]. In the [[2000s in television|2000s]], Sharp regularly appears on music TV channels presenting continuity in programmes looking back at 80s and 90s music hits, appearing on channels including [[The Hits]], [[NOW 80s]],  [[NOW 90s]] and others. He also appeared in episodes three and seven of the 24th series and episode four of the 26th series of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wh68x |title=Programmes \"Never Mind The Buzzcocks\"|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/leisure/tv/8632881.Review__Never_Mind_The_Buzzcocks__BBC2/?ref=rss|title=Review: Never Mind The Buzzcocks|author=Moseley, A|work=Lancashire Telegraph|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he participated in [[Channel 4]] sports reality show ''[[The Games (UK TV series)|The Games]]'' finishing last out of five contestants,<ref name=\"q103\">{{cite web|url=http://www.q103.co.uk/Article.asp?id=408331&spid=16160 |title=60 seconds with Pat Sharp |publisher=[[Heart Cambridge|Q103]] |accessdate=13 June 2007 }}</ref> but was proclaimed the People's Hero. Further [[Reality television|reality TV]] involvement came on 3 June 2006 when he appeared for a sketch on [[ITV2]]'s ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|X Factor]]'' spin-off show ''[[The X Factor: Battle of the Stars|X-Tra Factor: Battle Of The Stars]]''. He appeared briefly on 23 June 2007 on a ''[[Big Brother's Big Mouth]]'' phone-in. However he did appear on the show in person as a guest on 12 July 2007, then appeared four years later on ''[[Big Brother's Bit on the Side]]'' on 27 October 2011.\n\nIn May 2010, Sharp appeared on ''[[Come Dine with Me]]'' with [[Jenny Powell]], [[Michael Barrymore]] and [[Anthea Redfern]]. He also appeared on [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' twice in the same series in 2010, along with [[BBC One]]'s ''[[The One Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nIn November 2011, Sharp was a contestant on the [[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 11)|eleventh series]] of the [[ITV Network|ITV]] [[reality television]] show ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]''\n\nIn 2017 Sharp played a version of himself in online mockumentary Getting Back with [[Dave Benson Phillips]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLpNIvRaysNrKM2d69-Ovq5syzq6yURCZp|title=EPISODES - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettingbackdbp.com/credits/|title=Credits|website=Getting Back with Dave Benson Phillips|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/online/getting_back_with_dave_benson_phillips/episodes/|title=Getting Back With Dave Benson Phillips episode guide - British Comedy Guide|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1498031|name=Pat Sharp}}\n*[https://planetradio.co.uk/greatest-hits/shows/pat-sharp/ Pat Sharp on Greatest Hits Radio]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KlR0laKVGuI Pat Sharp presenting Coca-Cola Eurochart Top 50 in 1988 (programme open)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wl6abg9f8G0 Pat Sharp presenting Coca-Cola Eurochart Top 50 in 1988 (programme close)]\n*[http://www.denofgeek.com/television/13608/pat_sharp_interview.html Interview with Pat Sharp]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharp, Pat}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:English radio DJs]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:People educated at Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 1 presenters]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pat_Sharp"}
{"title_page": "Lego Masters (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Lego Masters\n| image                    = Lego Masters Us Logo.png\n| image_size               = \n| creator                  = \n| presenter                = [[Will Arnett]]\n| starring                 = \n| judges                   = Amy Corbett<br>Jamie Berard\n| opentheme                = \n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!-- increment when new season begins -->\n| num_episodes             = 9<!-- increment when new episode airs -->\n| executive_producer       = Anthony Dominici<br>Karen Smith<br>Steph Harris<br>Sharon Levy<br>DJ Nurre<br>Michael Heyerman<br>[[Brad Pitt]]<br>[[Dede Gardner]]<br>[[Jeremy Kleiner]]<br>Christina Oh<br>Jill Wilfert<br>Robert May<br>[[Will Arnett]]\n| location                 = \n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = [[Endemol Shine North America]]<br>Tuesday's Child<br>[[Plan B Entertainment]]<br>[[The Lego Group]]<br>Electric Avenue\n| network                  = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|2|5}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website                  = https://www.fox.com/lego-masters/\n}}\n'''''Lego Masters''''' is an American reality competition television series based on the British series [[Lego Masters (British TV series)|of the same name]] in which teams compete to build the best [[Lego|Lego]] project. It is hosted and executive produced by [[Will Arnett]].<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/will-arnett-lego-masters-host-fox-1203388544/|title=Will Arnett to Host 'Lego Masters' Competition Series on Fox|last=Thorne|first=Will|date=2019-10-30|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> The series premiered on February 5, 2020 on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9615014/|title=Lego Masters|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== Format ==\nThe series follows teams consisting of two Lego-building competitors, tasked with building creations out of Lego pieces based on a given theme within a given time period. After the allotted time to build, the teams demonstrate their creations to host [[Will Arnett]] and two expert judges from the [[Lego Group]]: Amy Corbett, a senior design manager at Lego, and Jamie Berard, who oversees the  [[Lego Creator]] Expert and [[Lego Architecture]] lines at Lego.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/48353/interview-with-lego-masters-judges-brick-master-amy-and-brick-master-jamie |title=Interview with LEGO Masters judges, Brick Master Amy and Brick Master Jamie |date=14 January 2020 |website=brickset.com |access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> The experts name the winning build and as well as the bottom two teams, explaining why teams were selected in this fashion. They then announce the losing team, who, save for the first week, is eliminated from the competition. In addition to this judging, Amy and Jamie provide suggestions to the teams mid-way through the build.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lego-masters-competition-series-a-go-at-fox-1225082|title='Lego Masters' Competition Series Produced by Brad Pitt a Go at Fox (Exclusive)|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=2019-07-18|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The first episode awarded the team with the best design judged by the experts with the Golden Brick, which they can use on any other challenge, after the build period but before the judging, to automatically advance to the next challenge if they do not feel confident about their work. Once they turn in the Golden Brick for immunity, it is then made available as the reward for a future challenge. The season will culminate in a finale, in which top teams compete for a $100,000, a Lego Masters trophy, and the title of Lego Master.<ref name=\"Variety\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/fox-builds-its-second-show-around-a-popular-brand-with-lego-masters/|title= Fox Builds Its Second Show Around a Popular Brand With Lego Masters and Eli Spiro is the best\n|work=Adweek}}</ref>\n\n==Elimination table==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Place\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Relation\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"9\"| Episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 1\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 2\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 3\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 4\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 5\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 6\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 7\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 8\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40px\"| 9\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | TBD\n| Mark & Boone\n| Friends\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:gold;\"| WIN\n| style=\"background:gold;\"| WIN\n| style=\"background:gold;\"| WIN<sup>\u2020</sup>\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:yellowgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:gold;\"| WIN\n|- \n| Sam & Jessica\n| Friends\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"| RISK\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"| RISK\n| style=\"background:forestgreen;\"| HIGH\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:lightgreen;\"| SAFE\n| style=\"background:forestgreen;\"| HIGH\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"| RISK\n| style=\"b