{"title_page": "Bonaventure Plantation", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Bonaventure Plantation\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = File:Bonaventure_Plantation_1779.png\n| caption             = An October 1779 map by Antoine O'Connor, chief engineer of French Admiral-General [[Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_hxaDPBdd8kC&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=antoine+o%27connor+engineer&source=bl&ots=DEXddG3f7G&sig=ACfU3U3SZmwnDL6gKWUU2RT1yGmXaWjOpw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi-3PGIh-voAhWUUs0KHcLzDdcQ6AEwAHoECAUQKQ#v=onepage&q=antoine%20o'connor%20engineer&f=false ''Engineers of Independence: A Documentary History of the Army Engineers in the American Revolution, 1775-1783'', Paul K. Walker; The Minerva Group, 2002]</ref> showing the location of Bonaventure\n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[colonial America|Colonial]] [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], \n| address             = \n| client              = \n| owner               = \u2022 John Mullryne (original; 1762)<br />\u2022 Josiah Tattnall, Sr. (''unknown''\u20131782)<br />\u2022 [[John Habersham]] (1782\u20131788)<br />\u2022 [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1788\u20131804)<br />\u2022 Edward Tattnall, Harriet Tattnall & [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall III]] (1817\u20131819)<br />\u2022 Edward Tattnall & Josiah Tattnall III (1819\u20131832)<br />\u2022 Josiah Tattnall III (1832\u20131846)<br />\u2022 Peter Wiltberger (1846\u20131853)<br >\u2022 William Wiltberger (1853\u20131907)\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32|2|33|N|81|2|35|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1762, after 1771\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     =\n| destruction_date    = 1771 (fire), 1800 (fire)\n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''Bonaventure Plantation''' was a [[plantation]] in [[colonial America|colonial]] [[Savannah, Georgia]], on land now occupied by Greenwich Cemetery and [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]. The site was {{convert|600|acre|km2}}, including a [[plantation house]] and private cemetery, located on the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], about {{convert|3.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} east of the Savannah Colony.\n\n==History==\nThe plantation was founded in 1762<ref name=archive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov</ref> by Colonel John Mullryne (d. January 6, 1786, in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]]),<ref name=weaver>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UVba5QR1YnkC&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=john+mullryne+1786&source=bl&ots=mxM_Oz0Z4K&sig=ACfU3U1yJ79kxRg78hsrsGypa-jo0sKgZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqhNT-zuvoAhWDAp0JHeCVBpAQ6AEwBnoECAsQQA#v=onepage&q=john%20mullryne%201786&f=false ''Tombstones I Have Known'', Lamar Weaver, Charaman M. Campbell, 2001]</ref> who had emigrated from England to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], initially, before moving north to Savannah.<ref name=jones>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1fExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA540&lpg=PA540&dq=colonel+john+mulryne+savannah&source=bl&ots=Mfalti1wc_&sig=ACfU3U00vP0eRMZLT6FGp_T_8j78kdIjVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj188Pv1-joAhVBXc0KHQ1iCD4Q6AEwBHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=colonel%20john%20mulryne%20savannah&f=false ''History of Savannah, Ga: From Its Settlement to the Close of the Eighteenth Century''], Charles Colcock Jones (D. Mason & Company, 1890)</ref> The property fell into the possession of the Tattnall family \u2014 Josiah Tattnall, Sr. (b. February 8, 1740),<ref name=huger>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/27575354?seq=3#metadata_info_tab_contents ''The South Carolina Historical and Genealogical Magazine'', Vol. 14, No. 1 (Jan., 1913), pp. 3-19 (17 pages)], D. E. Huger Smith</ref>  of Charleston, had married Mary (b. October 19, 1741),<ref name=huger/> the youngest daughter of John and Claudia Mullryne.<ref name=jones/> [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7958532/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Sr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref> was born at the plantation, a year after his brother, John Mullryne Tattnall.<ref name=archive/>\n\nPer Claudia Mullryne's [[will and testament]], dated December 10, 1781, her daughter Catharine Moore, a widow, was left \"the mansion house called Bonaventure where she now resides.\" Upon Catharine's death, John and Claudia's grandson, John Mullryne Tattnall, would inherit the mansion, as well as \"six hundred acres of land adjoining those of Josiah Tattnall.\" Josiah was also given a plantation called Placentia, adjoining Thunderbolt. Granddaughter Claudia Cattell Tattnall was deeded the \"slaves etc.\"<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/27571625?seq=1 ''Abstracts of Wills of South Carolinians Recorded in Savannah, Ga.'', B.F. Taylor (1940)]</ref>\n\nThe first house was destroyed by a fire on January 7, 1771.<ref name=weaver/> [[John Berendt]] wrote in his 1994 book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' that a formal dinner party, held by either John Mullryne or Josiah Tattnall, Sr.,<ref name=arcadia/> was in progress when one of the servants informed the host that the roof was ablaze and that nothing could be done to stop it. The host \"rose calmly, clinked his glass, and invited guests to pick up their dinner plates and follow him into the garden\", where they ate the remainder of their meals in the glow of the flames.<ref>''Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (John Berendt; Random House, 1994)</ref>\n\nThe house was replaced by a brick mansion.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWhen Savannahians ousted and arrested royal Governor [[James Wright (governor)|James Wright]] in February 1776, John Mullryne and Josiah Tattnall aided his escape through Bonaventure to the HMS ''Scarborough'', a British naval vessel nearby.<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1779 the mansion was used as a hospital during the [[siege of Savannah]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nAfter the Mullryne and Tattnall actions in support of [[the Crown]] six years earlier, the Bonaventure estate was confiscated by the Revolutionary government in 1782 and sold at public auction to [[John Habersham]], a friend of the Tattnalls, who sold the property in 1788 to Josiah Tattnall, Jr., who had married two years earlier.<ref name=arcadia>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mUiKz_4qY9QC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9&dq=st+augustine+creek+bonaventure&source=bl&ots=GXgsHmsx1j&sig=ACfU3U0vBdFx_vY6_eyPABm7ll5ABlOfsw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwit8evoyOnoAhWZbc0KHeyOBUgQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=st%20augustine%20creek%20bonaventure&f=false ''Historic Bonaventure Cemetery: Photographs from the Collection of the Georgia Historical Society'', Arcadia Publishing (1998)]</ref> His wife, Harriet (1769\u20131802),<ref name=harriet>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriet Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> gave birth to three children who lived to adulthood: Edward (1788\u20131832),<ref name=EFT>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7440959/edward-fenwick-tattnall Edward Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> Harriet (d. 1819)<ref name=arcadia/> and [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah III]] (1795\u20131871).<ref name=JT3/>\n\nHarriet died in 1802 and was buried at the plantation beside her five children who died in infancy: Mary, Claudia, Josiah, John and Sally.<ref name=arcadia/> Josiah, Jr. died in 1804, two years after his wife, while in [[the Bahamas]].<ref name=arcadia/> The orphaned children were raised in [[London]], England, by their grandfather.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nIn 1817, Josiah Tattnall, Jr.\u2019s children reclaimed their family's lands. After his sister's death in 1819 and his brother's in 1832, Bonaventure passed solely to Josiah III.<ref name=arcadia/> Josiah III had joined the [[United States Navy]] in 1812 and fought in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nThe mansion was destroyed, by another fire, in 1800.<ref name=weaver/>\n\nThe estate remained in the Tattnall family until 1846, when Captain Peter Wiltberger (1791\u20131853)<ref name=arcadia/> became the new owner. The sale excluded the Tattnall family cemetery, but Wiltberger agreed to maintain it.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nWiltberger died shortly after purchasing Bonaventure and was buried at the estate beside his wife, Susan (1788\u20131849), and their son, Rutherford (1827\u20131932).<ref name=arcadia/> Another son, Major William Henry Wiltberger (1825\u20131872),<ref name=arcadia/> inherited the property. After fighting in the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], in which he attained the rank of Major, he fulfilled his father's desire to turn part of Bonaventure into a public cemetery by forming Evergreen Cemetery Company on June 12, 1868.<ref name=arcadia/> Bonaventure came under the control of said company.<ref name=jones/> Major Wiltberger died in 1872 and was buried next to his family in section B, lot 3 of the cemetery he helped create.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nAfter the death of William, all titles to Bonaventure and the cemetery tracts were transferred to the Evergreen Cemetery Company by the executors of his estate. The Evergreen Cemetery of Bonaventure was bought by the city of Savannah on July 7, 1907, for $30,000.<ref name=arcadia/> Greenwich Cemetery became an addition to Bonaventure in 1933.<ref>[https://www.savannahga.gov/878/Greenwich-Cemetery Greenwich Cemetery] - SavannahGA.gov</ref>\n\n==Bonaventure Cemetery==\nThe following notable members of the Tattnall family are buried in today's [[Bonaventure Cemetery]], in section E, lot 1:<ref name=arcadia/>\n\n*Harriet Tattnall (1769\u20131802)<ref name=harriet/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1/>\n*Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832)<ref name=EFT/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall III]] (1795\u20131871)<ref name=JT3>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11367/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Jr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov\n\n[[Category:African-American history in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Plantations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1762]]\n[[Category:1762 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Bonaventure Plantation\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = File:Bonaventure_Plantation_1779.png\n| caption             = An October 1779 map by Antoine O'Connor, chief engineer of French Admiral-General [[Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_hxaDPBdd8kC&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=antoine+o%27connor+engineer&source=bl&ots=DEXddG3f7G&sig=ACfU3U3SZmwnDL6gKWUU2RT1yGmXaWjOpw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi-3PGIh-voAhWUUs0KHcLzDdcQ6AEwAHoECAUQKQ#v=onepage&q=antoine%20o'connor%20engineer&f=false ''Engineers of Independence: A Documentary History of the Army Engineers in the American Revolution, 1775-1783'', Paul K. Walker; The Minerva Group, 2002]</ref> showing the location of Bonaventure\n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[colonial America|Colonial]] [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], \n| address             = \n| client              = \n| owner               = \u2022 John Mullryne (original; 1762)<br />\u2022 Josiah Tattnall, Sr. (''unknown''\u20131782)<br />\u2022 [[John Habersham]] (1782\u20131788)<br />\u2022 [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1788\u20131804)<br />\u2022 Edward Tattnall, Harriet Tattnall & [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall III]] (1817\u20131819)<br />\u2022 Edward Tattnall & Josiah Tattnall III (1819\u20131832)<br />\u2022 Josiah Tattnall III (1832\u20131846)<br />\u2022 Peter Wiltberger (1846\u20131853)<br >\u2022 William Wiltberger (1853\u20131907)\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32|2|33|N|81|2|35|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1762, after 1771\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     =\n| destruction_date    = 1771 (fire), 1800 (fire)\n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''Bonaventure Plantation''' was a [[plantation]] in [[colonial America|colonial]] [[Savannah, Georgia]], on land now occupied by Greenwich Cemetery and [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]. The site was {{convert|600|acre|km2}}, including a [[plantation house]] and private cemetery, located on the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], about {{convert|3.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} east of the Savannah Colony.\n\n==History==\nThe plantation was founded in 1762<ref name=archive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov</ref> by Colonel John Mullryne (d. January 6, 1786, in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]]),<ref name=weaver>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UVba5QR1YnkC&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=john+mullryne+1786&source=bl&ots=mxM_Oz0Z4K&sig=ACfU3U1yJ79kxRg78hsrsGypa-jo0sKgZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqhNT-zuvoAhWDAp0JHeCVBpAQ6AEwBnoECAsQQA#v=onepage&q=john%20mullryne%201786&f=false ''Tombstones I Have Known'', Lamar Weaver, Charaman M. Campbell, 2001]</ref> who had emigrated from England to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], initially, before moving north to Savannah.<ref name=jones>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1fExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA540&lpg=PA540&dq=colonel+john+mulryne+savannah&source=bl&ots=Mfalti1wc_&sig=ACfU3U00vP0eRMZLT6FGp_T_8j78kdIjVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj188Pv1-joAhVBXc0KHQ1iCD4Q6AEwBHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=colonel%20john%20mulryne%20savannah&f=false ''History of Savannah, Ga: From Its Settlement to the Close of the Eighteenth Century''], Charles Colcock Jones (D. Mason & Company, 1890)</ref> The property fell into the possession of the Tattnall family \u2014 Josiah Tattnall, Sr. (b. February 8, 1740),<ref name=huger>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/27575354?seq=3#metadata_info_tab_contents ''The South Carolina Historical and Genealogical Magazine'', Vol. 14, No. 1 (Jan., 1913), pp. 3-19 (17 pages)], D. E. Huger Smith</ref>  of Charleston, had married Mary (b. October 19, 1741),<ref name=huger/> the youngest daughter of John and Claudia Mullryne.<ref name=jones/> [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7958532/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Sr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref> was born at the plantation, a year after his brother, John Mullryne Tattnall.<ref name=archive/>\n\nPer Claudia Mullryne's [[will and testament]], dated December 10, 1781, her daughter Catharine Moore, a widow, was left \"the mansion house called Bonaventure where she now resides.\" Upon Catharine's death, John and Claudia's grandson, John Mullryne Tattnall, would inherit the mansion, as well as \"six hundred acres of land adjoining those of Josiah Tattnall.\" Josiah was also given a plantation called Placentia, adjoining Thunderbolt. Granddaughter Claudia Cattell Tattnall was deeded the \"slaves etc.\"<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/27571625?seq=1 ''Abstracts of Wills of South Carolinians Recorded in Savannah, Ga.'', B.F. Taylor (1940)]</ref>\n\nThe first house was destroyed by a fire on January 7, 1771.<ref name=weaver/> [[John Berendt]] wrote in his 1994 book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' that a formal dinner party, held by either John Mullryne or Josiah Tattnall, Sr.,<ref name=arcadia/> was in progress when one of the servants informed the host that the roof was ablaze and that nothing could be done to stop it. The host \"rose calmly, clinked his glass, and invited guests to pick up their dinner plates and follow him into the garden\", where they ate the remainder of their meals in the glow of the flames.<ref>''Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (John Berendt; Random House, 1994)</ref>\n\nThe house was replaced by a brick mansion.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWhen Savannahians ousted and arrested royal Governor [[James Wright (governor)|James Wright]] in February 1776, John Mullryne and Josiah Tattnall aided his escape through Bonaventure to the HMS ''Scarborough'', a British naval vessel nearby.<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1779 the mansion was used as a hospital during the [[siege of Savannah]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe Bonaventure estate was confiscated by the Revolutionary government in 1782 and sold at public auction to [[John Habersham]], a friend of the Tattnalls, who sold the property in 1788 to Josiah Tattnall, Jr., who had married two years earlier.<ref name=arcadia>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mUiKz_4qY9QC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9&dq=st+augustine+creek+bonaventure&source=bl&ots=GXgsHmsx1j&sig=ACfU3U0vBdFx_vY6_eyPABm7ll5ABlOfsw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwit8evoyOnoAhWZbc0KHeyOBUgQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=st%20augustine%20creek%20bonaventure&f=false ''Historic Bonaventure Cemetery: Photographs from the Collection of the Georgia Historical Society'', Arcadia Publishing (1998)]</ref> His wife, Harriet (1769\u20131802),<ref name=harriet>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriet Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> gave birth to three children who lived to adulthood: Edward (1788\u20131832),<ref name=EFT>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7440959/edward-fenwick-tattnall Edward Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> Harriet (d. 1819)<ref name=arcadia/> and [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah III]] (1795\u20131871).<ref name=JT3/>\n\nHarriet died in 1802 and was buried at the plantation beside her five children who died in infancy: Mary, Claudia, Josiah, John and Sally.<ref name=arcadia/> Josiah, Jr. died in 1804, two years after his wife, while in [[the Bahamas]].<ref name=arcadia/> The orphaned children were raised in [[London]], England, by their grandfather.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nIn 1817, Josiah Tattnall, Jr.\u2019s children reclaimed their family's lands. After his sister's death in 1819 and his brother's in 1832, Bonaventure passed solely to Josiah III.<ref name=arcadia/> Josiah III had joined the [[United States Navy]] in 1812 and fought in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nThe mansion was destroyed, by another fire, in 1800.<ref name=weaver/>\n\nThe estate remained in the Tattnall family until 1846, when Captain Peter Wiltberger (1791\u20131853)<ref name=arcadia/> became the new owner. The sale excluded the Tattnall family cemetery, but Wiltberger agreed to maintain it.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nWiltberger died shortly after purchasing Bonaventure and was buried at the estate beside his wife, Susan (1788\u20131849), and their son, Rutherford (1827\u20131932).<ref name=arcadia/> Another son, Major William Henry Wiltberger (1825\u20131872),<ref name=arcadia/> inherited the property. After fighting in the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], in which he attained the rank of Major, he fulfilled his father's desire to turn part of Bonaventure into a public cemetery by forming Evergreen Cemetery Company on June 12, 1868.<ref name=arcadia/> Bonaventure came under the control of said company.<ref name=jones/> Major Wiltberger died in 1872 and was buried next to his family in section B, lot 3 of the cemetery he helped create.<ref name=arcadia/>\n\nAfter the death of William, all titles to Bonaventure and the cemetery tracts were transferred to the Evergreen Cemetery Company by the executors of his estate. The Evergreen Cemetery of Bonaventure was bought by the city of Savannah on July 7, 1907, for $30,000.<ref name=arcadia/> Greenwich Cemetery became an addition to Bonaventure in 1933.<ref>[https://www.savannahga.gov/878/Greenwich-Cemetery Greenwich Cemetery] - SavannahGA.gov</ref>\n\n==Bonaventure Cemetery==\nThe following notable members of the Tattnall family are buried in today's [[Bonaventure Cemetery]], in section E, lot 1:<ref name=arcadia/>\n\n*Harriet Tattnall (1769\u20131802)<ref name=harriet/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1/>\n*Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832)<ref name=EFT/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall III]] (1795\u20131871)<ref name=JT3>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11367/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Jr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov\n\n[[Category:African-American history in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Plantations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1762]]\n[[Category:1762 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventure_Plantation"}
{"title_page": "Eider Batista", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Eider Batista\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Cuban\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1981|2|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Holgu\u00edn]], Cuba\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Eider Batista''' (born 18 February 1981) is a Cuban [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]] event at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/eider-batista-1.html |title=Eider Batista Olympic Results |accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batista, Eider}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Holgu\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Eider Batista\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Cuban\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1981|2|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Holgu\u00edn]], Cuba\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Eider Batista''' (born 18 February 1981) is a Cuban [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]] event at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/eider-batista-1.html |title=Eider Batista Olympic Results |accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batista, Eider}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Holgu\u00edn]]\n{{Cuba-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in rowing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eider_Batista"}
{"title_page": "Participants in the Madoff investment scandal", "text_new": "{{update|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n[[File:BernardMadoff.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Bernard Madoff]]]]\n'''Participants in the [[Madoff investment scandal]]''' included employees of [[Bernard Madoff]]'s investment firm with specific knowledge of the [[Ponzi scheme]], a three-person accounting firm that assembled his reports, and a network of [[feeder fund]]s that invested their clients' money with Madoff while collecting significant fees. Madoff avoided most direct financial scrutiny by accepting investments only through these feeder funds, while obtaining false [[financial audit|auditing]] statements for his firm. The liquidation trustee of Madoff's firm has implicated managers of the feeder funds for ignoring signs of Madoff's deception. Although Madoff claimed to have executed the scheme alone, subsequent investigation has shown that he was assisted by a small group of close associates, as well as the feeders' self-interested indifference to the source of his investment returns.\n\n==Madoff Securities International Ltd.==\nIn 2008, about $1 billion was transferred last between Madoff's U.S. firm and Madoff Securities International Ltd. in London.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=azeCkQIOM0L8&refer=uk |title=Madoff Fraud Charges Could Be Filed in U.K. This Year (Update4) |last=Lumley |first=James |date=March 27, 2009 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130118064350/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=azeCkQIOM0L8&refer=uk |archivedate=January 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"article1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123815606271556053 |title=U.K. Could Charge More Than Just Madoff |last=Bryan-Low |first=Cassell |date=March 28, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219172250/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123815606271556053 |archivedate=February 19, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2009 Judge [[Louis L. Stanton]] granted [[power of attorney]] to [[Irving Picard]], trustee, over Madoff's controlling stake in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090324-716334.html |title=Trustee Granted Control Over Madoff's Stake In UK Operations |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 24, 2009}} {{dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities in the U.K. are seeking evidence of [[money laundering]] involving the London business, Madoff Securities International Ltd., which opened in 1983 as a separate legal entity from Mr. Madoff's U.S. New York office.  He allegedly sent more than $250 million beginning as early as 2002, from his New York-based firm, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities LLC, to the U.K. office and then back to accounts in the U.S.<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/><ref name=\"article1\"/>\n\nIn 2000, Madoff began to add staff and expand the operation, and loaned the business $62.5 million.  He had a staff of 25, including traders, managers and support.  Instructions to staff  was that they communicate with Madoff Securities through personal e-mail accounts, not through company e-mail.<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/>\n\nThere were nine directors. Family members with shares included Mark and Andrew Madoff, Peter Madoff, and Bernard himself. Ruth Madoff, Bernard Madoff's wife, also held shares.\n<ref name=\"article3\">{{cite news |last=Lauricella |first=Tom |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123681392137901653 |title=Madoff Used U.K. Office in Cash Ploy, Filing Says - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=March 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227150311/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123681392137901653 |archivedate=February 27, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nNon-family members with shares included Maurice J. \"Sonny\" Cohn. Madoff and Cohn were shareholders in [[Cohmad Securities]], which steered investors to Mr. Madoff's advisory business.  In 1987, Mr. Cohn had shares of Madoff Holdings Ltd., a predecessor to the current London firm. In 1998, Mr. Cohn held 35,624 non-voting shares, some of which he transferred to \"BL Madoff\" in 1998, and the rest that he \"disposed of\" in 2004.<ref name=\"article3\"/>\n\n===Paul Konigsberg===\nPaul Konigsberg, a New York City accountant and a longtime friend for more than 25 years, prepared two Madoff Family Foundation tax returns, and received the non-voting shares, valued at $35,000.  He did work for the London office when it was first opened.\n<ref name=\"article3\"/>  A general ledger of Madoff accounts listed Konigsberg, of the reputable accounting firm of Konigsberg, Wolf & Co., as receiving $30,000 a month to advise the MSIL operations, and funnel client checks to the London office for Madoff's own use.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-04-23/madoffs-london-money-laundering-scam/ |title=Was Madoff 'Victim' and Best Friend an Accomplice? \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=The Daily Beast |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425142840/http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-04-23/madoffs-london-money-laundering-scam/ |archivedate=April 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nClients were often directed to Mr. Konigsberg by Mr. Madoff and his family. Mr. Konigsberg prepared the tax returns of foundations of six other families, many of which have lost millions, even hundreds of millions, of dollars.  He also represented scores of individual Madoff investors.  Mr. Konigsberg's firm has received a civil subpoena from the SEC.  His Madoff-related clients included Carl and Ruth Shapiro, Boston philanthropists whose foundation lost $145 million, and whose son-in-law, Robert M. Jaffe, under investigation, is a Madoff business partner.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\"/><ref name=\"WayneRashbaumNYT031209\">{{cite news |first=Leslie |last=Wayne |author2=Rashbaum, William K. |title=Investigation Into Madoff Fraud Turns to a Small Circle of Accountants |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/12/business/12accountants.html |work=New York Times |date=March 11, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501173649/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/12/business/12accountants.html |archivedate=May 1, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nKonigsberg held Madoff accounts under his name including two in the name of the Westlake Foundation. Paul J. and Judith Konigsberg are officers and directors of the foundation. He owns homes in his wife, Judith's name in Greenwich, Connecticut and Palm Beach Gardens, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-4-million-lawsui.php?ref=reccafe |title=Bernie Madoff: $4 Million Lawsuit Filed Against Paul J. Konigsberg |date=May 28, 2009 |website=Mrs Panstreppon's Blog |publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531081307/http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-4-million-lawsui.php |archivedate=May 31, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2009, Steven Leber filed a $4 million lawsuit against Konigsberg and his accounting firm for [[negligence]], and breach of [[fiduciary]] duty.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/15891679/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Complaint |title=PACER \u2013 Leber vs. Konigsberg \u2013 Complaint |publisher=Scribd.com |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107063548/http://www.scribd.com/doc/15891679/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Complaint |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Konigsberg answered the charges with [[affirmative defense]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/15893994/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Konigsberg-Response |title=PACER \u2013 Leber vs. Konigsberg \u2013 Konigsberg Response |publisher=Scribd.com |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107063745/http://www.scribd.com/doc/15893994/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Konigsberg-Response |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Konigsberg pleaded guilty in connection to the Madoff case and will consequently face up to 30 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/24/news/companies/madoff-konigsberg-guilty/index.html |title=Madoff's accountant pleads guilty |last=Lobosco |first=Katie |date=June 24, 2014 |website=[[CNNMoney]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |quote=Paul Konigsberg, Bernie Madoff's former accountant, faces up to 30 years in prison. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816034519/http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/24/news/companies/madoff-konigsberg-guilty/index.html |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On July 9, 2015, U.S. District Court Judge Laura Taylor Swain agreed with prosecutors that Konigsberg did not know about Madoff's scheme and had cooperated fully with investigators. Swain ruled that Konigsberg had earned lenience from federal sentencing guidelines and did not have to serve any time in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-madoff-konigsberg-idUSKCN0PJ2VL20150709 |title=Ex-accounting executive avoids prison in Madoff fraud case |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=July 9, 2015 |accessdate=February 5, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526070831/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-madoff-konigsberg-idUSKCN0PJ2VL20150709 |archivedate=May 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Norman F. Levy===\nEvidence is being gathered  by investigators on a U.S.-U.K. task force that Konigsberg and Levy, a real-estate mogul and philanthropist are believed to be involved in an international transfer of money.   Levy is believed to have helped Paul Konigsberg funnel checks to London. And investigators in New York say there were billions of dollars' worth of checks going back and forth between Madoff and Levy.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\"/>\n\nRuth and Bernie Madoff had an intimate relationship with Levy and his wife, Betty.  Madoff was long known to have been Levy's \"fixer,\" obtaining everything from choice restaurant reservations to emergency medical care. Levy had offices one floor below Madoff's in New York's [[Lipstick Building]]. It was Levy who introduced high-profile investors to Madoff.\n\nJeanne Levy-Church's losses forced her to shut her JEHT Foundation and her parents' foundation, the Betty and Norman F. Levy Foundation, lost $244 million.  JEH helped the less fortunate, especially ex-convicts.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\" /><ref name=\"WayneRashbaumNYT031209\" />\n\nFollowing the death of his wife, Levy's girlfriend, model [[Carmen Dell'Orefice]], an investor, said Levy was Madoff's \"father figure\". When Levy died in 2005 at the age of 93, Madoff extolled him as a man whose friendship he had cherished and who had \"taught me so much.\" Levy's son Francis said his father believed in Madoff: \"If there's one honorable person,\" he said, \"it's Bernie.\"<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\" /><ref name=\"currentpage1\">{{cite web |last=Seal |first=Mark |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/04/madoff200904?currentPage=all |title=Madoff's World |publisher=vanityfair.com |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415021714/http://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/04/madoff200904?currentPage=all |archivedate=April 15, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Chapter 15 bankruptcy protection===\nOn April 14, 2009, the liquidators of Madoff International Limited of London filed for [[Chapter 15]] bankruptcy recognition in West Palm Beach, Florida, and sued Peter Madoff, to recover a  1964 [[Aston Martin DB2/4]] automobile worth an estimated $200,000.   In March and May 2008, Madoff International wire-transferred 135,000 pounds ($198,207) to buy a car for Peter Madoff, and delivered it to him  at his residence in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]]. Madoff International's listed assets are as much as $500 million and debt of more than $1 billion in its bankruptcy petition.  The bankruptcy is designed to block U.S. lawsuits against foreign companies with U.S. operations while they reorganize overseas.  Investors who filed an involuntary [[personal bankruptcy]] petition against Madoff want his business's U.K. unit's bankruptcy moved to New York because \"overlapping discovery, related assets and common creditors\" among the various cases mean they should be in the same court.\n\nThe Chapter 15 case is ''In re Madoff Securities International Ltd.'', 09-16751, [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]], Southern District of Florida (West Palm Beach).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=agGTdJJDCZos&refer=us |title=Madoff Investors Want U.K. Unit Bankruptcy Moved (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=April 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224028/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103 |archivedate=January 22, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2009 the Chapter 15 case was transferred to the Southern District of New York as ''Madoff Securities International Limited, Stephen John Akers, Mark Richard Byers, and Andrew Laurence as the Joint Provisional Liquidators'', 09-12998, so it can be administered more effectively with the related involuntary bankruptcies against Madoff, and his companies, also filed in New York. The associated adversary proceeding was also moved to the Southern District of New York as ''Akers et al. v. Madoff'', 09-1186, demanding $235,000 against Peter B. Madoff.\n\n==David G. Friehling==\nSince at least 1991, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities had been audited by Friehling & Horowitz CPAs, a little-known accounting firm in [[New City, New York|New City]], north of New York City. The firm consisted of two principals, [[David G. Friehling]] and Jerome Horowitz, and a part-time secretary. Horowitz was semi-retired; Friehling was the sole active practitioner.<ref name=SECFriehling>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2009/comp20959.pdf|title=Securities and Exchange Commission v. David G. Friehling, Friehling & Horowitz, CPAs, P.E.|date=March 2009|publisher=United States District Court, Southern District Of New York|accessdate=25 September 2015}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nWell before the Madoff scandal broke, several observers doubted that a tiny firm with only one active accountant could competently audit a firm that had grown into a multibillion-dollar operation.  In 2007, Aksia LLC, a hedge fund consultant, warned its clients to stay away from Madoff for that very reason; its CEO, Jim Vos, likened this situation to [[General Motors]] being audited by a three-person firm.<ref>Fitzgerald, Jim. [http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html Madoff's financial empire audited by tiny firm: one guy]. [[Associated Press]] via [[Seattle Times]], December 18, 2008.</ref>  Others were suspicious that Madoff refused requests for [[due diligence]] because his accountant\u2014supposedly his brother-in-law\u2014was the only one allowed to see the books.<ref>{{cite book|last=Markopolos|first=Harry|authorlink=Harry Markopolos|url=https://archive.org/details/noonewouldlisten00mark|title=No One Would Listen: A True Financial Thriller|date=March 2010|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]]|isbn=978-0-470-55373-2|url-access=registration}}</ref> Indeed, for many years, Friehling's practice was so small that he operated out of his house. He only got an office when Madoff told him that some investors were asking questions about the audits. Even then, his operation remained very small; in 2008 it only garnered $180,000 in earnings, far less than conventional wisdom would suggest for a firm that was supposedly earning substantial fees from auditing the Madoff operation. It later emerged that officials at [[Fairfield Greenwich Group]], operator of the largest Madoff [[feeder fund]], had been aware as early as 2005 that Friehling was the firm's sole employee.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nFriehling was charged on March 18, 2009, with [[securities fraud]], aiding and abetting [[investment adviser]] fraud, and four counts of filing false audit reports with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Friehling waived indictment and pleaded not guilty to criminal charges on July 10, 2009. He agreed to proceed without having the evidence in the criminal case against him reviewed by a grand jury at a hearing before U.S. District Judge Alvin Hellerstein in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124784585862258641 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first=Chad |last=Bray |title=Madoff Ex-Auditor Friehling Enters a Plea of Not Guilty |date=July 18, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110833/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124784585862258641 |archivedate=January 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He faced up to 105 years in prison on all of the charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/FriehlingComplaint20090318.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Friehling Complaint 2009-03-18 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109045508/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/FriehlingComplaint20090318.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"article4\">{{cite news |last=Efrati |first=Amir |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123738779664971505 |title=Accountant Arrested for Sham Audits - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=March 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705225627/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123738779664971505 |archivedate=July 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"press1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2009/2009-60.htm |title=Press Release: SEC Charges Madoff Auditors With Fraud; 2009\u201360; March 18, 2009 |publisher=Sec.gov |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507214906/http://www.sec.gov/news/press/2009/2009-60.htm |archivedate=May 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Federal prosecutors had until about June 17, 2009 to produce a [[grand jury]] indictment against him, or a plea bargain to end the case.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5g360RkdSH5ANu_nugd01e6IEjAfwD988U6LO0] {{dead link|date=June 2009|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nMadoff's firm paid Friehling between $12,000 and $14,500 a month for his services between 2004 and 2007.<ref name=\"article4\"/>\n\nAlthough required, Friehling was not registered with the [[Public Company Accounting Oversight Board]], which was created under the [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] of 2002 to help detect fraud.  Nor was the firm \"peer reviewed,\" in which auditors check out one another for [[quality control]].  According to the [[American Institute of Certified Public Accountants]] (AICPA), Friehling was enrolled in their peer-review program, but was not required to participate because he advised the group that he had not conducted audits for 15 years.<ref name=\"article2\">{{cite news |last=Jeanne |first=Ianthe |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123491638561904323 |title=Accounting Firms That Missed Fraud at Madoff May Be Liable - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=February 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706002421/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123491638561904323 |archivedate=July 6, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2008/12/17/news/companies/madoff.auditor.fortune/index.htm Madoff's Auditor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308000826/http://money.cnn.com/2008/12/17/news/companies/madoff.auditor.fortune/index.htm |date=March 8, 2009 }} [[CNN]] December 17, 2008.</ref> It later emerged that Madoff's banker, [[JPMorgan Chase]], had known that Friehling wasn't registered with the PCAOB or subject to peer review as early as 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/020311madoffjpm.pdf |title=Madoff trustee suit against JPMorgan Chase |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2013 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nFriehling pleaded guilty in November 2009. He admitted to simply rubber-stamping Madoff's filings with the SEC; rather than perform actual audits, he signed blank SEC forms before Madoff and others filled them in.  He also revealed that he continued to audit Madoff even though he had invested a substantial amount of money with him; accountants aren't allowed to audit broker-dealers with whom they're investing.  He agreed to forfeit $3.18 million in accounting fees and withdrawals from his account with Madoff, as well as his three-story, 4,400-square-foot house in New City and one other property.  Friehling faced a maximum sentence of 114 years in prison, but unlike Madoff has agreed to cooperate with the government. Calling himself a victim of Madoff, he faced a possible sentence of 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Hamblett&nbsp;All Articles |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202435168711&slreturn=1 |title=Madoff's Accountant Acknowledges Guilt, Casts Himself as Victim |publisher=Law.com |date=November 4, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nIn May 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Laura Taylor Swain]] sentenced Friehling to one year of home detention and one year of supervised release. Friehling avoided prison because he cooperated extensively with federal prosecutors and because he had been unaware of the extent of Madoff's crimes. Addressing the court at the hearing, Friehling apologized to Madoff's victims. Referring to Madoff's reported statement that he was a \"dumb auditor,\" Friehling said: \"I would rather be regarded as dumb than crooked. I did not question what I should have questioned.\"<ref name=\"Goldstein\">Matthew Goldstein, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/business/dealbook/madoff-accountant-avoids-prison-term.html Madoff Accountant Avoids Prison Term] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126104940/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/business/dealbook/madoff-accountant-avoids-prison-term.html |date=November 26, 2016 }}, ''New York Times'' (May 28, 2015).</ref>\n\nSwain accepted the plea terms, but suggested that Friehling be forced to pay part of the overall $130 million forfeiture arising from the fraud. Swain said that she did not believe Friehling's nonfeasance took place \"in a vacuum,\" and felt the forfeiture was necessary to hold the defendants to account even though it will likely never be repaid in full.<ref name=\"Goldstein\"/>\n\nFriehling's involvement made the Madoff scandal the largest [[accounting fraud]] in history, dwarfing the $11 billion fraud orchestrated by [[Bernard Ebbers]] at [[MCI Inc.|WorldCom]].\n\n==Peter B. Madoff==\nPeter B. Madoff, Chief Compliance Officer, worked with his brother Bernie for more than 40 years, and ran the daily operations for the past 20 years. Peter Madoff helped create the computerized trading system used by the firm and his daughter, [[Shana Madoff|Shana Madoff Swanson]], worked for him at the firm as a rules and compliance officer and attorney. In 2007 she married [[Eric Swanson]], whom she had met as he was conducting an SEC review of the firm in 2003 as an SEC Assistant Director.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=sI1jqoMRW7gC&pg=PA417&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=shana%20madoff%20peter%20compliance&f=false Business Ethics: Ethical Decision Making & Cases - O. C. Ferrell, John Fraedrich, Ferrell - Google Books] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704224558/http://books.google.com/books?id=sI1jqoMRW7gC&pg=PA417&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA |date=July 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=uDWuilMrwkcC&pg=PA376&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=shana%20&f=false Investigation of Failure of the SEC to Uncover Bernard Madoff's Ponzi Scheme ... - Google Books] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508170718/http://books.google.com/books?id=uDWuilMrwkcC&pg=PA376&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAg |date=May 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPeter graduated from [[Fordham University School of Law]] in 1970 and was formerly director of the [[National Stock Exchange (Jersey City, New Jersey)|National Stock Exchange]] (Cincinnati Stock Exchange).<ref name=\"Barlyn\">{{cite news | last = Barlyn | first = Suzanne | title = Madoff Case Raises Compliance Questions | work = [[Wall Street Journal]] | date = December 23, 2008 | url = http://www.careerjournal.com/article/SB123005903944830699.html | accessdate = March 1, 2008 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228034553/http://www.careerjournal.com/article/SB123005903944830699.html | archivedate = December 28, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"http\">{{cite news |last = Williamson |first = Elizabeth |author2 = Kara Scannell |title = Family Filled Posts at Industry Groups |work = [[Wall Street Journal]] |date = December 18, 2008 |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122956128953016563 |accessdate = March 1, 2009 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150303063407/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122956128953016563 |archivedate = March 3, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Peter owned a home in [[Old Westbury, New York]], valued between $3\u20135 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090403/FREE/904039987 |title=Peter Madoff gets $10K in monthly expenses \u2013 Crain's New York Business |publisher=Crainsnewyork.com |date=April 3, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406052156/http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090403/FREE/904039987 |archivedate=April 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a $4.2 million home in [[Palm Beach, Florida]], the title of which was transferred  on November 8, 2006 to his wife, Marion, and a vintage [[Aston Martin]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123154665944869835 |title=Madoff Brother, at Arm's Length? - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Tom |last1=Lauricella |first2=Aaron |last2=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405040115/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123154665944869835 |archivedate=April 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/30/cbsnews_investigates/main4765109.shtml |title=Double Trouble for Madoffs? \u2013 CBS News |publisher=CBS News |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203035014/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/30/cbsnews_investigates/main4765109.shtml |archivedate=February 3, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"investigates1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/12/cbsnews_investigates/main4797238.shtml |title=Madoff's Wife Could Face Legal Trouble \u2013 CBS News |publisher=CBS News |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223161150/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/12/cbsnews_investigates/main4797238.shtml |archivedate=February 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter stepped down from the Board of Directors of the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association (SIFMA) in December 2008, as news of the Ponzi scheme broke. Peter also co-signed Bernie's bail bond. According to court documents, Peter did not agree to cooperate in the investigation.<ref name=\"businessweek.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-06-29/peter-madoff-bernie-s-brother-to-plead-guilty |title=Peter Madoff Admits Aiding Brother's Ponzi Scheme |last1=Hurtado |first1=Patricia |last2=Van Voris |first2=Bob |last3=Smythe |first3=Christie |date=June 30, 2012 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712184337/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-06-29/peter-madoff-bernie-s-brother-to-plead-guilty |archivedate=July 12, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter also owns between 5% and 10% of, and is a director of, [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/>  He has been subpoenaed by [[Massachusetts]]'s [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[William F. Galvin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.tbo.com/content/2008/dec/18/sp-attorney-general-leaves-madoff-case/ |title=Attorney General Leaves Madoff Case |publisher=.tbo.com |date=December 18, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208015751/http://www2.tbo.com/content/2008/dec/18/sp-attorney-general-leaves-madoff-case/ |archivedate=February 8, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"business1\"/>\n\nOn  April 3, 2009, his temporarily frozen assets previously ordered were modified to be allowed to spend up to $10,000 per month for living expenses, including mortgage loans and insurance premiums.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123877013231186763 |title=Peter Madoff Agrees to Revised Asset Freeze - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 4, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Aaron |last=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314145644/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123877013231186763 |archivedate=March 14, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter served as a [[trustee]] for law student Andrew Samuels' $470,000 inheritance from his grandfather who worked for Madoff and created a trust for him.  Andrew's lawsuit, claiming $2 million for breach his fiduciary duty by investing his inheritance with Bernard Madoff was settled in July 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a0zI28JuSN9I | work=Bloomberg | title=Student Settles Suit Against Peter Madoff Over Lost Inheritance | date=July 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731153558/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a0zI28JuSN9I | archivedate=July 31, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The case is ''Ross v. Madoff'', 09-5534, [[New York Supreme Court]] for [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] ([[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]).<ref>{{cite news |last=McCool |first=Grant |date=25 March 2009 |title=NY student wins freeze of Madoff brother's assets |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-brother/ny-student-wins-freeze-of-madoff-brothers-assets-idUSTRE52O72X20090326 |agency=Reuters |location=New York |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing his assets. Madoff agreed to attachments of $2.5 million to his [[Long Island]] home. His attorney is H. James Pickerstein. The pension fund case is ''Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff'', FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=apLMJ4p8DYyY&refer=home |title=Madoff-Linked Asset Freeze Lifted in Connecticut Suit (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=April 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2009, Peter demanded a $500,000 licensing fee as part of the sale of BLMIS for intellectual property used by the market-making business, but it was rejected by the bankruptcy trustee who maintains that the patents are the property of the business. Members of the Madoff family, including Madoff, own holding companies that own Primex LLC, which holds intellectual property licensed to the Nasdaq stock market. The patents are used for electronic trading.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124110591783073437 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=David | last=Mclaughlin | title=Judge Backs Sale of Madoff Market-Making Unit | date=April 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310125309/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124110591783073437 | archivedate=March 10, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Frank Lautenberg]]'s family foundation, which invested more than $7 million, also filed a lawsuit against Peter Madoff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/jersey/index.ssf?/base/news-12/123553958738630.xml&coll=1 |title=Lautenberg foundation lawsuit targets Bernard Madoff's brother - NJ.com |publisher=NJ.com |date=February 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316211726/http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/jersey/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-12%2F123553958738630.xml&coll=1 |archivedate=March 16, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2012, Peter pleaded guilty in Federal court to a variety of charges and agreed to a 10-year prison term.  Peter Madoff sometimes signed many weeks of compliance reports in one sitting, intentionally changing pens and ink colors to make it appear he had signed them at various times, according to prosecutors.<ref>Neumeister, Larry, and Tom Hays, [https://news.yahoo.com/peter-madoff-pleads-guilty-nyc-blaming-brother-163003155--finance.html \"Peter Madoff pleads guilty in NYC, blaming brother\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305035239/http://news.yahoo.com/peter-madoff-pleads-guilty-nyc-blaming-brother-163003155--finance.html |date=March 5, 2016 }}, Associated Press via Yahoo!News, June 29, 2012.</ref> Peter Madoff admitted hiding millions of dollars from the I.R.S. to avoid taxes, and took $200,000 from the firm for charitable donations even after the fraud was exposed.<ref>Neumeister, Larry, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gswmdZD8Wz4Xb5xxqHEDuPJp6AeA?docId=b0b309c5e5144b76898f65279390a643 \"Peter Madoff pleads guilty in NYC, blaming brother\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702074228/http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gswmdZD8Wz4Xb5xxqHEDuPJp6AeA?docId=b0b309c5e5144b76898f65279390a643 |date=July 2, 2012 }}, Associated Press via Google.com/hostednews, June 29, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hoffman |first=William |title=Madoff's brother pleads guilty to tax fraud; Singer Hill admits failing to file returns |newspaper=Tax Notes Today \u2013 2012 TNT 127\u20138 |date=June 29, 2012}}<!--|accessdate=07/02/2012--></ref>\n\nA forfeiture order requires Peter to surrender all of his assets to the government, including cash, homes, cars and a [[Rolex]] [[watch]]. A settlement reached with his family requires the forfeiture of assets held by his wife, Marion, his daughter, Shana Madoff Swanson, and other family members.<ref name=\"businessweek.com\"/>\n\nOn December 20, 2012, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison for his involvement in the Ponzi scheme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madoff Brother To Serve 10 Years In Prison For Role In Ponzi Scheme|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/174312/madoff-brother-to-serve-10-years-in-prison-for-role-in-ponzi-scheme|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130130051431/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/174312/madoff-brother-to-serve-10-years-in-prison-for-role-in-ponzi-scheme|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 30, 2013|publisher=NY1|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref>  He is currently serving his sentence at [[FCI-Miami]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ | title=Inmate Locator}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/mia/ |title = FCI Miami}}</ref>  His Federal Bureau of Prisons inmate number is 67118-054.  His scheduled release date is 13 August 2020.\n\n==Ruth Madoff==\n[[Ruth Madoff]] withdrew $5.5 million on November 25, 2008, and $10 million on December 10, 2008, from her brokerage account at Cohmad, a feeder fund which had an office in Madoff's headquarters and was part-owned by him.<ref name=\"business1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/business/ticker/2009/02/galvin_seeks_to.html |title=Galvin seeks to shut down firm with Madoff ties \u2013 Daily Business Update \u2013 The Boston Globe |publisher=Boston.com |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214122117/http://boston.com/business/ticker/2009/02/galvin_seeks_to.html |archivedate=February 14, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"marketsnews1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSLC60093820090212 |title=Medici's Kohn says did not get Madoff payments &#124; Markets &#124; Markets News &#124; Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Boris |last=Groendahl |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707173215/http://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSLC60093820090212 |archivedate=July 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  In November, she also received $2 million from her husband's London office, Madoff Securities International Ltd.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29911053 |title=Madoff's Wife Got $2 Million from UK Unit \u2013 Financials * Europe * News * Story |publisher=CNBC.com |date=March 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612003214/http://www.cnbc.com/id/29911053 |archivedate=June 12, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2009, a [[CBS News]] investigation discovered that the Madoffs were moving assets during the 2006 SEC investigation.  Madoff had purchased their $9.5 million Palm Beach mansion in March 1994 in his wife's name.  Not until December 10, 2006, did she apply for \"[[Homestead exemption|homestead]]\" status, shielding their home from [[creditor]]s.  Her initial application was rejected because there was no proof it was her primary residence, which protects homeowners who have obtained the exemption from seizure.<ref name=\"bloomberg6\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aj6f7pk8l_00&refer=home |title=Madoff Prosecutors Seek to Take Businesses, Loans (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On September 18, 2008, she reapplied for [[Homestead exemption|Homestead]] Exemption, and it was granted on January 12, 2009, after Madoff's arrest.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/><ref name=\"investigates1\"/>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing her assets, because they were already frozen by the federal government. The pension fund case was ''Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff'', FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nShe did not attend her husband's sentencing.<ref name=wapo_20090626>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Madoff to Forfeit $170 Billion In Assets Ahead of Sentencing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/26/AR2009062604652.html |work=The Washington Post |agency=Bloomberg News  |date=27 June 2009 |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first1=Amir | last1=Efrati | first2=Robert | last2=Frank | title=Madoff's Wife Cedes Asset Claim | date=June 28, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310004154/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 | archivedate=March 10, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> As part of her husband's sentencing terms, she agreed to give up all of her possessions in return for a promise that federal prosecutors would not go after the $2.5 million she can keep from the federal prosecutors. The money was not protected from civil legal actions pursued by a court-appointed trustee liquidating Madoff's assets or by investor lawsuits, however.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,529858,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Ruth Madoff Asks to Keep Her Fur Coat as U.S. Marshals Seize Penthouse | date=July 2, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919011333/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,529858,00.html | archivedate=September 19, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2009, she was sued by trustee, [[Irving Picard]] for $45 million, which supported her \"life of splendor\". According to court filings, she received more than $3 million from the business over the prior six years to pay personal expenses charged to her [[American Express]] card, and $2 million in payments to a business called PetCare RX. \"Ruth Madoff was never an employee of BLMIS yet millions of dollars belonging to BLMIS and its customers found their way into her personal accounts and investments without any legitimate business purpose or any value to BLMIS, simply because of her relationship with Bernard Madoff.\" She was also required to itemize all expenditures over $100.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/08/04/2009-08-04_buybuy_to_madoff_wifes_free_spending.html | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Bernie Madoff's wife, Ruth, agrees to account for monthly spending | first1=Robert | last1=Gearty | first2=Leo | last2=Standora | date=August 4, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907153908/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/08/04/2009-08-04_buybuy_to_madoff_wifes_free_spending.html | archivedate=September 7, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The case is Picard v. Madoff, 1:09-ap-1391, U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Southern District of New York (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/29/trustee-sues-ruth-madoff-for-448-million/?hpw | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for $44.8 Million | first=Zachery | last=Kouwe | date=July 29, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Patrick | last=Fitzgerald | title=Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for More Than $44 Million | date=July 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110832/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 | archivedate=January 27, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/17780712/Lawsuit-Against-Ruth-Madoff-Irving-Picard |title=Lawsuit Against Ruth Madoff (Irving Picard) |publisher=Scribd.com |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025184157/http://www.scribd.com/doc/17780712/Lawsuit-Against-Ruth-Madoff-Irving-Picard |archivedate=October 25, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe has been named in several civil actions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aFpv4l_8Vg8Q&refer=home |title=Bernard Madoff's Wife Ruth Will Hire Her Own Lawyer (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 9, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She is represented by attorney Peter Chavkin<ref name=\"virtualbrandchannel1\"/> and David Barres.\n\nRuth has not been charged with any crime, and has not been questioned by prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lynnley |last=Browning |title=The Loneliest Woman in New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/14/fashion/14ruth.html |work=New York Times |date=June 12, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207212218/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/14/fashion/14ruth.html |archivedate=December 7, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She has been seen riding the [[New York City Subway]] and apparently did not attend her husband's June 29, 2009, sentencing hearing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 |title=Madoff's Wife Cedes Asset Claim |last1=Efrati |first1=Amir |last2=Frank |first2=Robert |date=June 28, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805033258/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 |archivedate=August 5, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRuth Madoff's combined assets with her husband had a net worth of between $823 million and $826 million. She had $92.6 million in assets listed in her own name:<ref name=\"regionalnews1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/03152009/news/regionalnews/ruth_in_crosshair_159631.htm |title=RUTH IN CROSSHAIR$ \u2013 New York Post |publisher=Nypost.com |date=March 15, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=James |last=Doran |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418061814/http://www.nypost.com/seven/03152009/news/regionalnews/ruth_in_crosshair_159631.htm |archivedate=April 18, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the $7 million Upper East Side penthouse; an $11 million mansion in Palm Beach, Fla.; Antibes and France totaling $19 million; $45 million in municipal bonds and $17 million in cash; $8.8 million worth of yachts; and $2.6 million worth of jewelry.<ref name=\"virtualbrandchannel1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE52C57L20090313?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Madoff to appeal bail, net worth revealed &#124; U.S. |publisher=Reuters |date=March 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318085800/http://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE52C57L20090313?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |archivedate=March 18, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The SEC worked with federal prosecutors, who filed a notice with the federal court to seek forfeiture of all listed ill-gotten assets.<ref name=\"regionalnews1\"/><ref>{{cite news |first=Michael J. |last=de la Merced |authorlink= |title=Prosecutors Try to Recover Assets of Madoff's Wife |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/17/business/17madoff.html |work=New York Times |publisher= |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2009, [[United States district court#United States district judges|U.S. District Judge]] Louis Stanton, presiding over the SEC case, filed an order modifying the property asset freeze. Ruth Madoff's lawyers asserted that \"Only Ruth Madoff has a [[beneficial ownership]]\" to a Manhattan apartment; about $45 million in [[municipal bond]]s deposited at [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp., and approximately $17 million in cash in another account, at [[Wachovia|Wachovia Bank]] NA.  Ruth Madoff says these assets are \"unrelated\" to the alleged fraud, Stanton wrote without ruling on her claim.<ref name=\"bloomberg1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aWVQJMrRh7Qc&refer=home |title=Ruth Madoff Says Her $62 Million 'Unrelated' to Fraud (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, shortly before Bernie Madoff was sentenced, prosecutors reached an agreement allowing Ruth Madoff to keep $2.5 million, while taking and selling the Madoffs' other assets.<ref name=autogenerated1a>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/06/bernie-madoffs-wife-ruth-settles-with-court-appointed-trustee.html \"Bernie Madoff\u2019s wife Ruth settles with court-appointed trustee\"]</ref> The settlement, however, did not preclude others, such as the court-appointed trustee [[Irving Picard]] of [[BakerHostetler]] who was liquidating her husband's firm, from seeking to recover funds from her, for example as a wrongful transferee of funds transferred to her.<ref>[https://www.assetsearchblog.com/2009/06/27/will-ruth-madoff-keep-her-remaining-2-5-million-in-assets/ \"Will Ruth Madoff Keep Her Remaining $2.5 Million In Assets?\"]</ref> Bernie Madoff\u2019s lawyer had asked the government to allow his wife to keep $70 million in assets that were in her name, as he forfeited all rights to assets totaling $170 billion.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-ruth/ruth-madoff-forfeits-asset-claims-left-with-2-5-million-idUSTRE55Q0BF20090627 \"Ruth Madoff forfeits asset claims, left with $2.5 million\"]</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, 77-year-old Ruth Madoff agreed to pay $594,000 ($250,000 in cash, and $344,000 of [[Trust law|trusts]] for two of her grandchildren), and to surrender her remaining assets when she dies, to settle claims by the court-appointed trustee Picard liquidating her husband's firm for former customers.<ref name=autogenerated1a /> Picard had sued Ruth Madoff for $44.8 million, saying she had lived a \"life of splendor\" on the gains from the fraud committed by her husband, but settled for less, given her limited assets.<ref name=autogenerated1a /><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 \"Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for More Than $44 Million,\"] ''The Wall Street Journal''.</ref> Picard said that the settlement was not evidence she knew of or participated in the fraud.<ref name=autogenerated1a /> She is required to provide reports to Picard about her expenditures often, as to any purchase over $100, to ensure she does not have any hidden bank accounts.<ref name=autogenerated2a>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/life-madoff-ruth-living-25-million-connecticut/story?id=36557458 \"Life After Madoff: Ruth Living on $2.5 Million in Connecticut\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/money-and-power/a9656715/bernie-madoff-ponzi-scheme-scandal-story-and-aftermath/ \"Bernie Madoff's Ponzi Scheme - How the Scandal Affected His Family, Ruth, Mark & Andrew\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Fred Wilpon==\n[[Sterling Equities]], a group of companies owned by [[Fred Wilpon]], was sued in December 2010, for $1 billion by trustee Picard. Wilpon owns the [[New York Mets]] baseball team, a [[SportsNet New York|sports cable network]] and extensive real estate holdings.  Picard charged that \"red flags\" were ignored, and there was no [[due diligence]].  He claimed that the Mets owners \"were simply in too deep \u2013 having substantially supported their businesses with Madoff money \u2013 to do anything but ignore the gathering clouds.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-05/mets-owners-may-follow-bayou-accord-in-any-settlement-deal-with-picard.html | work=Bloomberg | first1=Linda | last1=Sandler | first2=Bob | last2=Van Voris | title=Mets Bayou Accord May Be Model for a Madoff Suit Deal | date=February 5, 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812194501/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-05/mets-owners-may-follow-bayou-accord-in-any-settlement-deal-with-picard.html | archivedate=August 12, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  On February 10, 2011, former N.Y. governor [[Mario Cuomo]] was appointed as a mediator in the dispute between the trustee and Sterling.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/11/sports/11mediator.html?ref=sports | work=The New York Times | first1=Ken | last1=Belson | first2=Richard | last2=Sandomir | title=Mario Cuomo Is Named Mediator in the Mets-Madoff Case | date=February 10, 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206185752/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/11/sports/11mediator.html?ref=sports | archivedate=February 6, 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 19, 2012 Wilpon and Picard agreed to settle the lawsuit for $162 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/sports/baseball/mets-owners-pay-162-million-to-settle-madoff-suit.html |title=Mets' Owners Pay $162 Million to Settle Madoff Suit |accessdate=March 19, 2012 |date=March 19, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |first1=Richard |last1=Sandomir |first2=Ken |last2=Belson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320064540/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/sports/baseball/mets-owners-pay-162-million-to-settle-madoff-suit.html |archivedate=March 20, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Saul Katz==\n[[Saul Katz]], alongside Fred Wilpon, and other Sterling partners was sued by the Madoff trustee [[Irving Picard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=SECURITIES INVESTOR PROTECTION CORPORATION vs. BERNARD L. MADOFF INVESTMENT SECURITIES LLC |date= |website=}}</ref> Picard wrote of Katz: \"There are thousands of victims of Madoff\u2019s massive Ponzi scheme. But Saul Katz is not one of them.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/section/mlb/id/6090174|title=Madoff lawsuit: Mets owners owe victims $300M|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> Katz settled the accusations of willfully ignoring the Madoff fraud for $162 million thereby avoiding a federal trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-mets-idUSKCN0YN33E|title=N.Y. Mets owners reach revised deal with Madoff trustee|date=2016-06-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Greg Katz==\nGregory Katz, a Sterling Equities Partner alongside Fred Wilpon and Saul Katz, was sued by the Madoff trustee Irving Picard. Greg Katz was said to be intimately involved in Sterling\u2019s investments with Bernard L. Madoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/031811madoffwilpon.pdf|title=SECURITIES INVESTOR PROTECTION CORPORATION, vs BERNARD L. MADOFF INVESTMENT SECURITIES LLC,|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Katz opened his first Madoff account in January of 1992 and had interest in 31 accounts at the time the ponzi scheme was exposed to the public.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=Sterling Complaint|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Greg Katz was shown to have received approximately 23,527,313 in \"Fictitious Profits\" from individual or Sterling-controlled accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=Sterling Complaint|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Referring to Katz and other Sterling partners, Picard wrote: \"There are thousands of victims of Madoff\u2019s massive Ponzi scheme. But Saul Katz is not one of them. Neither is Fred Wilpon. And neither are the rest of the partners at Sterling Equities who, along with Fred Wilpon and Saul Katz, are sophisticated investors who oversee and control Sterling and its many businesses and investments.\" Picard also wrote that Sterling Partners such as Katz among the \"largest beneficiaries of Madoff\u2019s fraud.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Gregory Katz entered into a settlement agreement with the Madoff trustee Irving Picard in April 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/001734-katzwilponorder11-03605docket192.pdf|title=Madoff Katz Settlement|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Mark and Andrew Madoff==\nMadoff's sons Mark, 45, and Andrew, 42 worked in the trading arm in the New York office, but also raised money marketing the Madoff funds.<ref>{{cite web |author=Mike Greenlar / The Post Standard |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/how_warning_signs_eluded_berna.html |title=How warning signs eluded Bernard Madoff's man in Syracuse |publisher=Syracuse.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503015411/http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/how_warning_signs_eluded_berna.html |archivedate=May 3, 2009 |df=mdy-all |date=March 29, 2009 }}</ref>  Their assets were frozen on March 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last=Efrati |first=Amir |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123851832507274247 |title=Judge Freezes Assets of Madoff's Family - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110832/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123851832507274247 |archivedate=January 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Madoff has contended that his sons were not involved in the fraud, a claim backed up by his longtime secretary, Eleanor Squillari; she believes that if the sons were involved in the fraud, she would have known about it.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/> However, there is some skepticism about claims that Mark and Andrew were not in on the fraud.<ref name='vfairmargolick'>{{cite news | first=David | last=Margolick | authorlink=David Margolick | title=The Madoff Chronicles, Part III: Did the Sons Know | date=July 2009 | url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/07/madoff200907 | work=Vanity Fair | accessdate=June 25, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619110150/http://www.vanityfair.com//politics//features//2009//07//madoff200907 | archivedate=June 19, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nUntil their deaths, the two had been estranged from their father since December 10, 2008, when he revealed that he was running a Ponzi scheme. They had not spoken with their mother either, only communicating with her through lawyers.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nIn 1998, the sons became directors of the London office, Madoff Securities International Ltd. and took stakes in the business. They were given loans by the New York office to buy their shares. Interest on the loans was paid by dividends made by the London operation.  Andrew had several million dollars invested with his father at the time the fraud was revealed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123275697375711899 |title=Madoff Sons Are Scrutinized Over Contacts With Some at Investment Arm - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 23, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Aaron |last1=Lucchetti |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126064918/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123275697375711899 |archivedate=January 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nAt the time of Mark's divorce, in 2000, his interest in the London office was valued at $5 million. Other family members with shares in the London business were Bernard's wife, Ruth, and brother, Peter.\n<ref name=\"article3\"/>\n\nThe New York business paid Mark $770,000 in 1999 and rewarded him with a deferred-compensation plan valued at $5 million, but he withdrew his personal funds he had invested with his father's investment-advisory operation some time before his divorce. He remarried Stephanie in 2003 in [[Nantucket]].<ref name=\"currentpage1\"/>\n\nProsecutors intend to seize [[promissory note]]s given to the Madoffs by Andrew and Mark from 2001 to October 2008. Mark Madoff owed his parents $22 million, and Andrew Madoff owed $9.5 million. There were two loans in 2008 from Bernard Madoff to Andrew Madoff: $4.3 million on Oct 6, and $250,000 on Sept. 21.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg6\"/><ref name=\"usdoj.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/madoffbailpendingsentencing.pdf |title=Madoff Bail Pending Sentencing |website=[[American Association for Justice]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226062438/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/madoffbailpendingsentencing.pdf |archivedate=February 26, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in Bridgeport, Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing their assets. They agreed to attachments of $2.5 million each to their [[Greenwich]]{{clarify|reason=which Greenwich?|date=March 2015}} homes. The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn June 16, 2009, former employees Richard Stahl and Reed Abend, filed separate lawsuits against Madoff's sons claiming nearly $2 million in [[deferred compensation]]. Stahl, a former vice president at [[Cantor Fitzgerald]], claims $1.34 million for 2008, when he earned more than $5 million for Madoff Securities. Abend wants $473,940.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/06/17/2009-06-17_bernie_madoffs_sons_should_pay_two_traders_suits_charge.html | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Bernie Madoff's sons should pay, two traders' suits charge | first=Jose | last=Martinez | date=June 17, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620183626/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/06/17/2009-06-17_bernie_madoffs_sons_should_pay_two_traders_suits_charge.html | archivedate=June 20, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2009 a civil lawsuit was filed against them by trustee, Picard, for a judgment in the aggregate amount of at least, $198,743,299. Peter Madoff and daughter, Shana, are also defendants.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125451222667260197 |title=Madoff Trustee Sues Swindler's Family |last1=Lucchetti |first1=Aaron |last2=Forsyth |first2=Jennifer S. |date=October 3, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032605/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125451222667260197 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/Complaint.pdf |title=Complaint |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183010/http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/Complaint.pdf |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nOn March 15, 2010 the defendants filed a motion to dismiss, citing they were also victims, that lawsuit is \"predicated on the faulty assumption\" that the sons exercised a compliance function over the investment advisory business.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703734504575126013209903810 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Chad | last=Bray | title=Madoff Sons: We're Victims | date=March 17, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005165720/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703734504575126013209903810 | archivedate=October 5, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 2010, on the second anniversary of his father's arrest, Mark Madoff was found dead in his New York City apartment from an apparent suicide. It was later ruled suicide by hanging by a New York City medical examiner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/40617952/ns/business-us_business/|title=Madoff son's suicide follows battle with trustee|date=2010-12-13|access-date=2016-08-28|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829065410/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/40617952/ns/business-us_business|archivedate=August 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2013, a UK court dismissed a $40 million case against the directors of Madoff's British unit.  The directors included the deceased Mark Madoff and the critically ill Andrew Madoff, being treated for [[mantle cell lymphoma]] in Seattle at the time of the verdict.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/10/18/us-madoff-court-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 | work=Reuters | title=UK court dismisses case against directors of Madoff unit | date=October 18, 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129164158/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/10/18/us-madoff-court-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 | archivedate=November 29, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, 2014, Andrew Madoff died of [[mantle cell lymphoma]] at [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City. He was 48.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/03/andrew-madoff-dies/15015719/ | work=USA Today | title=Bernard Madoff's son, 48, dies in cancer battle | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117183338/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/03/andrew-madoff-dies/15015719/ | archivedate=November 17, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Jeffry Picower==\n[[Jeffry Picower]] was an industrialist and philanthropist who seemed to be a favored Madoff beneficiary, and made outlandish profits from his investments with Madoff.  From 1996\u20132007 there were 14 instances of greater than 100% yearly returns, and 25 of greater than 50%.  From 1996\u20131999 his regular trading account made from 120\u2013550% a year.  Some evidence of backdating trades, instituted by Picower, was presented by trustee [[Irving Picard]].  \n\nIn June 2009, [[Irving Picard]], the trustee liquidating Madoff's assets, filed a lawsuit against Picower in the [[United States bankruptcy court|U.S. Bankruptcy Court]] for the Southern District of New York (Manhattan), seeking the return of $7.2 billion in profits, alleging that Picower and his wife Barbara knew or should have known that their rates of return were \"implausibly high\", with some accounts showing annual returns ranging from 120% to more than 550% from 1996 through 1998, and 950% in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE54C4HW20090513 |title=Lawsuit claims Picower profits from Madoff $5 billion |author=Santosh Nadgir and Grant McCool |publisher=Reuters |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/13/business/13madoff.html|title=Billions Withdrawn Before Madoff Arrest|last=Henriques|first=Diana B.|last2=Kouwe|first2=Zachery|date=May 12, 2009|website=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref>  According to a June 28, 2009, [[MSNBC]] article, that would make Picower and his wife the biggest beneficiaries of Madoff's scam, exceeding even Madoff himself.<ref name=MSNBC>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31510209 |title=Madoff may not have benefited most in scam |publisher=[[NBC News]] |last=Bernstein |first=Jake |date=June 28, 2009 |accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> The Picowers' lawyer, William D. Zabel of Schulte Roth & Zabel, responded that, \"They were totally shocked by his fraud and were in no way complicit in it.\"<ref name=NYT2/> \n\nOn December 17, 2010, it was announced that a settlement of $7.2 billion had been reached between Irving Picard and Barbara Picower, Picower's widow, the executor of the Picower estate to resolve the Madoff trustee suit, and repay losses in the Madoff fraud.<ref name=autogenerated32>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704034804576025392596402176 \"Widow to Return $7.2 Billion\"]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.necn.com/news/new-england/_NECN__Madoff_Trustee_Gets__game_Changing__7_2_Billion_Settlement_NECN-251405161.html \"Madoff Trustee Gets 'game Changing' 7.2 Billion Settlement\" - NECN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It was the largest single forfeiture in American judicial history.<ref name=autogenerated22>[https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/17/big-settlement-with-madoff-investor-near/?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=F574E8492F5B58974037B4B91A067DD1&gwt=pay \"Madoff Trustee Recovers $7.2 Billion for Victims of Scheme\" - The New York Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/000040-09-01197d-order.pdf \"ORDER PURSUANT TO SECTION 105(a) OF THE BANKRUPTCY CODE AND RULES 2002 AND 9019 OF THE FEDERAL RULES OF BANKRUPTCY PROCEDURE APPROVING AN AGREEMENT BY AND AMONG THE TRUSTEE AND THE PICOWER BLMIS ACCOUNT HOLDERS AND ISSUING A PERMANENT INJUNCTION\"]</ref>  \"Barbara Picower has done the right thing,\" US Attorney [[Preet Bharara]] said.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/madoff-client-jeffry-picower-netted-5-billion |title=Madoff Client Jeffry Picower Netted $5 Billion\u2014Likely More Than Madoff Himself |publisher=ProPublica |date=June 23, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208222252/http://www.propublica.org/article/madoff-client-jeffry-picower-netted-5-billion |archivedate=February 8, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Picower died before the settlement.\n\n==Frank DiPascali==\n[[Frank DiPascali]], 52, who referred to himself as \"director of [[option (finance)|option]]s trading\" and as \"[[chief financial officer]]\" at Madoff Securities, pleaded guilty  on August 11, 2009, to 10 counts:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/DiPascali,%20Frank%20Charges%20Chart.pdf |title=DiPascali, Frank Charges Chart |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411181741/http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/DiPascali,%20Frank%20Charges%20Chart.pdf |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]], [[securities fraud]], investment advisor [[fraud]], [[mail fraud]], [[wire fraud]], [[perjury]], [[income tax evasion]], international [[money laundering]], falsifying books and records of a broker-dealer and an investment advisor. In his allocution to the Court, he admitted that he had known for at least two decades that Madoff was a fraud; he claimed to have learned in the late 1980s or early 1990s that no actual trading was occurring in Madoff's investment-advisory client accounts. About 2002, he set up an account for himself at the firm named after his fishing yacht, Dorothy Jo. Having never made a contribution, he withdrew more than $5 million. His salary and bonuses were over $2 million annually. He agreed in a [[Plea bargain|plea agreement]] and the signed Information document<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf |title=DiPascali Information - Signed |website=[[American Association for Justice]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609135048/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf |archivedate=June 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/081109DiPascaliplea.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=DiPascali Plea |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165331/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/081109DiPascaliplea.pdf |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> to connect the dots and to name names, with sentencing originally anticipated in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Blotter/Madoff/story?id=8304447&page=1 |title=Frank DiPascali Pleads Guilty, Bernard Madoff's Accomplice \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=August 11, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515090821/http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/Madoff/story?id=8304447&page=1 |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He faced a maximum of 125 years in prison. Prosecutors sought more than $170 million in forfeiture, the same amount sought from Madoff, which represents about double the funds deposited by investors and later disbursed to other investors. The same day, a [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] civil complaint<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SEC2009-182.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=SEC CHARGES KEY MADOFF LIEUTENANT FOR OPERATING AND CONCEALING FRAUD THROUGH BOGUS TRADES AND DOCUMENTS |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005010430/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SEC2009-182.pdf |archivedate=October 5, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> was filed against DiPascali.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124999709846222617 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first1=Chad |last1=Bray |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |title='All Fake': Key Madoff Executive Admits Guilt |date=August 12, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223220308/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124999709846222617 |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA college dropout, he joined Madoff's firm in 1975 at age 18 and eventually oversaw the day-to-day operations of Madoff's investment-advisory business.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> He was the person many of Madoff's investors dealt with regarding their accounts.  Madoff told investors DiPascali executed trades. However, a court-appointed trustee found that no trading had occurred for at least 13 years. Prosecutors have asked at least three employees, Eric Lipkin, JoAnn Crupi, and Robert Cardile, who is Mr. DiPascali's brother-in-law, about his role in the firm.<ref name=\"30909Wsj\"/>\nInvestors spoke to these other employees and would fax orders if they needed to withdraw money. DiPascali's name was sometimes given as an alternate contact.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123249539137500157 |title=Madoff's Point Man Is Cast in Same Role for Prosecutors |date=January 21, 2009 |accessdate=March 25, 2009 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first1=Aaron |last1=Lucchetti |first2=Amir |last2=Efrati |first3=Tom |last3=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716030328/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123249539137500157 |archivedate=July 16, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to an SEC memo, DiPascali \"responded evasively\" to questioning following Madoff's arrest.<ref name=\"1223WsjA\">{{cite news | last =Efrati | first =Amir | author2 =Aaron Lucchetti | author3 =Tom Lauricella | title =Probe Eyes Audit Files, Role of Aide To Madoff | work =[[The Wall Street Journal]] | publisher =[[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] | date =December 23, 2008 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122999256957528605 | accessdate =December 23, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150521234747/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122999256957528605 | archivedate =May 21, 2015 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, at a court hearing, he gave detailed information how Madoff was meticulous in the management of the fraud.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/12/07/madoff-sweated-scam-details/3890069/ Madoff sweated scam details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809134721/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/12/07/madoff-sweated-scam-details/3890069/ |date=August 9, 2017 }} USA Today, December 7, 2013</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2015, while still awaiting sentencing, DiPascali died of lung cancer.<ref>{{cite news | title=Former Madoff Aide Frank DiPascali Dies at Age 58 of Lung Cancer | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-madoff-aide-frank-dipascali-dies-at-age-58-of-lung-cancer-1431361169 | author=Yang, Stephanie | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=May 11, 2015 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604045956/http://www.wsj.com/articles/former-madoff-aide-frank-dipascali-dies-at-age-58-of-lung-cancer-1431361169 | archivedate=June 4, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Enrica Cotellessa-Pitz==\nEnrica Cotellessa-Pitz, was a [[Comptroller|controller]] at Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities LLC, but not a licensed [[Certified Public Accountant|certified public accountant]]. Her signature is on checks from BMIS to [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp. representing commission payments. She was the liaison between the SEC and BLMIS regarding the firm's financial statements. The SEC has removed the BMIS statements from its website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-why-is-enrica-co.php |title=Bernie Madoff: Why Is Bernie's Controller, Enrica Cotellessa-Pitz, Getting A Pass In The Press? |date=May 11, 2009 |website=Mrs Panstreppon's Blog |publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515125348/http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-why-is-enrica-co.php |archivedate=May 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Madoff backroom staff==\nIn 2010 five backroom employees pleaded not guilty to charges including conspiracy to commit securities fraud. On October 2, 2012 they maintained their innocence to further charges including bank fraud and tax offenses.<ref name=\"westlaw\">{{cite web |url=https://content.next.westlaw.com/Document/I6a91a730877511e293329f3d310cb5cf/View/FullText.html |title=Former Madoff aide seeks release of funds for his defense |last=Vaughan |first=Bernard |date=March 7, 2013 |website=[[Westlaw]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-access=registration}}</ref> Their trial (USA v O'Hara et al. in U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, No. 10-0228) opened on October 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-employees-trial/judge-sets-october-2013-trial-date-for-ex-madoff-backroom-staff-idUSL1E8L2FQK20121002 |title=Judge sets October 2013 trial date for ex-Madoff backroom staff |last=McCool |first=Grant |date=October 2, 2012 |website=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |quote={{blist|Five ex-Madoff employees face additional charges|All plead not guilty to allegations of role in fraud}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033647/https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-employees-trial/judge-sets-october-2013-trial-date-for-ex-madoff-backroom-staff-idUSL1E8L2FQK20121002 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Annette Bongiorno===\nAnnette Bongiorno was a long-time personal secretary and aide to Madoff. Bongiorno joined Madoff Investment Securities in 1967, soon after graduating high school; only Madoff's wife Ruth and brother Peter were at the firm longer. She recruited Frank DiPascali, then her next-door neighbor in [[Howard Beach]], to the firm.<ref name=MadoffChronicles>{{cite book|title=The Madoff Chronicles|last=Ross|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist)|publisher=[[Disney Publishing Worldwide|Kingswell]]|year=2015|isbn=9781484781401}}</ref>\n\nShe is accused of directing two assistants, Semone Anderson and Winnie Jackson, to generate fictitious trading tickets for customer accounts.<ref name=\"30909Wsj\">{{cite news | last =Efrati | first =Amir | title =Madoff Aide Allegedly Got Fake 'Tickets' of Trading | work =[[The Wall Street Journal]] | publisher =[[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] | date =March 9, 2009 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123655521154265891 | accessdate =March 9, 2009 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20160310201425/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123655521154265891 | archivedate =March 10, 2016 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"030909Street\">{{cite news | last =Woefel | first =Joseph | title =Madoff Aide Allegedly Got Fake Trading 'Tickets' | work =[[TheStreet.com]] | date =March 9, 2009 | url =http://www.thestreet.com/story/10469058/1/madoff-aide-allegedly-got-fake-trading-tickets.html?cm_ven=GOOGLEN | accessdate =March 9, 2009 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090312081858/http://www.thestreet.com/story/10469058/1/madoff-aide-allegedly-got-fake-trading-tickets.html?cm_ven=GOOGLEN | archivedate =March 12, 2009 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\nDuring the 1980s, Bongiorno recruited small investors from Howard Beach. Their money was held in accounts called \"RuAnn\" (named after Annette and her husband Rudy).  Madoff paid for her honeymoon airfare. She owns homes in [[Manhasset, New York]], and [[Boca Raton, Florida]], with a combined assessment of $3.85 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=auoogFU4GmKc&refer=home |title=Madoff Key Aide Recruited Her Neighbors as Investors (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=February 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525071928/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109 |archivedate=May 25, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/03/25/2009-03-25_bernie_madoffs_secretary_comes_away_with.html |title=Bernie Madoff's secretary comes away with mansions and Mercedes |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=New York |first=Tracy |last=Connor |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328091853/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/03/25/2009-03-25_bernie_madoffs_secretary_comes_away_with.html |archivedate=March 28, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nBongiorno was arrested in November 2010 and charged with conspiracy, securities fraud, and tax evasion.  She faced up to 75 years in jail.<ref name=\"wsjnov2010\">{{cite news | last = Hurtado | first = Patricia | title = Ex-Madoff Employee Bongiorno Unable to Post Bail, Must Remain in Custody | work = [[Bloomberg.com]] | publisher = Bloomberg | date = November 23, 2010 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/ex-madoff-employee-bongiorno-unable-to-post-bail-must-remain-in-custody.html | accessdate = November 23, 2010 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101127005529/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/ex-madoff-employee-bongiorno-unable-to-post-bail-must-remain-in-custody.html | archivedate = November 27, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  After a brief incarceration in late 2010 and after $7.6 million were seized from Bongiornos' accounts (out of an estimated $14 million personal take), Bongiorno was released to house arrest with ankle monitor at her Manhasset, Long Island, residence on a $3.6 million personal recognizance bond secured by eight co-signers.<ref name=\"dailybeast20110107\">{{cite news| last=Dodds Frank| first=Allan| title=Bernie Madoff's Secretary Annette Bongiorno Out on Bail| date=January 7, 2011| url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/01/07/bernie-madoffs-secretary-annete-bongiorno-out-on-bail.html| accessdate=March 15, 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318205443/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/01/07/bernie-madoffs-secretary-annete-bongiorno-out-on-bail.html| archivedate=March 18, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Her trial opened on October 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> In a bid for leniency, Bongiorno maintained that Madoff deceived her into printing bogus trade records.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2014/dec/09/madoff-secretary-six-years-prison-fraud|title='Compliant' Madoff secretary gets six years in prison over fraud scheme|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2014-12-09}}</ref> She claimed that she was merely doing the same thing she had been doing for over 40 years\u2013bolstering evidence that Madoff began his Ponzi scheme far earlier than 1991.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nBongiorno was convicted in March 2014 on charges of securities fraud and tax evasion. In December 2014, Bongiorno was sentenced to six years in federal prison. The sentence was far shorter than even the eight- to ten-year sentence recommended by her own lawyer. However, federal judge [[Laura Taylor Swain]] believed Bongiorno's \"small stature\"\u2013she is only {{convert|4.5|ft|m}} tall\u2013would put her in a \"vulnerable position\" in prison.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/09/madoff-secretary-gets-6-years-after-judge-cites-small-stature/ | work=New York Post | first=Rich | last=Calder | title=Madoff secretary gets 6 years after judge cites 'small stature' | date=December 9, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018015702/http://nypost.com/2014/12/09/madoff-secretary-gets-6-years-after-judge-cites-small-stature/ | archivedate=October 18, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Daniel Bonventre===\n[[Daniel Bonventre]] worked as company director of operations and as an accountant for Madoff since the 1960s. He was arrested in 2010 and charged with allegedly having created false and fraudulent books and records, conspiracy, securities fraud, and tax-related charges. He is also being sued by the SEC for falsifying records. On those initial charges he may be sentenced to a maximum of 77 years in prison if convicted. In Dec 2012 Bonventre's request for access to his seized funds for legal defense purposes was turned down by U.S. District Court. In March 2013 a three-judge appeals court granted a hearing in a lower court on his seized funds access request.<ref name=\"westlaw\" /> His trial opened on October 7, 2013 .<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> On December 8, 2014, Bonventre was sentenced to 10 years in prison after being convicted on securities fraud and tax-evasion charges for his involvement in Madoff's $17.5 billion fraud.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-08/madoff-ex-operations-chief-bonventre-given-10-years.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Erik | last=Larson | title=Madoff Aide Gets a Sentencing Break for Not Being Madoff | date=December 8, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230042829/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-08/madoff-ex-operations-chief-bonventre-given-10-years.html | archivedate=December 30, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Joann Crupi===\nJoann Crupi is a former investment advisor to Madoff. Her trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> A jury found her guilty, and on December 15, 2014 Crupi was sentenced to 6 years in prison for her role in the scam.<ref name=\"nyp20141216\">{{cite news |last=Neumeister |first=Larry |date=December 16, 2014 |title=Former Madoff account manager sentenced to six years |url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/16/former-madoff-account-manager-sentenced-to-six-years/ |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018015659/http://nypost.com/2014/12/16/former-madoff-account-manager-sentenced-to-six-years/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===George Perez===\nGeorge Perez is a former computer programmer of Madoff. His trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> A jury found him guilty, and on December 10, 2014 Perez was sentenced to 2\u00bd years in prison for his role in the scam.<ref name=\"usat20141211\">{{cite news |last=McCoy |first=Kevin |date=December 11, 2014 |title=Leniency for ex-Madoff staffer sparks complaint |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/12/10/madoff-george-perez-sentencing/19967501/ |work=[[USA Today]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222095147/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/12/10/madoff-george-perez-sentencing/19967501/ |archivedate=December 22, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Jerome O'Hara===\nJerome O'Hara is a former computer programmer of Madoff. His trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> On December 9, 2014, he was sentenced to 2 1/2 years in prison for his role in the scam.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/09/us-madoff-workers-sentencing-idUSKBN0JN20420141209 | work=Reuters | title=Ex-Madoff manager, computer programmer get prison terms | date=December 9, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211339/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/09/us-madoff-workers-sentencing-idUSKBN0JN20420141209 | archivedate=September 24, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sosnik Bell and Co.==\nEven before Sosnik and Bell took over a small [[New Jersey]] accounting firm in the early 1990s, Madoff and his affiliate, Cohmad Securities, encouraged hundreds of individual investors to retain the firm for an annual fee of $800 for routine [[Records management|recordkeeping]] to handle their monthly statements. The firm compiled profits, losses, and gains, and prepared tax-summary statements and schedules to be used by a client's regular accountant for [[income tax]] returns, producing one-page monthly statements and a quarterly statement.<ref name=\"article2\"/>\n\n==Fairfield Greenwich Group==\n[[Fairfield Greenwich Group]], based in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]], had a \"Fairfield Sentry\" fund which was one of many feeder funds that gave investors portals to Madoff.  Fairfield, in turn, set up further feeder funds such as \"Lion Fairfield Capital Management\" in [[Singapore]] and \"Stellar US Absolute Return,\" all conduits to Madoff, directing a total of $7.5 billion.<ref name=\"1219NYTmad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/20/business/20madoff.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 20, 2008 |title=Madoff Scheme Kept Rippling Outward, Across Borders |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |first=Diana B. |last=Henriques |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409233032/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/20/business/20madoff.html |archivedate=April 9, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMadoff was able to pitch his business in Europe and South America indirectly through Fairfield fund's founder, [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Walter Noel and Family|Walter Noel]]'s son-in-law Andr\u00e9s Piedrahita.<ref name=\"l'affaire madoff\">{{cite news | last =Schwartz | first =Nelson D. | title =Madoff Dealings Tarnish a Private Swiss Bank | work =[[The New York Times]] | date =December 24, 2008 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/24/business/worldbusiness/24ubp.html | accessdate =December 23, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130621035330/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/24/business/worldbusiness/24ubp.html | archivedate =June 21, 2013 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> Another Noel son-in-law's territory included Asia.  Madoff began advertising openly, contrary to his initial strategy of handpicking investors.<ref name=\"1219NYTmad\" />  The company is listed as a defendant in an investor lawsuit filed in [[Miami]].<ref name=\"article2\"/>\n\nIn August 2008, [[JPMorgan Chase]],  pulled $250 million from this Madoff feeder fund account.  Chase had become \"concerned about lack of transparency,\" and due-diligence  which had \"raised doubts\" about Madoff's operation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chew |first=Robert |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1887338,00.html |title=Madoff's Banker: Where Was JPMorgan Chase? |publisher=TIME |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428114723/http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1887338,00.html |archivedate=April 28, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] filed a civil action charging Fairfield Greenwich with fraud,  breaching its fiduciary duty to clients by failing to provide promised due diligence on its investments.  The complaint seeks a fine and restitution to Massachusetts investors for losses and disgorgement of performance fees paid to Fairfield by those investors. It alleges that in 2005 Mr. Madoff coached Fairfield staff about ways to answer questions from SEC attorneys who were looking into [[Harry Markopolos]]' complaint about Madoff's operations.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctfairfield/fairfieldidx.htm |title=Securities: Fairfield Greenwich |publisher=Sec.state.ma.us |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123859307450378115?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Madoff Feeder Is Charged in Fraud - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 | first1=Robert | last1=Frank | first2=Tom | last2=Lauricella}}</ref>  The Secretary of State has no plans to settle the lawsuit in spite of the fact that Fairfield Greenwich has offered to repay all Massachusetts investors, and is expected to force Fairfield to explain [[e-mails]] and other evidence he has uncovered that appear to show company officials knew about potential problems with Madoff but failed to disclose them to clients.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.boston.com/business/articles/2009/08/14/galvin_wont_settle_madoff_case/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Galvin won't settle Madoff case | first=Beth | last=Healy | date=August 14, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004234410/http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2009/08/14/galvin_wont_settle_madoff_case/ | archivedate=October 4, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE57D3X820090814 | work=Reuters | title=Mass. regulator will not settle Madoff feeder suit | date=August 14, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817165519/http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE57D3X820090814 | archivedate=August 17, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing Noel's and Tucker's assets. Noel agreed to attachments of $10 million to his Greenwich home, and $2 million from Jeffrey Tucker.  Noel's attorney is Glenn Kurtz, and Tucker's is Stanley Tawdry, Jr..  The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn May 18, 2009, the hedge fund was sued by bankruptcy trustee, [[Irving Picard]].  The complaint seeks a return of $3.2 billion during the period from 2002 \u2013 Madoff's arrest in December 2008.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/19/business/19madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Hedge Funds Over Losses to Madoff | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=May 19, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005112727/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/19/business/19madoff.html | archivedate=October 5, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, the money may already be in the hands of Fairfield's own clients, who are likely off-limits to Picard, since they weren't direct investors with Madoff.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2009/05/19/picards-latest-a-huge-lawsuit-against-fairfield-greenwich/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Picard's Latest: A Huge Lawsuit Against Fairfield Greenwich | first=Ashby | last=Jones | date=May 19, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812070718/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2009/05/19/picards-latest-a-huge-lawsuit-against-fairfield-greenwich/ | archivedate=August 12, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2009, Fairfield Sentry, based in the British Virgin Islands, filed a lawsuit seeking to recover more than $919 million in investment management and performance fees that it paid to Fairfield.  The lawsuit alleges breach of [[fiduciary]] duty, and [[unjust enrichment]]. It is \"the largest victim of the fraud perpetrated by Bernard L. Madoff,\" losing $7 billion.\nThe defendants include founders [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Walter Noel and Family|Walter Noel]] and [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Jeffrey Tucker|Jeffrey Tucker]] and other fund partners who the plaintiffs allege \"failed to fulfill their contractual obligations to use best efforts to supervise the operations\" of Madoff-related investments and to \"oversee the day-to-day investment activities of the fund.\"  The case is Fairfield Sentry Ltd. v. Fairfield Greenwich Group, 601687/2009, New York State Supreme Court (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aM2myGLTkcBQ&refer=home | work=Bloomberg | title=Fairfield Greenwich Asks to Dismiss Suits Over Madoff (Update2) | date=December 23, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 | archivedate=June 13, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2009, Justice Edward Alexander Bannister granted the request to liquidate the Fairfield Sentry funds, worth more than $7.2 billion in December 2008, now less than $70 million, incorporated in 1990 under the mutual fund statutes of the British Virgin Islands and technically under the control of their local directors.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/22/business/22madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Judge Approves Liquidation of Madoff Feeder Funds | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=July 22, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001063730/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/22/business/22madoff.html | archivedate=October 1, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sonja Kohn==\nOn December 10, 2010, [[Irving Picard]] sued [[Sonja Kohn]] and her bank, [[Bank Medici]], for $58.8 billion, accusing Kohn of being a \"criminal soul mate\" of [[Bernard Madoff|Madoff]].  She was accused of directing $9.1 billion to Madoff's fraud, about half of the actual money lost.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/madoff-trustee-sues-sonja-kohn-for-19-6-billion-treble-damages-via-rico.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Bob | last=Van Voris | title=Madoff Firm Trustee Seeks $50 Billion as Clawback Window Closes | date=December 13, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215204342/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/madoff-trustee-sues-sonja-kohn-for-19-6-billion-treble-damages-via-rico.html | archivedate=December 15, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/madoff-trustee-seeks-19-6-billion-from-austrian-banker/?hp | work=The New York Times | first1=Diana B. | last1=Henriques | first2=Peter | last2=Lattman | title=Madoff Trustee Seeks $19.6 Billion From Austrian Banker | date=December 10, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033037/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/madoff-trustee-seeks-19-6-billion-from-austrian-banker/?hp | archivedate=October 20, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 18, 2013 Kohn was found innocent of the civil charges leveled against her by the High Court in London and thus relieved of any liability to the Madoff creditors.<ref name=\"reuters20131018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-court/uk-court-dismisses-case-against-directors-of-madoff-unit-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 |title=UK court dismisses case against directors of Madoff unit |last1=Fletcher |first1=Laurence |last2=Shirbon |first2=Estelle |date=October 18, 2013 |editor-last=Holmes |editor-first=David |website=[[Reuters]] |location=London |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033529/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-court/uk-court-dismisses-case-against-directors-of-madoff-unit-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==J. Ezra Merkin==\n[[J. Ezra Merkin]], a prominent [[Financial adviser|investment advisor]] and philanthropist, has been sued for his role in running a \"feeder fund\" for Madoff.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Chad |date=17 December 2008 |title=GMAC's Merkin, Ascot Fund sued over Madoff investments |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/gmacs-merkin-ascot-fund-sued-over-madoff-investments |work=MarketWatch |location=New York |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> Merkin informed investors in his $1.8 billion [[Ascot Partners]] fund on December 11 that he was among those who suffered substantial personal losses, since all of the fund's money was invested with Madoff.<ref name=\"NYTAscot\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/20081216_MERKIN.pdf|title=Letter from Merkin to Investors|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 19, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114200414/http://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/20081216_MERKIN.pdf|archivedate=January 14, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Connecticut]] [[Attorney general|Attorney General]] [[Richard Blumenthal]] is examining the role boards of nonprofits played, in possibly not conducting due diligence on donors' contributions.<ref name=\"ct nonprofit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/wallstreet/2008/12/22/madoff-blumenthal-charities-biz-wall-cz_cc_1222charities.html?partner=contextstory|title=Blumenthal May Investigate Charities Ripped Off By Madoff|date=December 22, 2008|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=December 24, 2008|first=Carrie|last=Coolidge|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130123095253/http://www.forbes.com/2008/12/22/madoff-blumenthal-charities-biz-wall-cz_cc_1222charities.html?partner=contextstory|archivedate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2009, New York Attorney General [[Andrew Cuomo]] filed civil [[fraud]] charges<ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Complaint - Final |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307143258/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against J. Ezra Merkin  alleging he \"betrayed hundreds of investors\" by moving $2.4 billion of clients' money to Bernard Madoff without their knowledge.  The complaint states, he lied about putting the money with Madoff, failed to disclose conflicts of interest, and collected over $470 million in fees for his three hedge funds, Ascot Partners LP with Ascot Fund Ltd., Gabriel Capital Corp. and Ariel Fund Ltd.  He promised he would actively manage the money, but instead, he misguided investors about his Madoff investments in quarterly reports, in investor presentations, and in conversations with investors. \"Merkin held himself out to investors as an investing guru...In reality, Merkin was but a master marketer.\"<ref name=civilfraud1>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-merkin/merkin-charged-with-civil-fraud-in-madoff-case-idUSTRE53548420090406 |title=Merkin charged with civil fraud in Madoff case |last1=Graybow |first1=Martha |last2=Chasan |first2=Emily |date=April 6, 2009 |editor-last=Moss |editor-first=Brian |website=[[Reuters]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905235040/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-merkin/merkin-charged-with-civil-fraud-in-madoff-case-idUSTRE53548420090406 |archivedate=September 5, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf |title=Merkin Exhibits (1/3) |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604042707/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Exhibits (2/3) |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604044008/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Exhibits (3/3) |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604042648/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the complaint accused Merkin of improperly commingling his personal funds with his hedge fund accounts and using some of the money to buy artwork worth more than $91 million. Mr. Cuomo's office is seeking restitution and unspecified damages from Mr. Merkin.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/07/business/07madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Cuomo Sues Over Madoff Investments | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=April 7, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616172623/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/07/business/07madoff.html | archivedate=June 16, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2009, Madoff Bankruptcy Trustee, [[Irving Picard]] filed a lawsuit<ref>{{cite news |url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf |work=The New York Times |title=Madoff_Complaint |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616181923/http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf |archivedate=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against Merkin seeking to recover almost $500 million withdrawn from Madoff accounts in the last six years. The complaint alleges that since 1995, Merkin steered more than $1 billion to Madoff through three private hedge funds, Ascot Partners, Ariel Fund and Gabriel Capital. Since 2002, the funds withdrew at least $494 million from Madoff \u2014 returns that Merkin \"knew or should have known\" were fraudulent.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/08/business/08madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Madoff Hedge Fund Investor | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=May 8, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616072434/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/08/business/08madoff.html | archivedate=June 16, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of May 18, 2009, Merkin's control of Ascot, Gabriel and Ariel hedge funds are to be placed into [[receivership]] for [[liquidation]] by Guidepost Partners. One receiver will be responsible for managing the remaining money, nearly $1 billion, in the Gabriel and Ariel funds, and another will be responsible for overseeing Ascot, whose entire $1.8 billion in assets was lost to Madoff's Ponzi scheme.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124274106281334617 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Merkin to Put Funds in Receivership | date=May 20, 2009 | first=Liz | last=Rappaport | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217111859/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124274106281334617 | archivedate=December 17, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Cohmad Securities Corp.==\n[[Cohmad Securities]], whose name combines \"Cohn\" and \"Madoff,\" founded in 1985 by Madoff and Cohn, Madoff's friend and former neighbor.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=amvc1G6COZes | work=Bloomberg | title=Madoff Bankruptcy Trustee Sues Cohmad Securities (Update2) | date=June 22, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 | archivedate=June 13, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn owned 48% of Cohmad, and his daughter  Marcia, who served as president and chief compliance officer owned 25%.  Madoff owned 15%. Mr. Madoff's brother, Peter owned 9%, and Mr. Cohn's brother owned 1%, and another unnamed Cohmad employee owned 1%.\n<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124568875235837661#articleTabs%3Darticle |title=SEC Files Fraud Charges Against Cohmad, Co-Founder in Madoff Case |last1=Scannell |first1=Kara |last2=Frank |first2=Robert |date=June 23, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032737/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124568875235837661#articleTabs%3Darticle |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe brokerage firm lists its address as Madoff's firm's address in New York City. Cohmad employs [[Robert Jaffe (stockbroker)|Robert Jaffe]], as vice president.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123189380284379481?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Cohmad, Jaffe Draw Closer Look - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 14, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Robert |last1=Frank |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |first3=Aaron |last3=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206185751/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123189380284379481?mod=googlenews_wsj |archivedate=February 6, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Jaffe is married to Ellen Shapiro, daughter of Boston philanthropist [[Carl J. Shapiro]], the founder and former chairman of apparel company Kay Windsor Inc., and an early investor and close friend of Madoff.  Jaffe reportedly convinced the elder Shapiro to invest $250 million with Madoff just 10 days before Madoff's arrest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/localnews/content/local_news/epaper/2008/12/20/a1a_jaffe_1221.html |title=Scandal sullies Robert Jaffe as feds probe ties to Bernard Madoff |last=Musgrave |first=Jane |date=December 20, 2008 |website=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110617003417/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/localnews/content/local_news/epaper/2008/12/20/a1a_jaffe_1221.html |archivedate=June 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nJaffe, a philanthropist, \"worked the [[Palm Beach, Florida]] circuit, and attracted many Palm Beach Country Club members as investors.\"<ref name=\"Vics1\">{{cite news | last =Frank | first =Robert | author2 =Peter Lattman | author3 =Dionne Searcey | author4 =Aaron Lucucchetti | title =Fund Fraud Hits Big Names; Madoff's Clients Included Mets Owner, GMAC Chairman, Country-Club Recruits | work =[[Wall Street Journal]] | date =December 13, 2008 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122914169719104017?mod=djemalertNEWS | accessdate =December 13, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170806062445/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122914169719104017?mod=djemalertNEWS | archivedate =August 6, 2017 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> Jaffe brought in 150 accounts and more than $1 billion to Madoff.  Madoff paid Jaffe directly through accounts he kept with Madoff at much higher returns than earned by other investors. Between 1996 and 2008, Jaffe withdrew at least $150 million, and the SEC claims he was aware Madoff was engaged in fictitious trading.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>  Jaffe has said he received a commission of 1% to 2% from an investor's first profit, and he paid commissions to financial advisers who steered cash to Madoff's fund.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5562935.ece |title=Madoff associate skips court hearing \u2013 Times Online |publisher=Business.timesonline.co.uk |date=January 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=London |first=Christine |last=Seib |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612101142/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5562935.ece |archivedate=June 12, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.muckety.com/2009/01/15/cohmad-securities-robert-jaffe-face-tough-questions-about-madoff-ties/10151 |title=Cohmad Securities, Robert Jaffe face tough questions about Madoff ties &#124; Muckety.com \u2013 See the news |publisher=News.muckety.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430120644/http://news.muckety.com/2009/01/15/cohmad-securities-robert-jaffe-face-tough-questions-about-madoff-ties/10151 |archivedate=April 30, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRichard Spring, of [[Boca Raton, Florida]], received payments from Cohmad for many years in exchange for bringing investors and investment ideas to Madoff.\n\nAlvin J. \"Sonny\" Delaire, Jr. of [[Far Hills, New Jersey]] also recruited clients for Madoff's advisory business.  Delaire has been sued by Dr. Martin and Suzanne Schulman of [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]], New York, claiming they were induced by Delaire to make investments with Madoff \"based on fraudulent misrepresentations by Delaire and his omissions to disclose material facts.\"  The lawsuit seeks a minimum of $9.6 million in damages since 2002 from Delaire.\nThe case is Martin Schulman, M.D. and Suzanne Schulman v Alvin J. Delaire, Jr. 09-3871[[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/managementIssues/idUSN1746032320090417 |title=U.S. investors sue Madoff-linked broker for fraud |publisher=Reuters |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009215352/http://www.reuters.com/article/managementIssues/idUSN1746032320090417 |archivedate=October 9, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCohmad had fewer than 650 client accounts, and made 99.7% of its sales from brokerage services to Madoff's larger broker-dealer.  In its audited financial statements for the 12 months ending June 30, 2008, Cohmad said revenue from Madoff Securities totaled $3,736,829.  Its total sales for the same period were $3,748,397.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muckety.com/Cohmad-Securities/5058711.muckety|title=Cohmad Securities at Muckety.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321100955/http://www.muckety.com/Cohmad-Securities/5058711.muckety|archivedate=March 21, 2009|df=mdy-all|access-date=April 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2009, [[William F. Galvin]], [[Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts]], who is in charge of the state's securities issues, filed suit against Jaffe, who promoted Madoff's funds to wealthy investors in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/general/view/2009_01_15_William_Galvin_sues_salesman_Robert_Jaffe:_Demands_testimony/srvc=business&position=recent_bullet |title=William Galvin Sues Salesman Robert Jaffe \u2013 Demands Testimony |date=January 15, 2009 |website=[[Boston Herald]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224010342/http://bostonherald.com/business/general/view/2009_01_15_William_Galvin_sues_salesman_Robert_Jaffe%3A_Demands_testimony/srvc%3Dbusiness%26position%3Drecent_bullet |archivedate=February 24, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On February 4, compelled to testify, Jaffe invoked his [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] right.  Marcia Cohn, Maurice Cohn, and Alvin Delaire, Jr. failed to appear. On February 11, 2009, Galvin filed a complaint<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf |title=Cohmand Securities Complaint |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211040/http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |website=William Francis Galvin, Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts}}</ref> seeking to revoke the Massachusetts license of Cohmad Securities Corp., an accounting of all Massachusetts investors Cohmad referred to Madoff's company, all the fees it earned doing so (more than $67 million), and a fine.  It cited $526,000 in referral fees paid from Madoff Investments, to Cohmad, to Vienna [[Bank Medici]] majority owner, [[Sonja Kohn]], which she subsequently denied.<ref name=\"business1\"/><ref name=\"marketsnews1\"/> On May 28, 2009, Bank Medici lost its Austrian banking license. Kohn and the Bank are under investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124351941925862619 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Madoff-Hit Bank Medici Loses License | date=May 28, 2009 | first=Flemming E. | last=Hansen | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127064946/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124351941925862619 | archivedate=January 27, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2009, the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] found the firm to be in \"default\" for not assisting regulators.  Cohmad's securities registration has been revoked, and they must provide an accounting of all fees the company or its agents earned for referring Massachusetts investors to Mr. Madoff's firm as well as, pay a $100,000 fine for failing to cooperate with the state securities investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124179163909400903 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Madoff-Tied Brokerage Loses Its Registration | date=May 9, 2009 | first=Robert | last=Frank | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311063346/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124179163909400903 | archivedate=March 11, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2009, Federal prosecutors filed a notice in federal court declaring its intent to seek the forfeiture of the Madoffs' interests in Cohmad Securities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/16/government-files-notice-seeking-madoff-assets/ |title=Government Files Notice Seeking Madoff Assets - DealBook Blog - NYTimes.com |publisher=Dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523193646/http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/16/government-files-notice-seeking-madoff-assets/ |archivedate=May 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, Madoff Trustee, [[Irving Picard]] filed a claim against Cohmad, founder Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn, daughter Marcia Cohn, and Robert Jaffe, among more than two dozen individuals and trusts in [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]] in New York. The lawsuit claims that up to 90 percent of Cohmad's income came from referring clients and that the firm had a \"symbiotic\" relationship with Madoff, having earned hundreds of millions of dollars from the fraud.  The lawsuit seeks more than $100 million paid to Cohmad six years prior to Madoff's firm declaring bankruptcy, and more than $105 million in profits Cohmad employees and their families withdrew from the investment accounts they held with Madoff.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/><ref name=\"bloomberg3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a81_r.GbN1_4 | work=Bloomberg | title=Cohmad's Jaffe Seeks Dismissal of SEC, Picard Counts (Update1) | date=August 21, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224028/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103 | archivedate=January 22, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) also filed civil fraud charges\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Cohmad Complaint 2009-06-22 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109112821/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against co-founder Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn, president Marcia Cohn, and Robert Jaffe. The lawsuit alleges the company was Madoff's \"in-house marketing arm\" and critical to Madoff's scam. Cohmad representatives were paid for funds they brought into the firm but not for any increase in the investments' value. Withdrawals were treated as a loss, which \"suggested that profits generated by Madoff were fictitious\", although  Madoff changed the arrangement for Maurice Cohn in 2002, to pay him a flat $2 million a year.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nJaffe has filed requests with the Courts to dismiss the SEC and the Picard cases.  The cases are Picard v. Cohmad Securities Corp., 09-AP- 1305, [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]], [[Southern District of New York]] (Manhattan), and SEC v. Cohmad, 09-cv-5680, U.S. District Court, (Southern District of New York.).<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/><ref name=\"bloomberg3\"/>\n\n==Stanley Chais, the Brighton Company==\n[[Stanley Chais]] was a wealthy investment advisor from [[Beverly Hills, California]], who was accused of steering money to private interests, including Madoff, through Chais's Brighton Co., a [[limited partnership]] formed to manage money.  He took about 3.8% of the profits as management fees.  His Chais Family Foundation, which in 2007 reported assets of $178 million and charitable contributions of nearly $8.2 million, was wiped out and has shut down.  He had a home in Beverly Hills, and an apartment in New York.\n\nOn May 1, 2009, [[Irving Picard]], bankruptcy trustee, filed a lawsuit against Stanley Chais, 82.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 |work=The New York Times |title=Madoff: Lawsuit Against Stanley Chais |accessdate=May 21, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708012138/http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 |archivedate=July 8, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The complaint alleged Chais \"knew or should have known\" he was deep in a Ponzi scheme when his family investments with Madoff averaged 40% and sometimes soared as high as 300%. It also claimed Chais was a primary beneficiary of the scheme for at least 30 years, allowing his family to withdraw more than $1 billion from their accounts since 1995 \u2013 money that belonged to Madoff victims.<ref>{{cite news |last=Standora |first=Leo |date=2 May 2009 |title=Los Angeles investment manager Stanley Chais sued for funneling cash to Bernie Madoff fund |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/los-angeles-investment-manager-stanley-chais-sued-funneling-cash-bernie-madoff-fund-article-1.409647 |work=New York Daily News |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> The case number is ''Picard v. Chais'', 09-01172. When Chais claimed to be broke, Picard told a judge that Chais should sell his [[Fifth Avenue]] New York apartment to pay his legal fees.<ref>[http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2016/oct/28/bernie-madoff-friends-estate-agrees-to-pay-277-mil/ \"Bernie Madoff friend\u2019s estate agrees to pay $277 million to end lawsuit,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Spokesman-Review''.</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, the SEC filed civil fraud charges against Chais. According to the complaint, Chais told Madoff he didn't want to see any losses on the funds' trades.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Chais Complaint 2009-06-22 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109113101/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> On September 23, 2009, California Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]] filed a lawsuit against Chais seeking $25 million in penalties and restitution for victims.<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite news |\nwork=The Los Angeles Times |\ntitle=Financial advisor Stanley Chais sued in Bernard Madoff scheme |\nurl=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-chais23-2009sep23,0,3042092.story |\ndate=September 23, 2009 |\nauthor=Pfeifer, Stuart}}</ref> Federal prosecutors had opened a criminal probe into him, but he died in September 2010 before they filed charges against him.<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-chais/update-2-accused-madoff-middleman-stanley-chais-dies-idUSN2725688920100927?dbk \"Accused Madoff middleman Stanley Chais dies,\"] Reuters.</ref> His lawyer denied that Chais committed any wrongdoing.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nMichael Chaleff, a former [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] lawyer, was part of a 50-member investment group named CMG that lost $75 million to $80 million it gave to Chais' Brighton Co.  Chaleff filed a $250-million [[class action]] federal lawsuit against Chais in Los Angeles, as did [[screenwriter]] [[Eric Roth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2008/12/26/2008-12-26_forrest_gump_eric_roth_screenwriter_sues.html |title='Forrest Gump' Eric Roth screenwriter sues over Madoff losses |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=December 27, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=New York |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208001811/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2008/12/26/2008-12-26_forrest_gump_eric_roth_screenwriter_sues.html |archivedate=February 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christensen |first=Kim |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/front/la-fi-madoff-chais21-2008dec21,0,7052710.story |title=A Beverly Hills investor's ties to Madoff sink many \u2013 Los Angeles Times |publisher=Latimes.com |date=December 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130040353/http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/front/la-fi-madoff-chais21-2008dec21,0,7052710.story |archivedate=January 30, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[New Jersey]] State Senator [[Loretta Weinberg]] lost her entire life savings in Chais' \"Arbitrage Partnerships\" fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politickernj.com/max/26238/weinberg-loses-life-savings-ponzi-scheme |title=Weinberg loses life savings in Madoff Ponzi scheme &#124; Politicker NJ &#124; New Jersey Politics News, Reaction, and Analysis |publisher=Politicker NJ |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422063847/http://www.politickernj.com/max/26238/weinberg-loses-life-savings-ponzi-scheme |archivedate=April 22, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/nyregion/new-jersey/18weinbergnj.html |work=The New York Times |title=In Madoff Case, Politicians Current and Former Feel the Loss |first=Jacqueline |last=Mroz |date=January 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 21, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425135604/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/nyregion/new-jersey/18weinbergnj.html |archivedate=April 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nChais died on September 26, 2010 at age 84, in [[Manhattan]], where he and his wife had moved to further the treatment of a [[blood disorder]] that eventually took his life.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-me-stanley-chais-death,0,3602441.story | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Stanley Chais dies at 84; money manager invested with Bernard Madoff | first1=Stuart | last1=Pfeifer | first2=David | last2=Sarno | date=September 26, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007054718/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-me-stanley-chais-death,0,3602441.story | archivedate=October 7, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe widow, children, family, and estate of Chais settled with Picard in 2016 for $277 million.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-chais-idUSKCN12S1Y1 \"Madoff trustee reaches $277 million accord with money manager's family,\"] Reuters.</ref> On November 19, 2016, the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]] approved a global settlement \u2013 made in cooperation with the California Attorney General - with the defendants in ''Picard v. the Estate of Stanley Chais, et al''. The agreement was made with the Stanley Chais estate, Chais\u2019s widow, children, and a number of other Chais family members, investment funds, trusts, companies, and other entities associated with Chais. Under the terms of the agreement, the BLMIS Customer Fund received $277 million, including a cash payment of $258.47 million, as well as the assignment of other assets that would be liquidated over time.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> All proceeds of the settlement were to go to the BLMIS Customer Fund for the benefit of BLMIS customers with allowed claims.<ref>[https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/007385-chaisorder09-01172docket157.pdf \"ORDER PURSUANT TO SECTION 105(a) OF THE BANKRUPTCY CODE AND RULES 2002 AND 9019 OF THE FEDERAL RULES OF BANKRUPTCY PROCEDURE APPROVING AN AGREEMENT BY AND AMONG THE TRUSTEE AND THE ESTATE OF STANLEY CHAIS AND OTHER DEFENDANTS,\"] November 18, 2016.</ref> Picard\u2019s lawyers said the settlement covered all of Chais\u2019 estate and substantially all of his widow\u2019s assets, and represented \u201ca good faith, complete and total compromise.\u201d<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Tremont Group Holdings==\n{{Main|Tremont Group}}\n\n[[Tremont Group Holdings]], a division of [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company|MassMutual]],<ref name=\"MassMutualTremontSettlement\">{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/07/29/massmutual_unit_to_pay_1b_to_fund_for_madoff_clients/ |title=Madoff clients get $1b in deal |first=Beth |last=Healy |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 29, 2011 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023033248/http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/07/29/massmutual_unit_to_pay_1b_to_fund_for_madoff_clients/ |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> started its first Madoff-only fund in 1997. That group managed several funds marketed under the Rye Select Broad Market Fund,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aCT_aoIRYqRg&refer=home |title=Tremont Group Funds Invested $3.3 Billion With Madoff (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> which charged a 1% management fee and a 0.5% administration fee. The fund held $2.3 billion on Sep 30, 2008, collecting $34 million in fees a year. Tremont also offered the Rye Select Broad Market Portfolio Ltd., which charged total fees of 1.95% of assets and held $1.2 billion on Sep 30, 2008, with annual fees of $23.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/madoff-feeder-funds-reaped-huge |title=Madoff feeder funds reaped big fees |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 April 2009 |website=MarketWatch.com |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>  For investing $3.3 billion, Tremont was scheduled to receive over $30 million in fees in 2008. The town of [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]], Conn., is seeking the recovery of fees, and the assets of Robert Schulman, who once ran Tremont Group Holdings have been temporarily frozen.\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123940737747310069 |title=Feeder Fees Topped $790 Million - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Tom |last=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126190017/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123940737747310069 |archivedate=January 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/12872951/Town-of-Fairfield-suit-against-NEPC-and-KPMG |title=Town of Fairfield suit against NEPC and KPMG |publisher=Scribd.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306181226/http://www.scribd.com/doc/12872951/Town-of-Fairfield-suit-against-NEPC-and-KPMG |archivedate=March 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMassachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. has agreed to pay more than $1 billion to customers of the now-imprisoned Bernard Madoff in July 2011. The bankruptcy trustee sued Tremont, a group of hedge funds owned by Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co, as well as, its parent companies in December 2010, seeking more than $2 billion and alleging that company executives ignored \"obvious warning signs'' that Madoff was running a fraud. Picard alleged that Tremont failed to do any meaningful review of Madoff's operations or purported investment results, blindly allowing Rye to turn over half its $6 billion in client assets to Madoff and losing half that money when the scheme finally collapsed. The payment of $1 billion to the Madoff truste, provided by Massachusetts Mutual Life as a loan to Tremont, may have protected the reputation and financial interest of Massachusetts Mutual Life, as well as, saved  Tremont's customers with net gains from Madoff from [[clawback]]s. Some investors of Tremont had a net gains and could have been subject to clawbacks from the bankruptcy attorney if Tremont was forced into insolvency and the bankruptcy attorney could then examine the books of Tremont to see the actual investors' net Madoff gains.\n  \nLawsuits filed have been consolidated into three categories: federal security laws, insurance actions, and state law actions. They are: Lange, et al. v. Mass. Mutual Life Ins. Co., et al. (08 CV 11117, S.D. N.Y.); Finkelstein v. Tremont Group Holdings, Inc. (08 CV 11141, S.D. N.Y.); Peshkin v. Tremont Group Holdings, et al. (08 CV 11183, S.D.N.Y.).; Arthur M. Brainson IRA R/O v. Rye Select Broad Market Fund, L.P., et al. (No. 08 CV 11212, S.D.N.Y.); and Group Defined Pension Plan & Trust v. Tremont Market Neutral Fund, L.P., et al. (No. 08 CV 11359, S.D.N.Y.). The plaintiffs are all investors in hedge funds with assets that they entrusted to Madoff for investment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.lexisnexis.com/practiceareas/Focus-on-Madoff/Securities-Law/Tremont-Group-Moves-To-Consolidate-Madoff-Cases |title=Mealey's Emerging Securities Litigation Report: Tremont Group Moves To Consolidate Madoff Cases |date=March 12, 2009 |website=[[LexisNexis]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120712131834/http://www.lexisnexis.com/community/corpsec/blogs/sec-law-alerts/archive/2012/06/04/mealey_1920_s-emerging-securities-litigation-report_3a00_-tremont-group-moves-to-consolidate-madoff-cases.aspx |archivedate=July 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nFour state law cases have been consolidated with [[Hagens Berman Sobol Shapiro]] as co-lead counsel. They initially filed a class-action lawsuit on behalf of investors and groups that invested capital with [[Tremont Group Holdings]], alleging the company and others grossly neglected fiduciary duties and lost a total of $3.3 billion in assets, $3.1 billion from the Rye Funds invested with Bernard Madoff Investment Securities, relinquishing management to Madoff while continuing to receive client management fees.  The complaint names Tremont Group Holdings, its Rye Investment Funds, Oppenheimer Acquisition Corporation, [[OppenheimerFunds]], which owns Tremont, [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company]], a majority owner of OppenheimerFunds and [[KPMG LLP]], Tremont's auditor, as defendants.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hbsslaw.com/cases/tremont |title=Tremont Group Holdings Lawsuit |date=December 22, 2008 |website=Hagens Berman Sobol Shapiro |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033836/https://www.hbsslaw.com/cases/tremont |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing assets, in exchange for a pledge of $2.5 million in total from Tremont Entities and Robert Shulman and $500,000 from Oppenheimer Acquisition Corporation. The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nThe Tremont Group is represented by Michael Gruenglas of [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom]] in New York.\n\n===Maxam Capital===\nMadoff was the investment adviser over all the $300 million Maxam Absolute Return Fund's assets. Maxam was scheduled to receive $2.8 million for investing $280 million in 2008. The Town of [[Fairfield, Connecticut]] invested in Madoff through the Return Fund created by Maxam Capital Management LLC, based in [[Darien, Connecticut]]. The Maxam fund in turn invested in Madoff through Tremont. Sandra L. Manzke, the founder of Maxam Capital, has had her assets temporarily frozen by the same Connecticut court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/03/31/madoff-connecticut-ponzi-personal-finance_fairfield.html |title=Judge Freezes Madoff Assets |publisher=Forbes.com |date=March 31, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=David |last=Randall}}</ref>\n\nMaxam Absolute Return Fund LP has filed a lawsuit in [[Connecticut Superior Court]] in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]] against auditors Goldstein Golub Kessler LLP and McGladrey & Pullen LLP to recover losses, claiming they relied on the auditors for their expertise in examining Madoff's firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-maxam/maxam-hedge-fund-sues-auditors-over-madoff-losses-idUSTRE50U06V20090131 |title=Maxam hedge fund sues auditors over Madoff losses |last=Giannone |first=Joseph A. |date=January 30, 2009 |editor-last=Hill |editor-first=Gary |website=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing assets, and ordered Sandra Manzke, to provide a $2.5 million mortgage on a piece of property she owns in Vermont.<ref>{{cite web |last=Quinn |first=Brigid |url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1653&dept_id=686445&newsid=20299234&PAG=461&rfi=9 |title=Fairfield Minuteman \u2013 Town secures pledges of $25M in Madoff scandal |publisher=Zwire.com |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706213401/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1653&dept_id=686445&newsid=20299234&PAG=461&rfi=9 |archivedate=July 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Maxam's attorney, Jonathan D. Cogan said,\"The Town of Fairfield's suit is an outrageous publicity stunt to divert attention from the town's own decision to invest in Madoff, which was made long before it did business with Maxam.\" The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn July 28, 2011, [[Irving Picard]], the receiver assigned to Madoff's Ponzi scheme, extracted a settlement from Tremont worth over one billion dollars.<ref name=\"MassMutualTremontSettlement\" />\n\n==Defender==\n[[Defender Limited]] acted as a [[feeder fund]], by funneling clients' funds to Bernard Madoff's firm, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities (BLMIS), as part of the Ponzi scheme run by Madoff.{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-settlement-idUSKBN0MJ2F720150323|title=Madoff feeder fund settles; victims' recovery tops $10.6 billion|date=23 March 2015|work=Reuters}}</ref> In December 2013, Defender sued HSBC Institutional Trust Services Incorporated, an Irish subsidiary of [[HSBC Bank]] with registered offices in [[Dublin]], in an Irish court for $539 million.<ref name=\"bvibeacon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://bvibeacon.com/vi-feeder-fund-sues-bank-to-recover-madoff-monies/|title=VI 'feeder fund' sues bank to recover Madoff monies|date=4 December 2013|website=The BVI Beacon}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=f2616787-5f11-4eb0-8af8-dce3a3003fcf|title=Hard to Gain, Easy to Lose? - Lexology|first1=William Fry-Paul|last1=Convery|first2=Derek|last2=Hegarty|website=lexology.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20110321/BUSINESS02/703219913|title=HSBC warned about Madoff 'fraud and operational risks' in two KPMG reports - The Royal Gazette:Bermuda International Business|first=Boris|last=Groendahl|website=The Royal Gazette}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/financial-services/ruling-casts-doubt-on-141m-case-against-hsbc-s-irish-arm-1.3722911|title=Ruling casts doubt on $141m case against HSBC's Irish arm|first=Mary|last=Carolan|website=The Irish Times}}</ref> Defender alleged that the bank failed to conduct adequate [[due diligence]] on Madoff, and failed to warn Defender that HSBC was not able to confirm the existence of Defender's assets.<ref name=\"bvibeacon.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-arm-of-hsbc-bank-being-sued-over-madoff-scheme-29802611.html|title=Irish arm of HSBC bank being sued over Madoff scheme|website=The Irish Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bvi-grey-area.offshore-journals.com/bvi-investment-fund-sues-hsbcs-arm-over-madoff-polzi-scheme-806.html|title=BVI investment fund sues HSBC's arm over Madoff Ponzi scheme - BVI Offshore Business: Grey Area|last=Mike}}</ref>  In December 2018, the [[High Court of Ireland]] ruled that Defender's claim against HSBC was reduced by 100% due to Defender's earlier settlement with BLMIS.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Defender appealed that decision to the Irish [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]], where the appeal is pending.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/judge-says-recusal-hearing-in-madoff-case-would-be-waste-of-court-time-1.3739795|title=Judge says recusal hearing in Madoff case would be 'waste of court time'|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2015, the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]] approved an agreement between Picard on the one hand, and Defender and related entities on the other hand.<ref name=\"madofftrustee.com\">[https://www.madofftrustee.com/recoveries-25.html \"Defender\"]</ref>  The BLMIS Customer Fund benefited by $93 million.<ref name=\"madofftrustee.com\"/>  Defender received a $522.8 million claim in the BLMIS liquidation, because Defender had deposited more with BLMIS than Defender withdrew.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-settlement-idUSKBN0MJ2F720150323|title=Madoff feeder fund settles; victims' recovery tops $10.6 billion|date=23 March 2015|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n==Fiserv Inc.==\nA $1\u2002billion class-action federal lawsuit was filed in Colorado against [[Fiserv]], Inc. of [[Brookfield, Wisconsin]], whose subsidiaries were custodians for [[pension]] or [[Individual Retirement Account|IRA]] accounts and invested with Madoff. The complaint alleges Fiserv failed \"to hold and safeguard assets entrusted to it\" by about 800 Madoff customers who had been told to hire Fiserv to handle their accounts with him.  Fiserv is accused of breach of [[fiduciary]] duty, [[fraud]], [[negligence]], and aiding and abetting breach of fiduciary. Fiserv sold its investment account administration business in 2007 to [[TD Ameritrade]], also a defendant.  The lawsuit estimates Fiserv generated at least $25\u2002million annually from Madoff investors, and claims it wasn't diligent because \"Fiserv had too much revenue at stake to risk upsetting Madoff.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Gores |first=Paul |url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/43208047.html |title=Fiserv faces suit in Madoff case |publisher=JSOnline |date=April 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424104045/http://www.jsonline.com/business/43208047.html |archivedate=April 24, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Judge Christine M. Arguello ruled in favor of Fiserv Inc. and its co-defendants. Arguello found that the investors bore responsibility for the investment decisions, and that the funds transferred to Madoff were done so at the direction of the investors. Although Madoff was included among Fiserv's investment options, Arguello noted that the IRA agreements provided to Fiserv's investors clearly indemnified the defendants, and that Fiserv \"had no obligation to verify or audit.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Gores |first=Paul |url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/123773989.html |title=Fiserv not responsible for losses in Madoff scheme, judge rules |publisher=JSOnline |date=June 13, 2011 |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206151327/http://www.jsonline.com/business/123773989.html |archivedate=February 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==David and Craig Kugel==\nOn November 16, 2011, longtime Madoff trader David Kugel pleaded guilty to backdating trades for Madoff. Kugel joined the firm in 1970, eventually becoming a supervisor with Madoff's legitimate [[proprietary trading]] operation. In his allocution, he admitted creating bogus trading records as early as the 1970s\u2013further undermining Madoff's claim that he only began his fraud in 1991. He made greater than $10 million in profits from investments with Madoff, and his salary was as high as $588,000 a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/former-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/2011/11/21/gIQATSFLjN_story.html|title=Former Madoff trader David Kugel pleads guilty to fraud|author1=David S. Hilzenrath|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-21/ex-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-bank-fraud-dating-to-1970s |title=Ex-Madoff Trader Kugel Admits to Creating Records of Fake Trades |last=Hurtado |first=Patricia |date=November 21, 2011 |website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720161918/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-21/ex-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-bank-fraud-dating-to-1970s |archivedate=July 20, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He told prosecutors that after the main backoffice secretary on the 17th floor\u2013Annette Bongiorno in the 1970s and 1980s, and Judi Crupi from the 1980s onward\u2013told him how much money should be \"invested\" for a client, he would note how much volume actually occurred so the \"trades\" looked real. He faced up to 85 years in prison.<ref name=WizardofLies>{{cite book|title=The Wizard of Lies|last=Henriques|first=Diana|authorlink=Diana B. Henriques|publisher=[[Times Books]]|date=2011|isbn=978-0805091342}}</ref> However, after testifying at Bongiorno, Crupi, Bonventre and Perez' trial, he was sentenced to 10 months' house arrest and 200 hours community service in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-crime-madoff-kugel-idUSL1N0YI1C720150527|title=Ex-Madoff trader turned prosecution witness avoids prison time|author1=Joseph Ax|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=May 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCraig Kugel pleaded guilty to tax fraud; he arranged salaries for non-employees.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-06-05/ex-madoff-employee-craig-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-tax-scheme |title=Ex-Madoff Employee Craig Kugel Pleads Guilty to Scheme |last=Hurtado |first=Patricia |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |date=June 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130118165232/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-06-05/ex-madoff-employee-craig-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-tax-scheme |archivedate=January 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090416035906/http://www.rightpundits.com/?p=3299 Ruth Madoff Biography] Ruth Madoff biography and photos.\n* [http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/nys/madoff/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf Frank DiPascali DOJ Information/Plea Agreement] (August 2009)\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/27/serious-fraud-office-bernard-madoff-feeder-funds Serious Fraud Office broadens investigation to Madoff feeders] ''[[The Guardian]]'', March 27, 2009, British government's investigation into the London activities of certain feeder funds that channeled investments to Madoff\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf Merkin Civil Fraud Complaint], State of New York (April 6, 2009)\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf#  Exhibits 1\u201320 to Civil Fraud Complaint]\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf Exhibits 21\u201326 to Civil Fraud Complaint]\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf# Exhibits 27\u201348 from Civil Fraud Complaint]\n* [http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf Bankruptcy Complaint against J. Ezra Merkin] (May 7, 2009)\n* [https://www.scribd.com/doc/15274382/Madoff-Trustee-Suit-Against-Harley Complaint against Harley International (Cayman) Limited] (May 12, 2009)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211040/http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf Commonwealth of Massachusetts Secretary of State Complaint] (January 14, 2009)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091229223951/http://www.nylj.com/nylawyer/adgifs/decisions/062309cohmad.pdf Picard v. Cohmad Securities Corp. 09-AP-1305] (June 22, 2009)\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf, SEC v. Cohmad Securities Corp., 09 Civ. 5680] (June 22, 2009)\n* [http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 Picard v. Chais et al. 08-01789] (May 1, 2009)\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf SEC v. Stanley Chais, 09 CIV 5681] (June 22, 2009)\n\n{{Madoff investment scandal}}\n{{2008 economic crisis}}\n\n[[Category:Madoff investment scandal]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Madoff investment scandal| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{update|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n[[File:BernardMadoff.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Bernard Madoff]]]]\n'''Participants in the [[Madoff investment scandal]]''' included employees of [[Bernard Madoff]]'s investment firm with specific knowledge of the [[Ponzi scheme]], a three-person accounting firm that assembled his reports, and a network of [[feeder fund]]s that invested their clients' money with Madoff while collecting significant fees. Madoff avoided most direct financial scrutiny by accepting investments only through these feeder funds, while obtaining false [[financial audit|auditing]] statements for his firm. The liquidation trustee of Madoff's firm has implicated managers of the feeder funds for ignoring signs of Madoff's deception. Although Madoff claimed to have executed the scheme alone, subsequent investigation has shown that he was assisted by a small group of close associates, as well as the feeders' self-interested indifference to the source of his investment returns.\n\n==Madoff Securities International Ltd.==\nIn 2008, about $1 billion was transferred last between Madoff's U.S. firm and Madoff Securities International Ltd. in London.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=azeCkQIOM0L8&refer=uk |title=Madoff Fraud Charges Could Be Filed in U.K. This Year (Update4) |last=Lumley |first=James |date=March 27, 2009 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130118064350/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=azeCkQIOM0L8&refer=uk |archivedate=January 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"article1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123815606271556053 |title=U.K. Could Charge More Than Just Madoff |last=Bryan-Low |first=Cassell |date=March 28, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219172250/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123815606271556053 |archivedate=February 19, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2009 Judge [[Louis L. Stanton]] granted [[power of attorney]] to [[Irving Picard]], trustee, over Madoff's controlling stake in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090324-716334.html |title=Trustee Granted Control Over Madoff's Stake In UK Operations |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 24, 2009}} {{dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities in the U.K. are seeking evidence of [[money laundering]] involving the London business, Madoff Securities International Ltd., which opened in 1983 as a separate legal entity from Mr. Madoff's U.S. New York office.  He allegedly sent more than $250 million beginning as early as 2002, from his New York-based firm, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities LLC, to the U.K. office and then back to accounts in the U.S.<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/><ref name=\"article1\"/>\n\nIn 2000, Madoff began to add staff and expand the operation, and loaned the business $62.5 million.  He had a staff of 25, including traders, managers and support.  Instructions to staff  was that they communicate with Madoff Securities through personal e-mail accounts, not through company e-mail.<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/>\n\nThere were nine directors. Family members with shares included Mark and Andrew Madoff, Peter Madoff, and Bernard himself. Ruth Madoff, Bernard Madoff's wife, also held shares.\n<ref name=\"article3\">{{cite news |last=Lauricella |first=Tom |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123681392137901653 |title=Madoff Used U.K. Office in Cash Ploy, Filing Says - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=March 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227150311/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123681392137901653 |archivedate=February 27, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nNon-family members with shares included Maurice J. \"Sonny\" Cohn. Madoff and Cohn were shareholders in [[Cohmad Securities]], which steered investors to Mr. Madoff's advisory business.  In 1987, Mr. Cohn had shares of Madoff Holdings Ltd., a predecessor to the current London firm. In 1998, Mr. Cohn held 35,624 non-voting shares, some of which he transferred to \"BL Madoff\" in 1998, and the rest that he \"disposed of\" in 2004.<ref name=\"article3\"/>\n\n===Paul Konigsberg===\nPaul Konigsberg, a New York City accountant and a longtime friend for more than 25 years, prepared two Madoff Family Foundation tax returns, and received the non-voting shares, valued at $35,000.  He did work for the London office when it was first opened.\n<ref name=\"article3\"/>  A general ledger of Madoff accounts listed Konigsberg, of the reputable accounting firm of Konigsberg, Wolf & Co., as receiving $30,000 a month to advise the MSIL operations, and funnel client checks to the London office for Madoff's own use.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-04-23/madoffs-london-money-laundering-scam/ |title=Was Madoff 'Victim' and Best Friend an Accomplice? \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=The Daily Beast |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425142840/http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-04-23/madoffs-london-money-laundering-scam/ |archivedate=April 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nClients were often directed to Mr. Konigsberg by Mr. Madoff and his family. Mr. Konigsberg prepared the tax returns of foundations of six other families, many of which have lost millions, even hundreds of millions, of dollars.  He also represented scores of individual Madoff investors.  Mr. Konigsberg's firm has received a civil subpoena from the SEC.  His Madoff-related clients included Carl and Ruth Shapiro, Boston philanthropists whose foundation lost $145 million, and whose son-in-law, Robert M. Jaffe, under investigation, is a Madoff business partner.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\"/><ref name=\"WayneRashbaumNYT031209\">{{cite news |first=Leslie |last=Wayne |author2=Rashbaum, William K. |title=Investigation Into Madoff Fraud Turns to a Small Circle of Accountants |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/12/business/12accountants.html |work=New York Times |date=March 11, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501173649/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/12/business/12accountants.html |archivedate=May 1, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nKonigsberg held Madoff accounts under his name including two in the name of the Westlake Foundation. Paul J. and Judith Konigsberg are officers and directors of the foundation. He owns homes in his wife, Judith's name in Greenwich, Connecticut and Palm Beach Gardens, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-4-million-lawsui.php?ref=reccafe |title=Bernie Madoff: $4 Million Lawsuit Filed Against Paul J. Konigsberg |date=May 28, 2009 |website=Mrs Panstreppon's Blog |publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531081307/http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-4-million-lawsui.php |archivedate=May 31, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2009, Steven Leber filed a $4 million lawsuit against Konigsberg and his accounting firm for [[negligence]], and breach of [[fiduciary]] duty.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/15891679/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Complaint |title=PACER \u2013 Leber vs. Konigsberg \u2013 Complaint |publisher=Scribd.com |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107063548/http://www.scribd.com/doc/15891679/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Complaint |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Konigsberg answered the charges with [[affirmative defense]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/15893994/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Konigsberg-Response |title=PACER \u2013 Leber vs. Konigsberg \u2013 Konigsberg Response |publisher=Scribd.com |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107063745/http://www.scribd.com/doc/15893994/PACER-Leber-vs-Konigsberg-Konigsberg-Response |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Konigsberg pleaded guilty in connection to the Madoff case and will consequently face up to 30 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/24/news/companies/madoff-konigsberg-guilty/index.html |title=Madoff's accountant pleads guilty |last=Lobosco |first=Katie |date=June 24, 2014 |website=[[CNNMoney]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |quote=Paul Konigsberg, Bernie Madoff's former accountant, faces up to 30 years in prison. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816034519/http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/24/news/companies/madoff-konigsberg-guilty/index.html |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On July 9, 2015, U.S. District Court Judge Laura Taylor Swain agreed with prosecutors that Konigsberg did not know about Madoff's scheme and had cooperated fully with investigators. Swain ruled that Konigsberg had earned lenience from federal sentencing guidelines and did not have to serve any time in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-madoff-konigsberg-idUSKCN0PJ2VL20150709 |title=Ex-accounting executive avoids prison in Madoff fraud case |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=July 9, 2015 |accessdate=February 5, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526070831/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-madoff-konigsberg-idUSKCN0PJ2VL20150709 |archivedate=May 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Norman F. Levy===\nEvidence is being gathered  by investigators on a U.S.-U.K. task force that Konigsberg and Levy, a real-estate mogul and philanthropist are believed to be involved in an international transfer of money.   Levy is believed to have helped Paul Konigsberg funnel checks to London. And investigators in New York say there were billions of dollars' worth of checks going back and forth between Madoff and Levy.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\"/>\n\nRuth and Bernie Madoff had an intimate relationship with Levy and his wife, Betty.  Madoff was long known to have been Levy's \"fixer,\" obtaining everything from choice restaurant reservations to emergency medical care. Levy had offices one floor below Madoff's in New York's [[Lipstick Building]]. It was Levy who introduced high-profile investors to Madoff.\n\nJeanne Levy-Church's losses forced her to shut her JEHT Foundation and her parents' foundation, the Betty and Norman F. Levy Foundation, lost $244 million.  JEH helped the less fortunate, especially ex-convicts.<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\" /><ref name=\"WayneRashbaumNYT031209\" />\n\nFollowing the death of his wife, Levy's girlfriend, model [[Carmen Dell'Orefice]], an investor, said Levy was Madoff's \"father figure\". When Levy died in 2005 at the age of 93, Madoff extolled him as a man whose friendship he had cherished and who had \"taught me so much.\" Levy's son Francis said his father believed in Madoff: \"If there's one honorable person,\" he said, \"it's Bernie.\"<ref name=\"thedailybeast1\" /><ref name=\"currentpage1\">{{cite web |last=Seal |first=Mark |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/04/madoff200904?currentPage=all |title=Madoff's World |publisher=vanityfair.com |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415021714/http://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/04/madoff200904?currentPage=all |archivedate=April 15, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Chapter 15 bankruptcy protection===\nOn April 14, 2009, the liquidators of Madoff International Limited of London filed for [[Chapter 15]] bankruptcy recognition in West Palm Beach, Florida, and sued Peter Madoff, to recover a  1964 [[Aston Martin DB2/4]] automobile worth an estimated $200,000.   In March and May 2008, Madoff International wire-transferred 135,000 pounds ($198,207) to buy a car for Peter Madoff, and delivered it to him  at his residence in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]]. Madoff International's listed assets are as much as $500 million and debt of more than $1 billion in its bankruptcy petition.  The bankruptcy is designed to block U.S. lawsuits against foreign companies with U.S. operations while they reorganize overseas.  Investors who filed an involuntary [[personal bankruptcy]] petition against Madoff want his business's U.K. unit's bankruptcy moved to New York because \"overlapping discovery, related assets and common creditors\" among the various cases mean they should be in the same court.\n\nThe Chapter 15 case is ''In re Madoff Securities International Ltd.'', 09-16751, [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]], Southern District of Florida (West Palm Beach).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=agGTdJJDCZos&refer=us |title=Madoff Investors Want U.K. Unit Bankruptcy Moved (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=April 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224028/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103 |archivedate=January 22, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2009 the Chapter 15 case was transferred to the Southern District of New York as ''Madoff Securities International Limited, Stephen John Akers, Mark Richard Byers, and Andrew Laurence as the Joint Provisional Liquidators'', 09-12998, so it can be administered more effectively with the related involuntary bankruptcies against Madoff, and his companies, also filed in New York. The associated adversary proceeding was also moved to the Southern District of New York as ''Akers et al. v. Madoff'', 09-1186, demanding $235,000 against Peter B. Madoff.\n\n==David G. Friehling==\nSince at least 1991, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities had been audited by Friehling & Horowitz CPAs, a little-known accounting firm in [[New City, New York|New City]], north of New York City. The firm consisted of two principals, [[David G. Friehling]] and Jerome Horowitz, and a part-time secretary. Horowitz was semi-retired; Friehling was the sole active practitioner.<ref name=SECFriehling>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2009/comp20959.pdf|title=Securities and Exchange Commission v. David G. Friehling, Friehling & Horowitz, CPAs, P.E.|date=March 2009|publisher=United States District Court, Southern District Of New York|accessdate=25 September 2015}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nWell before the Madoff scandal broke, several observers doubted that a tiny firm with only one active accountant could competently audit a firm that had grown into a multibillion-dollar operation.  In 2007, Aksia LLC, a hedge fund consultant, warned its clients to stay away from Madoff for that very reason; its CEO, Jim Vos, likened this situation to [[General Motors]] being audited by a three-person firm.<ref>Fitzgerald, Jim. [http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html Madoff's financial empire audited by tiny firm: one guy]. [[Associated Press]] via [[Seattle Times]], December 18, 2008.</ref>  Others were suspicious that Madoff refused requests for [[due diligence]] because his accountant\u2014supposedly his brother-in-law\u2014was the only one allowed to see the books.<ref>{{cite book|last=Markopolos|first=Harry|authorlink=Harry Markopolos|url=https://archive.org/details/noonewouldlisten00mark|title=No One Would Listen: A True Financial Thriller|date=March 2010|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]]|isbn=978-0-470-55373-2|url-access=registration}}</ref> Indeed, for many years, Friehling's practice was so small that he operated out of his house. He only got an office when Madoff told him that some investors were asking questions about the audits. Even then, his operation remained very small; in 2008 it only garnered $180,000 in earnings, far less than conventional wisdom would suggest for a firm that was supposedly earning substantial fees from auditing the Madoff operation. It later emerged that officials at [[Fairfield Greenwich Group]], operator of the largest Madoff [[feeder fund]], had been aware as early as 2005 that Friehling was the firm's sole employee.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nFriehling was charged on March 18, 2009, with [[securities fraud]], aiding and abetting [[investment adviser]] fraud, and four counts of filing false audit reports with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Friehling waived indictment and pleaded not guilty to criminal charges on July 10, 2009. He agreed to proceed without having the evidence in the criminal case against him reviewed by a grand jury at a hearing before U.S. District Judge Alvin Hellerstein in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124784585862258641 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first=Chad |last=Bray |title=Madoff Ex-Auditor Friehling Enters a Plea of Not Guilty |date=July 18, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110833/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124784585862258641 |archivedate=January 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He faced up to 105 years in prison on all of the charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/FriehlingComplaint20090318.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Friehling Complaint 2009-03-18 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109045508/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/FriehlingComplaint20090318.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"article4\">{{cite news |last=Efrati |first=Amir |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123738779664971505 |title=Accountant Arrested for Sham Audits - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=March 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705225627/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123738779664971505 |archivedate=July 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"press1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2009/2009-60.htm |title=Press Release: SEC Charges Madoff Auditors With Fraud; 2009\u201360; March 18, 2009 |publisher=Sec.gov |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507214906/http://www.sec.gov/news/press/2009/2009-60.htm |archivedate=May 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Federal prosecutors had until about June 17, 2009 to produce a [[grand jury]] indictment against him, or a plea bargain to end the case.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5g360RkdSH5ANu_nugd01e6IEjAfwD988U6LO0] {{dead link|date=June 2009|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nMadoff's firm paid Friehling between $12,000 and $14,500 a month for his services between 2004 and 2007.<ref name=\"article4\"/>\n\nAlthough required, Friehling was not registered with the [[Public Company Accounting Oversight Board]], which was created under the [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] of 2002 to help detect fraud.  Nor was the firm \"peer reviewed,\" in which auditors check out one another for [[quality control]].  According to the [[American Institute of Certified Public Accountants]] (AICPA), Friehling was enrolled in their peer-review program, but was not required to participate because he advised the group that he had not conducted audits for 15 years.<ref name=\"article2\">{{cite news |last=Jeanne |first=Ianthe |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123491638561904323 |title=Accounting Firms That Missed Fraud at Madoff May Be Liable - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=February 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706002421/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123491638561904323 |archivedate=July 6, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2008/12/17/news/companies/madoff.auditor.fortune/index.htm Madoff's Auditor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308000826/http://money.cnn.com/2008/12/17/news/companies/madoff.auditor.fortune/index.htm |date=March 8, 2009 }} [[CNN]] December 17, 2008.</ref> It later emerged that Madoff's banker, [[JPMorgan Chase]], had known that Friehling wasn't registered with the PCAOB or subject to peer review as early as 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/020311madoffjpm.pdf |title=Madoff trustee suit against JPMorgan Chase |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2013 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nFriehling pleaded guilty in November 2009. He admitted to simply rubber-stamping Madoff's filings with the SEC; rather than perform actual audits, he signed blank SEC forms before Madoff and others filled them in.  He also revealed that he continued to audit Madoff even though he had invested a substantial amount of money with him; accountants aren't allowed to audit broker-dealers with whom they're investing.  He agreed to forfeit $3.18 million in accounting fees and withdrawals from his account with Madoff, as well as his three-story, 4,400-square-foot house in New City and one other property.  Friehling faced a maximum sentence of 114 years in prison, but unlike Madoff has agreed to cooperate with the government. Calling himself a victim of Madoff, he faced a possible sentence of 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Hamblett&nbsp;All Articles |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202435168711&slreturn=1 |title=Madoff's Accountant Acknowledges Guilt, Casts Himself as Victim |publisher=Law.com |date=November 4, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nIn May 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Laura Taylor Swain]] sentenced Friehling to one year of home detention and one year of supervised release. Friehling avoided prison because he cooperated extensively with federal prosecutors and because he had been unaware of the extent of Madoff's crimes. Addressing the court at the hearing, Friehling apologized to Madoff's victims. Referring to Madoff's reported statement that he was a \"dumb auditor,\" Friehling said: \"I would rather be regarded as dumb than crooked. I did not question what I should have questioned.\"<ref name=\"Goldstein\">Matthew Goldstein, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/business/dealbook/madoff-accountant-avoids-prison-term.html Madoff Accountant Avoids Prison Term] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126104940/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/business/dealbook/madoff-accountant-avoids-prison-term.html |date=November 26, 2016 }}, ''New York Times'' (May 28, 2015).</ref>\n\nSwain accepted the plea terms, but suggested that Friehling be forced to pay part of the overall $130 million forfeiture arising from the fraud. Swain said that she did not believe Friehling's nonfeasance took place \"in a vacuum,\" and felt the forfeiture was necessary to hold the defendants to account even though it will likely never be repaid in full.<ref name=\"Goldstein\"/>\n\nFriehling's involvement made the Madoff scandal the largest [[accounting fraud]] in history, dwarfing the $11 billion fraud orchestrated by [[Bernard Ebbers]] at [[MCI Inc.|WorldCom]].\n\n==Peter B. Madoff==\nPeter B. Madoff, Chief Compliance Officer, worked with his brother Bernie for more than 40 years, and ran the daily operations for the past 20 years. Peter Madoff helped create the computerized trading system used by the firm and his daughter, [[Shana Madoff|Shana Madoff Swanson]], worked for him at the firm as a rules and compliance officer and attorney. In 2007 she married [[Eric Swanson]], whom she had met as he was conducting an SEC review of the firm in 2003 as an SEC Assistant Director.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=sI1jqoMRW7gC&pg=PA417&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=shana%20madoff%20peter%20compliance&f=false Business Ethics: Ethical Decision Making & Cases - O. C. Ferrell, John Fraedrich, Ferrell - Google Books] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704224558/http://books.google.com/books?id=sI1jqoMRW7gC&pg=PA417&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA |date=July 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=uDWuilMrwkcC&pg=PA376&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=shana%20&f=false Investigation of Failure of the SEC to Uncover Bernard Madoff's Ponzi Scheme ... - Google Books] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508170718/http://books.google.com/books?id=uDWuilMrwkcC&pg=PA376&dq=shana+madoff+peter+compliance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IJguUcygAcaQ0QH32oGIAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAg |date=May 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPeter graduated from [[Fordham University School of Law]] in 1970 and was formerly director of the [[National Stock Exchange (Jersey City, New Jersey)|National Stock Exchange]] (Cincinnati Stock Exchange).<ref name=\"Barlyn\">{{cite news | last = Barlyn | first = Suzanne | title = Madoff Case Raises Compliance Questions | work = [[Wall Street Journal]] | date = December 23, 2008 | url = http://www.careerjournal.com/article/SB123005903944830699.html | accessdate = March 1, 2008 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228034553/http://www.careerjournal.com/article/SB123005903944830699.html | archivedate = December 28, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"http\">{{cite news |last = Williamson |first = Elizabeth |author2 = Kara Scannell |title = Family Filled Posts at Industry Groups |work = [[Wall Street Journal]] |date = December 18, 2008 |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122956128953016563 |accessdate = March 1, 2009 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150303063407/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122956128953016563 |archivedate = March 3, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Peter owned a home in [[Old Westbury, New York]], valued between $3\u20135 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090403/FREE/904039987 |title=Peter Madoff gets $10K in monthly expenses \u2013 Crain's New York Business |publisher=Crainsnewyork.com |date=April 3, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406052156/http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20090403/FREE/904039987 |archivedate=April 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a $4.2 million home in [[Palm Beach, Florida]], the title of which was transferred  on November 8, 2006 to his wife, Marion, and a vintage [[Aston Martin]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123154665944869835 |title=Madoff Brother, at Arm's Length? - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Tom |last1=Lauricella |first2=Aaron |last2=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405040115/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123154665944869835 |archivedate=April 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/30/cbsnews_investigates/main4765109.shtml |title=Double Trouble for Madoffs? \u2013 CBS News |publisher=CBS News |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203035014/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/30/cbsnews_investigates/main4765109.shtml |archivedate=February 3, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"investigates1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/12/cbsnews_investigates/main4797238.shtml |title=Madoff's Wife Could Face Legal Trouble \u2013 CBS News |publisher=CBS News |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223161150/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/12/cbsnews_investigates/main4797238.shtml |archivedate=February 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter stepped down from the Board of Directors of the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association (SIFMA) in December 2008, as news of the Ponzi scheme broke. Peter also co-signed Bernie's bail bond. According to court documents, Peter did not agree to cooperate in the investigation.<ref name=\"businessweek.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-06-29/peter-madoff-bernie-s-brother-to-plead-guilty |title=Peter Madoff Admits Aiding Brother's Ponzi Scheme |last1=Hurtado |first1=Patricia |last2=Van Voris |first2=Bob |last3=Smythe |first3=Christie |date=June 30, 2012 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712184337/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-06-29/peter-madoff-bernie-s-brother-to-plead-guilty |archivedate=July 12, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter also owns between 5% and 10% of, and is a director of, [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/>  He has been subpoenaed by [[Massachusetts]]'s [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[William F. Galvin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.tbo.com/content/2008/dec/18/sp-attorney-general-leaves-madoff-case/ |title=Attorney General Leaves Madoff Case |publisher=.tbo.com |date=December 18, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208015751/http://www2.tbo.com/content/2008/dec/18/sp-attorney-general-leaves-madoff-case/ |archivedate=February 8, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"business1\"/>\n\nOn  April 3, 2009, his temporarily frozen assets previously ordered were modified to be allowed to spend up to $10,000 per month for living expenses, including mortgage loans and insurance premiums.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123877013231186763 |title=Peter Madoff Agrees to Revised Asset Freeze - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 4, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Aaron |last=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314145644/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123877013231186763 |archivedate=March 14, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPeter served as a [[trustee]] for law student Andrew Samuels' $470,000 inheritance from his grandfather who worked for Madoff and created a trust for him.  Andrew's lawsuit, claiming $2 million for breach his fiduciary duty by investing his inheritance with Bernard Madoff was settled in July 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a0zI28JuSN9I | work=Bloomberg | title=Student Settles Suit Against Peter Madoff Over Lost Inheritance | date=July 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731153558/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a0zI28JuSN9I | archivedate=July 31, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The case is ''Ross v. Madoff'', 09-5534, [[New York Supreme Court]] for [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] ([[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]).<ref>{{cite news |last=McCool |first=Grant |date=25 March 2009 |title=NY student wins freeze of Madoff brother's assets |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-brother/ny-student-wins-freeze-of-madoff-brothers-assets-idUSTRE52O72X20090326 |agency=Reuters |location=New York |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing his assets. Madoff agreed to attachments of $2.5 million to his [[Long Island]] home. His attorney is H. James Pickerstein. The pension fund case is ''Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff'', FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=apLMJ4p8DYyY&refer=home |title=Madoff-Linked Asset Freeze Lifted in Connecticut Suit (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=April 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2009, Peter demanded a $500,000 licensing fee as part of the sale of BLMIS for intellectual property used by the market-making business, but it was rejected by the bankruptcy trustee who maintains that the patents are the property of the business. Members of the Madoff family, including Madoff, own holding companies that own Primex LLC, which holds intellectual property licensed to the Nasdaq stock market. The patents are used for electronic trading.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124110591783073437 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=David | last=Mclaughlin | title=Judge Backs Sale of Madoff Market-Making Unit | date=April 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310125309/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124110591783073437 | archivedate=March 10, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Frank Lautenberg]]'s family foundation, which invested more than $7 million, also filed a lawsuit against Peter Madoff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/jersey/index.ssf?/base/news-12/123553958738630.xml&coll=1 |title=Lautenberg foundation lawsuit targets Bernard Madoff's brother - NJ.com |publisher=NJ.com |date=February 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316211726/http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/jersey/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-12%2F123553958738630.xml&coll=1 |archivedate=March 16, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2012, Peter pleaded guilty in Federal court to a variety of charges and agreed to a 10-year prison term.  Peter Madoff sometimes signed many weeks of compliance reports in one sitting, intentionally changing pens and ink colors to make it appear he had signed them at various times, according to prosecutors.<ref>Neumeister, Larry, and Tom Hays, [https://news.yahoo.com/peter-madoff-pleads-guilty-nyc-blaming-brother-163003155--finance.html \"Peter Madoff pleads guilty in NYC, blaming brother\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305035239/http://news.yahoo.com/peter-madoff-pleads-guilty-nyc-blaming-brother-163003155--finance.html |date=March 5, 2016 }}, Associated Press via Yahoo!News, June 29, 2012.</ref> Peter Madoff admitted hiding millions of dollars from the I.R.S. to avoid taxes, and took $200,000 from the firm for charitable donations even after the fraud was exposed.<ref>Neumeister, Larry, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gswmdZD8Wz4Xb5xxqHEDuPJp6AeA?docId=b0b309c5e5144b76898f65279390a643 \"Peter Madoff pleads guilty in NYC, blaming brother\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702074228/http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gswmdZD8Wz4Xb5xxqHEDuPJp6AeA?docId=b0b309c5e5144b76898f65279390a643 |date=July 2, 2012 }}, Associated Press via Google.com/hostednews, June 29, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hoffman |first=William |title=Madoff's brother pleads guilty to tax fraud; Singer Hill admits failing to file returns |newspaper=Tax Notes Today \u2013 2012 TNT 127\u20138 |date=June 29, 2012}}<!--|accessdate=07/02/2012--></ref>\n\nA forfeiture order requires Peter to surrender all of his assets to the government, including cash, homes, cars and a [[Rolex]] [[watch]]. A settlement reached with his family requires the forfeiture of assets held by his wife, Marion, his daughter, Shana Madoff Swanson, and other family members.<ref name=\"businessweek.com\"/>\n\nOn December 20, 2012, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison for his involvement in the Ponzi scheme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madoff Brother To Serve 10 Years In Prison For Role In Ponzi Scheme|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/174312/madoff-brother-to-serve-10-years-in-prison-for-role-in-ponzi-scheme|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130130051431/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/174312/madoff-brother-to-serve-10-years-in-prison-for-role-in-ponzi-scheme|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 30, 2013|publisher=NY1|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref>  He is currently serving his sentence at [[FCI-Miami]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ | title=Inmate Locator}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/mia/ |title = FCI Miami}}</ref>  His Federal Bureau of Prisons inmate number is 67118-054.  His scheduled release date is 13 August 2020.\n\n==Ruth Madoff==\n[[Ruth Madoff]] withdrew $5.5 million on November 25, 2008, and $10 million on December 10, 2008, from her brokerage account at Cohmad, a feeder fund which had an office in Madoff's headquarters and was part-owned by him.<ref name=\"business1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/business/ticker/2009/02/galvin_seeks_to.html |title=Galvin seeks to shut down firm with Madoff ties \u2013 Daily Business Update \u2013 The Boston Globe |publisher=Boston.com |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214122117/http://boston.com/business/ticker/2009/02/galvin_seeks_to.html |archivedate=February 14, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"marketsnews1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSLC60093820090212 |title=Medici's Kohn says did not get Madoff payments &#124; Markets &#124; Markets News &#124; Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Boris |last=Groendahl |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707173215/http://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSLC60093820090212 |archivedate=July 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  In November, she also received $2 million from her husband's London office, Madoff Securities International Ltd.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29911053 |title=Madoff's Wife Got $2 Million from UK Unit \u2013 Financials * Europe * News * Story |publisher=CNBC.com |date=March 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612003214/http://www.cnbc.com/id/29911053 |archivedate=June 12, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2009, a [[CBS News]] investigation discovered that the Madoffs were moving assets during the 2006 SEC investigation.  Madoff had purchased their $9.5 million Palm Beach mansion in March 1994 in his wife's name.  Not until December 10, 2006, did she apply for \"[[Homestead exemption|homestead]]\" status, shielding their home from [[creditor]]s.  Her initial application was rejected because there was no proof it was her primary residence, which protects homeowners who have obtained the exemption from seizure.<ref name=\"bloomberg6\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aj6f7pk8l_00&refer=home |title=Madoff Prosecutors Seek to Take Businesses, Loans (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On September 18, 2008, she reapplied for [[Homestead exemption|Homestead]] Exemption, and it was granted on January 12, 2009, after Madoff's arrest.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/><ref name=\"investigates1\"/>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing her assets, because they were already frozen by the federal government. The pension fund case was ''Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff'', FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nShe did not attend her husband's sentencing.<ref name=wapo_20090626>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Madoff to Forfeit $170 Billion In Assets Ahead of Sentencing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/26/AR2009062604652.html |work=The Washington Post |agency=Bloomberg News  |date=27 June 2009 |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first1=Amir | last1=Efrati | first2=Robert | last2=Frank | title=Madoff's Wife Cedes Asset Claim | date=June 28, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310004154/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 | archivedate=March 10, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> As part of her husband's sentencing terms, she agreed to give up all of her possessions in return for a promise that federal prosecutors would not go after the $2.5 million she can keep from the federal prosecutors. The money was not protected from civil legal actions pursued by a court-appointed trustee liquidating Madoff's assets or by investor lawsuits, however.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,529858,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Ruth Madoff Asks to Keep Her Fur Coat as U.S. Marshals Seize Penthouse | date=July 2, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919011333/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,529858,00.html | archivedate=September 19, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2009, she was sued by trustee, [[Irving Picard]] for $45 million, which supported her \"life of splendor\". According to court filings, she received more than $3 million from the business over the prior six years to pay personal expenses charged to her [[American Express]] card, and $2 million in payments to a business called PetCare RX. \"Ruth Madoff was never an employee of BLMIS yet millions of dollars belonging to BLMIS and its customers found their way into her personal accounts and investments without any legitimate business purpose or any value to BLMIS, simply because of her relationship with Bernard Madoff.\" She was also required to itemize all expenditures over $100.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/08/04/2009-08-04_buybuy_to_madoff_wifes_free_spending.html | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Bernie Madoff's wife, Ruth, agrees to account for monthly spending | first1=Robert | last1=Gearty | first2=Leo | last2=Standora | date=August 4, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907153908/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/08/04/2009-08-04_buybuy_to_madoff_wifes_free_spending.html | archivedate=September 7, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The case is Picard v. Madoff, 1:09-ap-1391, U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Southern District of New York (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/29/trustee-sues-ruth-madoff-for-448-million/?hpw | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for $44.8 Million | first=Zachery | last=Kouwe | date=July 29, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Patrick | last=Fitzgerald | title=Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for More Than $44 Million | date=July 30, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110832/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 | archivedate=January 27, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/17780712/Lawsuit-Against-Ruth-Madoff-Irving-Picard |title=Lawsuit Against Ruth Madoff (Irving Picard) |publisher=Scribd.com |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025184157/http://www.scribd.com/doc/17780712/Lawsuit-Against-Ruth-Madoff-Irving-Picard |archivedate=October 25, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe has been named in several civil actions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aFpv4l_8Vg8Q&refer=home |title=Bernard Madoff's Wife Ruth Will Hire Her Own Lawyer (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 9, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She is represented by attorney Peter Chavkin<ref name=\"virtualbrandchannel1\"/> and David Barres.\n\nRuth has not been charged with any crime, and has not been questioned by prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lynnley |last=Browning |title=The Loneliest Woman in New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/14/fashion/14ruth.html |work=New York Times |date=June 12, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207212218/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/14/fashion/14ruth.html |archivedate=December 7, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She has been seen riding the [[New York City Subway]] and apparently did not attend her husband's June 29, 2009, sentencing hearing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 |title=Madoff's Wife Cedes Asset Claim |last1=Efrati |first1=Amir |last2=Frank |first2=Robert |date=June 28, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805033258/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124612092335264949 |archivedate=August 5, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRuth Madoff's combined assets with her husband had a net worth of between $823 million and $826 million. She had $92.6 million in assets listed in her own name:<ref name=\"regionalnews1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/03152009/news/regionalnews/ruth_in_crosshair_159631.htm |title=RUTH IN CROSSHAIR$ \u2013 New York Post |publisher=Nypost.com |date=March 15, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=James |last=Doran |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418061814/http://www.nypost.com/seven/03152009/news/regionalnews/ruth_in_crosshair_159631.htm |archivedate=April 18, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the $7 million Upper East Side penthouse; an $11 million mansion in Palm Beach, Fla.; Antibes and France totaling $19 million; $45 million in municipal bonds and $17 million in cash; $8.8 million worth of yachts; and $2.6 million worth of jewelry.<ref name=\"virtualbrandchannel1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE52C57L20090313?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Madoff to appeal bail, net worth revealed &#124; U.S. |publisher=Reuters |date=March 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318085800/http://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE52C57L20090313?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |archivedate=March 18, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The SEC worked with federal prosecutors, who filed a notice with the federal court to seek forfeiture of all listed ill-gotten assets.<ref name=\"regionalnews1\"/><ref>{{cite news |first=Michael J. |last=de la Merced |authorlink= |title=Prosecutors Try to Recover Assets of Madoff's Wife |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/17/business/17madoff.html |work=New York Times |publisher= |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2009, [[United States district court#United States district judges|U.S. District Judge]] Louis Stanton, presiding over the SEC case, filed an order modifying the property asset freeze. Ruth Madoff's lawyers asserted that \"Only Ruth Madoff has a [[beneficial ownership]]\" to a Manhattan apartment; about $45 million in [[municipal bond]]s deposited at [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp., and approximately $17 million in cash in another account, at [[Wachovia|Wachovia Bank]] NA.  Ruth Madoff says these assets are \"unrelated\" to the alleged fraud, Stanton wrote without ruling on her claim.<ref name=\"bloomberg1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aWVQJMrRh7Qc&refer=home |title=Ruth Madoff Says Her $62 Million 'Unrelated' to Fraud (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=March 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, shortly before Bernie Madoff was sentenced, prosecutors reached an agreement allowing Ruth Madoff to keep $2.5 million, while taking and selling the Madoffs' other assets.<ref name=autogenerated1a>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/06/bernie-madoffs-wife-ruth-settles-with-court-appointed-trustee.html \"Bernie Madoff\u2019s wife Ruth settles with court-appointed trustee\"]</ref> The settlement, however, did not preclude others, such as the court-appointed trustee [[Irving Picard]] of [[BakerHostetler]] who was liquidating her husband's firm, from seeking to recover funds from her, for example as a wrongful transferee of funds transferred to her.<ref>[https://www.assetsearchblog.com/2009/06/27/will-ruth-madoff-keep-her-remaining-2-5-million-in-assets/ \"Will Ruth Madoff Keep Her Remaining $2.5 Million In Assets?\"]</ref> Bernie Madoff\u2019s lawyer had asked the government to allow his wife to keep $70 million in assets that were in her name, as he forfeited all rights to assets totaling $170 billion.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-ruth/ruth-madoff-forfeits-asset-claims-left-with-2-5-million-idUSTRE55Q0BF20090627 \"Ruth Madoff forfeits asset claims, left with $2.5 million\"]</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, 77-year-old Ruth Madoff agreed to pay $594,000 ($250,000 in cash, and $344,000 of [[Trust law|trusts]] for two of her grandchildren), and to surrender her remaining assets when she dies, to settle claims by the court-appointed trustee Picard liquidating her husband's firm for former customers.<ref name=autogenerated1a /> Picard had sued Ruth Madoff for $44.8 million, saying she had lived a \"life of splendor\" on the gains from the fraud committed by her husband, but settled for less, given her limited assets.<ref name=autogenerated1a /><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124889554637990959 \"Trustee Sues Ruth Madoff for More Than $44 Million,\"] ''The Wall Street Journal''.</ref> Picard said that the settlement was not evidence she knew of or participated in the fraud.<ref name=autogenerated1a /> She is required to provide reports to Picard about her expenditures often, as to any purchase over $100, to ensure she does not have any hidden bank accounts.<ref name=autogenerated2a>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/life-madoff-ruth-living-25-million-connecticut/story?id=36557458 \"Life After Madoff: Ruth Living on $2.5 Million in Connecticut\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/money-and-power/a9656715/bernie-madoff-ponzi-scheme-scandal-story-and-aftermath/ \"Bernie Madoff's Ponzi Scheme - How the Scandal Affected His Family, Ruth, Mark & Andrew\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Fred Wilpon==\n[[Sterling Equities]], a group of companies owned by [[Fred Wilpon]], was sued in December 2010, for $1 billion by trustee Picard. Wilpon owns the [[New York Mets]] baseball team, a [[SportsNet New York|sports cable network]] and extensive real estate holdings.  Picard charged that \"red flags\" were ignored, and there was no [[due diligence]].  He claimed that the Mets owners \"were simply in too deep \u2013 having substantially supported their businesses with Madoff money \u2013 to do anything but ignore the gathering clouds.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-05/mets-owners-may-follow-bayou-accord-in-any-settlement-deal-with-picard.html | work=Bloomberg | first1=Linda | last1=Sandler | first2=Bob | last2=Van Voris | title=Mets Bayou Accord May Be Model for a Madoff Suit Deal | date=February 5, 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812194501/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-05/mets-owners-may-follow-bayou-accord-in-any-settlement-deal-with-picard.html | archivedate=August 12, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  On February 10, 2011, former N.Y. governor [[Mario Cuomo]] was appointed as a mediator in the dispute between the trustee and Sterling.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/11/sports/11mediator.html?ref=sports | work=The New York Times | first1=Ken | last1=Belson | first2=Richard | last2=Sandomir | title=Mario Cuomo Is Named Mediator in the Mets-Madoff Case | date=February 10, 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206185752/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/11/sports/11mediator.html?ref=sports | archivedate=February 6, 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 19, 2012 Wilpon and Picard agreed to settle the lawsuit for $162 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/sports/baseball/mets-owners-pay-162-million-to-settle-madoff-suit.html |title=Mets' Owners Pay $162 Million to Settle Madoff Suit |accessdate=March 19, 2012 |date=March 19, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |first1=Richard |last1=Sandomir |first2=Ken |last2=Belson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320064540/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/sports/baseball/mets-owners-pay-162-million-to-settle-madoff-suit.html |archivedate=March 20, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Saul Katz==\n[[Saul Katz]], alongside Fred Wilpon, and other Sterling partners was sued by the Madoff trustee [[Irving Picard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=SECURITIES INVESTOR PROTECTION CORPORATION vs. BERNARD L. MADOFF INVESTMENT SECURITIES LLC |date= |website=}}</ref> Picard wrote of Katz: \"There are thousands of victims of Madoff\u2019s massive Ponzi scheme. But Saul Katz is not one of them.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/section/mlb/id/6090174|title=Madoff lawsuit: Mets owners owe victims $300M|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> Katz settled the accusations of willfully ignoring the Madoff fraud for $162 million thereby avoiding a federal trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-mets-idUSKCN0YN33E|title=N.Y. Mets owners reach revised deal with Madoff trustee|date=2016-06-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Greg Katz==\nGregory Katz, a Sterling Equities Partner alongside Fred Wilpon and Saul Katz, was sued by the Madoff trustee Irving Picard. Greg Katz was said to be intimately involved in Sterling\u2019s investments with Bernard L. Madoff<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/031811madoffwilpon.pdf|title=SECURITIES INVESTOR PROTECTION CORPORATION, vs BERNARD L. MADOFF INVESTMENT SECURITIES LLC,|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Katz opened his first Madoff account in January of 1992 and had interest in 31 accounts at the time the ponzi scheme was exposed to the public.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=Sterling Complaint|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Greg Katz was shown to have received approximately 23,527,313 in \"Fictitious Profits\" from individual or Sterling-controlled accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/0204sterlingcompaintfinal.PDF|title=Sterling Complaint|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Referring to Katz and other Sterling partners, Picard wrote: \"There are thousands of victims of Madoff\u2019s massive Ponzi scheme. But Saul Katz is not one of them. Neither is Fred Wilpon. And neither are the rest of the partners at Sterling Equities who, along with Fred Wilpon and Saul Katz, are sophisticated investors who oversee and control Sterling and its many businesses and investments.\" Picard also wrote that Sterling Partners such as Katz among the \"largest beneficiaries of Madoff\u2019s fraud.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Gregory Katz entered into a settlement agreement with the Madoff trustee Irving Picard in April 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/001734-katzwilponorder11-03605docket192.pdf|title=Madoff Katz Settlement|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Mark and Andrew Madoff==\nMadoff's sons Mark, 45, and Andrew, 42 worked in the trading arm in the New York office, but also raised money marketing the Madoff funds.<ref>{{cite web |author=Mike Greenlar / The Post Standard |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/how_warning_signs_eluded_berna.html |title=How warning signs eluded Bernard Madoff's man in Syracuse |publisher=Syracuse.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503015411/http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/how_warning_signs_eluded_berna.html |archivedate=May 3, 2009 |df=mdy-all |date=March 29, 2009 }}</ref>  Their assets were frozen on March 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last=Efrati |first=Amir |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123851832507274247 |title=Judge Freezes Assets of Madoff's Family - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127110832/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123851832507274247 |archivedate=January 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Madoff has contended that his sons were not involved in the fraud, a claim backed up by his longtime secretary, Eleanor Squillari; she believes that if the sons were involved in the fraud, she would have known about it.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/> However, there is some skepticism about claims that Mark and Andrew were not in on the fraud.<ref name='vfairmargolick'>{{cite news | first=David | last=Margolick | authorlink=David Margolick | title=The Madoff Chronicles, Part III: Did the Sons Know | date=July 2009 | url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/07/madoff200907 | work=Vanity Fair | accessdate=June 25, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619110150/http://www.vanityfair.com//politics//features//2009//07//madoff200907 | archivedate=June 19, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nUntil their deaths, the two had been estranged from their father since December 10, 2008, when he revealed that he was running a Ponzi scheme. They had not spoken with their mother either, only communicating with her through lawyers.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nIn 1998, the sons became directors of the London office, Madoff Securities International Ltd. and took stakes in the business. They were given loans by the New York office to buy their shares. Interest on the loans was paid by dividends made by the London operation.  Andrew had several million dollars invested with his father at the time the fraud was revealed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123275697375711899 |title=Madoff Sons Are Scrutinized Over Contacts With Some at Investment Arm - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 23, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Aaron |last1=Lucchetti |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126064918/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123275697375711899 |archivedate=January 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nAt the time of Mark's divorce, in 2000, his interest in the London office was valued at $5 million. Other family members with shares in the London business were Bernard's wife, Ruth, and brother, Peter.\n<ref name=\"article3\"/>\n\nThe New York business paid Mark $770,000 in 1999 and rewarded him with a deferred-compensation plan valued at $5 million, but he withdrew his personal funds he had invested with his father's investment-advisory operation some time before his divorce. He remarried Stephanie in 2003 in [[Nantucket]].<ref name=\"currentpage1\"/>\n\nProsecutors intend to seize [[promissory note]]s given to the Madoffs by Andrew and Mark from 2001 to October 2008. Mark Madoff owed his parents $22 million, and Andrew Madoff owed $9.5 million. There were two loans in 2008 from Bernard Madoff to Andrew Madoff: $4.3 million on Oct 6, and $250,000 on Sept. 21.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg6\"/><ref name=\"usdoj.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/madoffbailpendingsentencing.pdf |title=Madoff Bail Pending Sentencing |website=[[American Association for Justice]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226062438/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/madoffbailpendingsentencing.pdf |archivedate=February 26, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in Bridgeport, Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing their assets. They agreed to attachments of $2.5 million each to their [[Greenwich]]{{clarify|reason=which Greenwich?|date=March 2015}} homes. The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn June 16, 2009, former employees Richard Stahl and Reed Abend, filed separate lawsuits against Madoff's sons claiming nearly $2 million in [[deferred compensation]]. Stahl, a former vice president at [[Cantor Fitzgerald]], claims $1.34 million for 2008, when he earned more than $5 million for Madoff Securities. Abend wants $473,940.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/06/17/2009-06-17_bernie_madoffs_sons_should_pay_two_traders_suits_charge.html | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Bernie Madoff's sons should pay, two traders' suits charge | first=Jose | last=Martinez | date=June 17, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620183626/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/06/17/2009-06-17_bernie_madoffs_sons_should_pay_two_traders_suits_charge.html | archivedate=June 20, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2009 a civil lawsuit was filed against them by trustee, Picard, for a judgment in the aggregate amount of at least, $198,743,299. Peter Madoff and daughter, Shana, are also defendants.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125451222667260197 |title=Madoff Trustee Sues Swindler's Family |last1=Lucchetti |first1=Aaron |last2=Forsyth |first2=Jennifer S. |date=October 3, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032605/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125451222667260197 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/Complaint.pdf |title=Complaint |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183010/http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/Complaint.pdf |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nOn March 15, 2010 the defendants filed a motion to dismiss, citing they were also victims, that lawsuit is \"predicated on the faulty assumption\" that the sons exercised a compliance function over the investment advisory business.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703734504575126013209903810 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Chad | last=Bray | title=Madoff Sons: We're Victims | date=March 17, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005165720/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703734504575126013209903810 | archivedate=October 5, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 2010, on the second anniversary of his father's arrest, Mark Madoff was found dead in his New York City apartment from an apparent suicide. It was later ruled suicide by hanging by a New York City medical examiner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/40617952/ns/business-us_business/|title=Madoff son's suicide follows battle with trustee|date=2010-12-13|access-date=2016-08-28|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829065410/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/40617952/ns/business-us_business|archivedate=August 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2013, a UK court dismissed a $40 million case against the directors of Madoff's British unit.  The directors included the deceased Mark Madoff and the critically ill Andrew Madoff, being treated for [[mantle cell lymphoma]] in Seattle at the time of the verdict.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/10/18/us-madoff-court-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 | work=Reuters | title=UK court dismisses case against directors of Madoff unit | date=October 18, 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129164158/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/10/18/us-madoff-court-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 | archivedate=November 29, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, 2014, Andrew Madoff died of [[mantle cell lymphoma]] at [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City. He was 48.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/03/andrew-madoff-dies/15015719/ | work=USA Today | title=Bernard Madoff's son, 48, dies in cancer battle | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117183338/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/03/andrew-madoff-dies/15015719/ | archivedate=November 17, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Jeffry Picower==\n[[Jeffry Picower]] was an industrialist and philanthropist who seemed to be a favored Madoff beneficiary, and made outlandish profits from his investments with Madoff.  From 1996\u20132007 there were 14 instances of greater than 100% yearly returns, and 25 of greater than 50%.  From 1996\u20131999 his regular trading account made from 120\u2013550% a year.  Some evidence of backdating trades, instituted by Picower, was presented by trustee [[Irving Picard]].  \n\nIn June 2009, [[Irving Picard]], the trustee liquidating Madoff's assets, filed a lawsuit against Picower in the [[United States bankruptcy court|U.S. Bankruptcy Court]] for the Southern District of New York (Manhattan), seeking the return of $7.2 billion in profits, alleging that Picower and his wife Barbara knew or should have known that their rates of return were \"implausibly high\", with some accounts showing annual returns ranging from 120% to more than 550% from 1996 through 1998, and 950% in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE54C4HW20090513 |title=Lawsuit claims Picower profits from Madoff $5 billion |author=Santosh Nadgir and Grant McCool |publisher=Reuters |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/13/business/13madoff.html|title=Billions Withdrawn Before Madoff Arrest|last=Henriques|first=Diana B.|last2=Kouwe|first2=Zachery|date=May 12, 2009|website=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref>  According to a June 28, 2009, [[MSNBC]] article, that would make Picower and his wife the biggest beneficiaries of Madoff's scam, exceeding even Madoff himself.<ref name=MSNBC>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31510209 |title=Madoff may not have benefited most in scam |publisher=[[NBC News]] |last=Bernstein |first=Jake |date=June 28, 2009 |accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> The Picowers' lawyer, William D. Zabel of Schulte Roth & Zabel, responded that, \"They were totally shocked by his fraud and were in no way complicit in it.\"<ref name=NYT2/> \n\nOn December 17, 2010, it was announced that a settlement of $7.2 billion had been reached between Irving Picard and Barbara Picower, Picower's widow, the executor of the Picower estate to resolve the Madoff trustee suit, and repay losses in the Madoff fraud.<ref name=autogenerated32>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704034804576025392596402176 \"Widow to Return $7.2 Billion\"]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.necn.com/news/new-england/_NECN__Madoff_Trustee_Gets__game_Changing__7_2_Billion_Settlement_NECN-251405161.html \"Madoff Trustee Gets 'game Changing' 7.2 Billion Settlement\" - NECN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It was the largest single forfeiture in American judicial history.<ref name=autogenerated22>[https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/17/big-settlement-with-madoff-investor-near/?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=F574E8492F5B58974037B4B91A067DD1&gwt=pay \"Madoff Trustee Recovers $7.2 Billion for Victims of Scheme\" - The New York Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/000040-09-01197d-order.pdf \"ORDER PURSUANT TO SECTION 105(a) OF THE BANKRUPTCY CODE AND RULES 2002 AND 9019 OF THE FEDERAL RULES OF BANKRUPTCY PROCEDURE APPROVING AN AGREEMENT BY AND AMONG THE TRUSTEE AND THE PICOWER BLMIS ACCOUNT HOLDERS AND ISSUING A PERMANENT INJUNCTION\"]</ref>  \"Barbara Picower has done the right thing,\" US Attorney [[Preet Bharara]] said.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/madoff-client-jeffry-picower-netted-5-billion |title=Madoff Client Jeffry Picower Netted $5 Billion\u2014Likely More Than Madoff Himself |publisher=ProPublica |date=June 23, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208222252/http://www.propublica.org/article/madoff-client-jeffry-picower-netted-5-billion |archivedate=February 8, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Picower died before the settlement.\n\n==Frank DiPascali==\n[[Frank DiPascali]], 52, who referred to himself as \"director of [[option (finance)|option]]s trading\" and as \"[[chief financial officer]]\" at Madoff Securities, pleaded guilty  on August 11, 2009, to 10 counts:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/DiPascali,%20Frank%20Charges%20Chart.pdf |title=DiPascali, Frank Charges Chart |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411181741/http://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/DiPascali,%20Frank%20Charges%20Chart.pdf |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]], [[securities fraud]], investment advisor [[fraud]], [[mail fraud]], [[wire fraud]], [[perjury]], [[income tax evasion]], international [[money laundering]], falsifying books and records of a broker-dealer and an investment advisor. In his allocution to the Court, he admitted that he had known for at least two decades that Madoff was a fraud; he claimed to have learned in the late 1980s or early 1990s that no actual trading was occurring in Madoff's investment-advisory client accounts. About 2002, he set up an account for himself at the firm named after his fishing yacht, Dorothy Jo. Having never made a contribution, he withdrew more than $5 million. His salary and bonuses were over $2 million annually. He agreed in a [[Plea bargain|plea agreement]] and the signed Information document<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf |title=DiPascali Information - Signed |website=[[American Association for Justice]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609135048/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/usao-sdny/legacy/2012/04/16/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf |archivedate=June 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/081109DiPascaliplea.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=DiPascali Plea |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165331/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/081109DiPascaliplea.pdf |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> to connect the dots and to name names, with sentencing originally anticipated in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Blotter/Madoff/story?id=8304447&page=1 |title=Frank DiPascali Pleads Guilty, Bernard Madoff's Accomplice \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=August 11, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515090821/http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/Madoff/story?id=8304447&page=1 |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He faced a maximum of 125 years in prison. Prosecutors sought more than $170 million in forfeiture, the same amount sought from Madoff, which represents about double the funds deposited by investors and later disbursed to other investors. The same day, a [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] civil complaint<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SEC2009-182.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=SEC CHARGES KEY MADOFF LIEUTENANT FOR OPERATING AND CONCEALING FRAUD THROUGH BOGUS TRADES AND DOCUMENTS |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005010430/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SEC2009-182.pdf |archivedate=October 5, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> was filed against DiPascali.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124999709846222617 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first1=Chad |last1=Bray |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |title='All Fake': Key Madoff Executive Admits Guilt |date=August 12, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223220308/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124999709846222617 |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA college dropout, he joined Madoff's firm in 1975 at age 18 and eventually oversaw the day-to-day operations of Madoff's investment-advisory business.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> He was the person many of Madoff's investors dealt with regarding their accounts.  Madoff told investors DiPascali executed trades. However, a court-appointed trustee found that no trading had occurred for at least 13 years. Prosecutors have asked at least three employees, Eric Lipkin, JoAnn Crupi, and Robert Cardile, who is Mr. DiPascali's brother-in-law, about his role in the firm.<ref name=\"30909Wsj\"/>\nInvestors spoke to these other employees and would fax orders if they needed to withdraw money. DiPascali's name was sometimes given as an alternate contact.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123249539137500157 |title=Madoff's Point Man Is Cast in Same Role for Prosecutors |date=January 21, 2009 |accessdate=March 25, 2009 |work=The Wall Street Journal |first1=Aaron |last1=Lucchetti |first2=Amir |last2=Efrati |first3=Tom |last3=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716030328/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123249539137500157 |archivedate=July 16, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to an SEC memo, DiPascali \"responded evasively\" to questioning following Madoff's arrest.<ref name=\"1223WsjA\">{{cite news | last =Efrati | first =Amir | author2 =Aaron Lucchetti | author3 =Tom Lauricella | title =Probe Eyes Audit Files, Role of Aide To Madoff | work =[[The Wall Street Journal]] | publisher =[[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] | date =December 23, 2008 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122999256957528605 | accessdate =December 23, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150521234747/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122999256957528605 | archivedate =May 21, 2015 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, at a court hearing, he gave detailed information how Madoff was meticulous in the management of the fraud.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/12/07/madoff-sweated-scam-details/3890069/ Madoff sweated scam details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809134721/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/12/07/madoff-sweated-scam-details/3890069/ |date=August 9, 2017 }} USA Today, December 7, 2013</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2015, while still awaiting sentencing, DiPascali died of lung cancer.<ref>{{cite news | title=Former Madoff Aide Frank DiPascali Dies at Age 58 of Lung Cancer | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-madoff-aide-frank-dipascali-dies-at-age-58-of-lung-cancer-1431361169 | author=Yang, Stephanie | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=May 11, 2015 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604045956/http://www.wsj.com/articles/former-madoff-aide-frank-dipascali-dies-at-age-58-of-lung-cancer-1431361169 | archivedate=June 4, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Enrica Cotellessa-Pitz==\nEnrica Cotellessa-Pitz, was a [[Comptroller|controller]] at Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities LLC, but not a licensed [[Certified Public Accountant|certified public accountant]]. Her signature is on checks from BMIS to [[Cohmad Securities]] Corp. representing commission payments. She was the liaison between the SEC and BLMIS regarding the firm's financial statements. The SEC has removed the BMIS statements from its website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-why-is-enrica-co.php |title=Bernie Madoff: Why Is Bernie's Controller, Enrica Cotellessa-Pitz, Getting A Pass In The Press? |date=May 11, 2009 |website=Mrs Panstreppon's Blog |publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515125348/http://tpmcafe.talkingpointsmemo.com/talk/blogs/mrs_panstreppon/2009/05/bernie-madoff-why-is-enrica-co.php |archivedate=May 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Madoff backroom staff==\nIn 2010 five backroom employees pleaded not guilty to charges including conspiracy to commit securities fraud. On October 2, 2012 they maintained their innocence to further charges including bank fraud and tax offenses.<ref name=\"westlaw\">{{cite web |url=https://content.next.westlaw.com/Document/I6a91a730877511e293329f3d310cb5cf/View/FullText.html |title=Former Madoff aide seeks release of funds for his defense |last=Vaughan |first=Bernard |date=March 7, 2013 |website=[[Westlaw]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-access=registration}}</ref> Their trial (USA v O'Hara et al. in U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, No. 10-0228) opened on October 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-employees-trial/judge-sets-october-2013-trial-date-for-ex-madoff-backroom-staff-idUSL1E8L2FQK20121002 |title=Judge sets October 2013 trial date for ex-Madoff backroom staff |last=McCool |first=Grant |date=October 2, 2012 |website=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |quote={{blist|Five ex-Madoff employees face additional charges|All plead not guilty to allegations of role in fraud}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033647/https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-employees-trial/judge-sets-october-2013-trial-date-for-ex-madoff-backroom-staff-idUSL1E8L2FQK20121002 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Annette Bongiorno===\nAnnette Bongiorno was a long-time personal secretary and aide to Madoff. Bongiorno joined Madoff Investment Securities in 1967, soon after graduating high school; only Madoff's wife Ruth and brother Peter were at the firm longer. She recruited Frank DiPascali, then her next-door neighbor in [[Howard Beach]], to the firm.<ref name=MadoffChronicles>{{cite book|title=The Madoff Chronicles|last=Ross|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist)|publisher=[[Disney Publishing Worldwide|Kingswell]]|year=2015|isbn=9781484781401}}</ref>\n\nShe is accused of directing two assistants, Semone Anderson and Winnie Jackson, to generate fictitious trading tickets for customer accounts.<ref name=\"30909Wsj\">{{cite news | last =Efrati | first =Amir | title =Madoff Aide Allegedly Got Fake 'Tickets' of Trading | work =[[The Wall Street Journal]] | publisher =[[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] | date =March 9, 2009 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123655521154265891 | accessdate =March 9, 2009 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20160310201425/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123655521154265891 | archivedate =March 10, 2016 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"030909Street\">{{cite news | last =Woefel | first =Joseph | title =Madoff Aide Allegedly Got Fake Trading 'Tickets' | work =[[TheStreet.com]] | date =March 9, 2009 | url =http://www.thestreet.com/story/10469058/1/madoff-aide-allegedly-got-fake-trading-tickets.html?cm_ven=GOOGLEN | accessdate =March 9, 2009 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090312081858/http://www.thestreet.com/story/10469058/1/madoff-aide-allegedly-got-fake-trading-tickets.html?cm_ven=GOOGLEN | archivedate =March 12, 2009 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\nDuring the 1980s, Bongiorno recruited small investors from Howard Beach. Their money was held in accounts called \"RuAnn\" (named after Annette and her husband Rudy).  Madoff paid for her honeymoon airfare. She owns homes in [[Manhasset, New York]], and [[Boca Raton, Florida]], with a combined assessment of $3.85 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=auoogFU4GmKc&refer=home |title=Madoff Key Aide Recruited Her Neighbors as Investors (Update2) - Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=February 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525071928/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109 |archivedate=May 25, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/03/25/2009-03-25_bernie_madoffs_secretary_comes_away_with.html |title=Bernie Madoff's secretary comes away with mansions and Mercedes |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=New York |first=Tracy |last=Connor |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328091853/http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/03/25/2009-03-25_bernie_madoffs_secretary_comes_away_with.html |archivedate=March 28, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nBongiorno was arrested in November 2010 and charged with conspiracy, securities fraud, and tax evasion.  She faced up to 75 years in jail.<ref name=\"wsjnov2010\">{{cite news | last = Hurtado | first = Patricia | title = Ex-Madoff Employee Bongiorno Unable to Post Bail, Must Remain in Custody | work = [[Bloomberg.com]] | publisher = Bloomberg | date = November 23, 2010 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/ex-madoff-employee-bongiorno-unable-to-post-bail-must-remain-in-custody.html | accessdate = November 23, 2010 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101127005529/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/ex-madoff-employee-bongiorno-unable-to-post-bail-must-remain-in-custody.html | archivedate = November 27, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  After a brief incarceration in late 2010 and after $7.6 million were seized from Bongiornos' accounts (out of an estimated $14 million personal take), Bongiorno was released to house arrest with ankle monitor at her Manhasset, Long Island, residence on a $3.6 million personal recognizance bond secured by eight co-signers.<ref name=\"dailybeast20110107\">{{cite news| last=Dodds Frank| first=Allan| title=Bernie Madoff's Secretary Annette Bongiorno Out on Bail| date=January 7, 2011| url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/01/07/bernie-madoffs-secretary-annete-bongiorno-out-on-bail.html| accessdate=March 15, 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318205443/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/01/07/bernie-madoffs-secretary-annete-bongiorno-out-on-bail.html| archivedate=March 18, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Her trial opened on October 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> In a bid for leniency, Bongiorno maintained that Madoff deceived her into printing bogus trade records.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2014/dec/09/madoff-secretary-six-years-prison-fraud|title='Compliant' Madoff secretary gets six years in prison over fraud scheme|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2014-12-09}}</ref> She claimed that she was merely doing the same thing she had been doing for over 40 years\u2013bolstering evidence that Madoff began his Ponzi scheme far earlier than 1991.<ref name=MadoffChronicles/>\n\nBongiorno was convicted in March 2014 on charges of securities fraud and tax evasion. In December 2014, Bongiorno was sentenced to six years in federal prison. The sentence was far shorter than even the eight- to ten-year sentence recommended by her own lawyer. However, federal judge [[Laura Taylor Swain]] believed Bongiorno's \"small stature\"\u2013she is only {{convert|4.5|ft|m}} tall\u2013would put her in a \"vulnerable position\" in prison.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/09/madoff-secretary-gets-6-years-after-judge-cites-small-stature/ | work=New York Post | first=Rich | last=Calder | title=Madoff secretary gets 6 years after judge cites 'small stature' | date=December 9, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018015702/http://nypost.com/2014/12/09/madoff-secretary-gets-6-years-after-judge-cites-small-stature/ | archivedate=October 18, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Daniel Bonventre===\n[[Daniel Bonventre]] worked as company director of operations and as an accountant for Madoff since the 1960s. He was arrested in 2010 and charged with allegedly having created false and fraudulent books and records, conspiracy, securities fraud, and tax-related charges. He is also being sued by the SEC for falsifying records. On those initial charges he may be sentenced to a maximum of 77 years in prison if convicted. In Dec 2012 Bonventre's request for access to his seized funds for legal defense purposes was turned down by U.S. District Court. In March 2013 a three-judge appeals court granted a hearing in a lower court on his seized funds access request.<ref name=\"westlaw\" /> His trial opened on October 7, 2013 .<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> On December 8, 2014, Bonventre was sentenced to 10 years in prison after being convicted on securities fraud and tax-evasion charges for his involvement in Madoff's $17.5 billion fraud.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-08/madoff-ex-operations-chief-bonventre-given-10-years.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Erik | last=Larson | title=Madoff Aide Gets a Sentencing Break for Not Being Madoff | date=December 8, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230042829/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-08/madoff-ex-operations-chief-bonventre-given-10-years.html | archivedate=December 30, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Joann Crupi===\nJoann Crupi is a former investment advisor to Madoff. Her trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> A jury found her guilty, and on December 15, 2014 Crupi was sentenced to 6 years in prison for her role in the scam.<ref name=\"nyp20141216\">{{cite news |last=Neumeister |first=Larry |date=December 16, 2014 |title=Former Madoff account manager sentenced to six years |url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/16/former-madoff-account-manager-sentenced-to-six-years/ |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018015659/http://nypost.com/2014/12/16/former-madoff-account-manager-sentenced-to-six-years/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===George Perez===\nGeorge Perez is a former computer programmer of Madoff. His trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> A jury found him guilty, and on December 10, 2014 Perez was sentenced to 2\u00bd years in prison for his role in the scam.<ref name=\"usat20141211\">{{cite news |last=McCoy |first=Kevin |date=December 11, 2014 |title=Leniency for ex-Madoff staffer sparks complaint |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/12/10/madoff-george-perez-sentencing/19967501/ |work=[[USA Today]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222095147/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/12/10/madoff-george-perez-sentencing/19967501/ |archivedate=December 22, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Jerome O'Hara===\nJerome O'Hara is a former computer programmer of Madoff. His trial was to open on Oct 7, 2013.<ref name=\"reuters20121002\" /> On December 9, 2014, he was sentenced to 2 1/2 years in prison for his role in the scam.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/09/us-madoff-workers-sentencing-idUSKBN0JN20420141209 | work=Reuters | title=Ex-Madoff manager, computer programmer get prison terms | date=December 9, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211339/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/09/us-madoff-workers-sentencing-idUSKBN0JN20420141209 | archivedate=September 24, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sosnik Bell and Co.==\nEven before Sosnik and Bell took over a small [[New Jersey]] accounting firm in the early 1990s, Madoff and his affiliate, Cohmad Securities, encouraged hundreds of individual investors to retain the firm for an annual fee of $800 for routine [[Records management|recordkeeping]] to handle their monthly statements. The firm compiled profits, losses, and gains, and prepared tax-summary statements and schedules to be used by a client's regular accountant for [[income tax]] returns, producing one-page monthly statements and a quarterly statement.<ref name=\"article2\"/>\n\n==Fairfield Greenwich Group==\n[[Fairfield Greenwich Group]], based in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]], had a \"Fairfield Sentry\" fund which was one of many feeder funds that gave investors portals to Madoff.  Fairfield, in turn, set up further feeder funds such as \"Lion Fairfield Capital Management\" in [[Singapore]] and \"Stellar US Absolute Return,\" all conduits to Madoff, directing a total of $7.5 billion.<ref name=\"1219NYTmad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/20/business/20madoff.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 20, 2008 |title=Madoff Scheme Kept Rippling Outward, Across Borders |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |first=Diana B. |last=Henriques |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409233032/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/20/business/20madoff.html |archivedate=April 9, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMadoff was able to pitch his business in Europe and South America indirectly through Fairfield fund's founder, [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Walter Noel and Family|Walter Noel]]'s son-in-law Andr\u00e9s Piedrahita.<ref name=\"l'affaire madoff\">{{cite news | last =Schwartz | first =Nelson D. | title =Madoff Dealings Tarnish a Private Swiss Bank | work =[[The New York Times]] | date =December 24, 2008 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/24/business/worldbusiness/24ubp.html | accessdate =December 23, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130621035330/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/24/business/worldbusiness/24ubp.html | archivedate =June 21, 2013 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> Another Noel son-in-law's territory included Asia.  Madoff began advertising openly, contrary to his initial strategy of handpicking investors.<ref name=\"1219NYTmad\" />  The company is listed as a defendant in an investor lawsuit filed in [[Miami]].<ref name=\"article2\"/>\n\nIn August 2008, [[JPMorgan Chase]],  pulled $250 million from this Madoff feeder fund account.  Chase had become \"concerned about lack of transparency,\" and due-diligence  which had \"raised doubts\" about Madoff's operation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chew |first=Robert |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1887338,00.html |title=Madoff's Banker: Where Was JPMorgan Chase? |publisher=TIME |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428114723/http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1887338,00.html |archivedate=April 28, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] filed a civil action charging Fairfield Greenwich with fraud,  breaching its fiduciary duty to clients by failing to provide promised due diligence on its investments.  The complaint seeks a fine and restitution to Massachusetts investors for losses and disgorgement of performance fees paid to Fairfield by those investors. It alleges that in 2005 Mr. Madoff coached Fairfield staff about ways to answer questions from SEC attorneys who were looking into [[Harry Markopolos]]' complaint about Madoff's operations.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctfairfield/fairfieldidx.htm |title=Securities: Fairfield Greenwich |publisher=Sec.state.ma.us |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123859307450378115?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Madoff Feeder Is Charged in Fraud - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 | first1=Robert | last1=Frank | first2=Tom | last2=Lauricella}}</ref>  The Secretary of State has no plans to settle the lawsuit in spite of the fact that Fairfield Greenwich has offered to repay all Massachusetts investors, and is expected to force Fairfield to explain [[e-mails]] and other evidence he has uncovered that appear to show company officials knew about potential problems with Madoff but failed to disclose them to clients.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.boston.com/business/articles/2009/08/14/galvin_wont_settle_madoff_case/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Galvin won't settle Madoff case | first=Beth | last=Healy | date=August 14, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004234410/http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2009/08/14/galvin_wont_settle_madoff_case/ | archivedate=October 4, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE57D3X820090814 | work=Reuters | title=Mass. regulator will not settle Madoff feeder suit | date=August 14, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817165519/http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE57D3X820090814 | archivedate=August 17, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing Noel's and Tucker's assets. Noel agreed to attachments of $10 million to his Greenwich home, and $2 million from Jeffrey Tucker.  Noel's attorney is Glenn Kurtz, and Tucker's is Stanley Tawdry, Jr..  The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn May 18, 2009, the hedge fund was sued by bankruptcy trustee, [[Irving Picard]].  The complaint seeks a return of $3.2 billion during the period from 2002 \u2013 Madoff's arrest in December 2008.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/19/business/19madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Hedge Funds Over Losses to Madoff | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=May 19, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005112727/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/19/business/19madoff.html | archivedate=October 5, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, the money may already be in the hands of Fairfield's own clients, who are likely off-limits to Picard, since they weren't direct investors with Madoff.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2009/05/19/picards-latest-a-huge-lawsuit-against-fairfield-greenwich/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Picard's Latest: A Huge Lawsuit Against Fairfield Greenwich | first=Ashby | last=Jones | date=May 19, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812070718/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2009/05/19/picards-latest-a-huge-lawsuit-against-fairfield-greenwich/ | archivedate=August 12, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2009, Fairfield Sentry, based in the British Virgin Islands, filed a lawsuit seeking to recover more than $919 million in investment management and performance fees that it paid to Fairfield.  The lawsuit alleges breach of [[fiduciary]] duty, and [[unjust enrichment]]. It is \"the largest victim of the fraud perpetrated by Bernard L. Madoff,\" losing $7 billion.\nThe defendants include founders [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Walter Noel and Family|Walter Noel]] and [[Fairfield Greenwich Group#Jeffrey Tucker|Jeffrey Tucker]] and other fund partners who the plaintiffs allege \"failed to fulfill their contractual obligations to use best efforts to supervise the operations\" of Madoff-related investments and to \"oversee the day-to-day investment activities of the fund.\"  The case is Fairfield Sentry Ltd. v. Fairfield Greenwich Group, 601687/2009, New York State Supreme Court (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aM2myGLTkcBQ&refer=home | work=Bloomberg | title=Fairfield Greenwich Asks to Dismiss Suits Over Madoff (Update2) | date=December 23, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 | archivedate=June 13, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2009, Justice Edward Alexander Bannister granted the request to liquidate the Fairfield Sentry funds, worth more than $7.2 billion in December 2008, now less than $70 million, incorporated in 1990 under the mutual fund statutes of the British Virgin Islands and technically under the control of their local directors.\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/22/business/22madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Judge Approves Liquidation of Madoff Feeder Funds | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=July 22, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001063730/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/22/business/22madoff.html | archivedate=October 1, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sonja Kohn==\nOn December 10, 2010, [[Irving Picard]] sued [[Sonja Kohn]] and her bank, [[Bank Medici]], for $58.8 billion, accusing Kohn of being a \"criminal soul mate\" of [[Bernard Madoff|Madoff]].  She was accused of directing $9.1 billion to Madoff's fraud, about half of the actual money lost.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/madoff-trustee-sues-sonja-kohn-for-19-6-billion-treble-damages-via-rico.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Bob | last=Van Voris | title=Madoff Firm Trustee Seeks $50 Billion as Clawback Window Closes | date=December 13, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215204342/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/madoff-trustee-sues-sonja-kohn-for-19-6-billion-treble-damages-via-rico.html | archivedate=December 15, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/madoff-trustee-seeks-19-6-billion-from-austrian-banker/?hp | work=The New York Times | first1=Diana B. | last1=Henriques | first2=Peter | last2=Lattman | title=Madoff Trustee Seeks $19.6 Billion From Austrian Banker | date=December 10, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033037/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/madoff-trustee-seeks-19-6-billion-from-austrian-banker/?hp | archivedate=October 20, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 18, 2013 Kohn was found innocent of the civil charges leveled against her by the High Court in London and thus relieved of any liability to the Madoff creditors.<ref name=\"reuters20131018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-court/uk-court-dismisses-case-against-directors-of-madoff-unit-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 |title=UK court dismisses case against directors of Madoff unit |last1=Fletcher |first1=Laurence |last2=Shirbon |first2=Estelle |date=October 18, 2013 |editor-last=Holmes |editor-first=David |website=[[Reuters]] |location=London |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033529/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-court/uk-court-dismisses-case-against-directors-of-madoff-unit-idUSBRE99H0PO20131018 |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==J. Ezra Merkin==\n[[J. Ezra Merkin]], a prominent [[Financial adviser|investment advisor]] and philanthropist, has been sued for his role in running a \"feeder fund\" for Madoff.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Chad |date=17 December 2008 |title=GMAC's Merkin, Ascot Fund sued over Madoff investments |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/gmacs-merkin-ascot-fund-sued-over-madoff-investments |work=MarketWatch |location=New York |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> Merkin informed investors in his $1.8 billion [[Ascot Partners]] fund on December 11 that he was among those who suffered substantial personal losses, since all of the fund's money was invested with Madoff.<ref name=\"NYTAscot\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/20081216_MERKIN.pdf|title=Letter from Merkin to Investors|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 19, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114200414/http://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/20081216_MERKIN.pdf|archivedate=January 14, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Connecticut]] [[Attorney general|Attorney General]] [[Richard Blumenthal]] is examining the role boards of nonprofits played, in possibly not conducting due diligence on donors' contributions.<ref name=\"ct nonprofit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/wallstreet/2008/12/22/madoff-blumenthal-charities-biz-wall-cz_cc_1222charities.html?partner=contextstory|title=Blumenthal May Investigate Charities Ripped Off By Madoff|date=December 22, 2008|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=December 24, 2008|first=Carrie|last=Coolidge|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130123095253/http://www.forbes.com/2008/12/22/madoff-blumenthal-charities-biz-wall-cz_cc_1222charities.html?partner=contextstory|archivedate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2009, New York Attorney General [[Andrew Cuomo]] filed civil [[fraud]] charges<ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Complaint - Final |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307143258/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against J. Ezra Merkin  alleging he \"betrayed hundreds of investors\" by moving $2.4 billion of clients' money to Bernard Madoff without their knowledge.  The complaint states, he lied about putting the money with Madoff, failed to disclose conflicts of interest, and collected over $470 million in fees for his three hedge funds, Ascot Partners LP with Ascot Fund Ltd., Gabriel Capital Corp. and Ariel Fund Ltd.  He promised he would actively manage the money, but instead, he misguided investors about his Madoff investments in quarterly reports, in investor presentations, and in conversations with investors. \"Merkin held himself out to investors as an investing guru...In reality, Merkin was but a master marketer.\"<ref name=civilfraud1>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-merkin/merkin-charged-with-civil-fraud-in-madoff-case-idUSTRE53548420090406 |title=Merkin charged with civil fraud in Madoff case |last1=Graybow |first1=Martha |last2=Chasan |first2=Emily |date=April 6, 2009 |editor-last=Moss |editor-first=Brian |website=[[Reuters]] |location=New York |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905235040/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-merkin/merkin-charged-with-civil-fraud-in-madoff-case-idUSTRE53548420090406 |archivedate=September 5, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf |title=Merkin Exhibits (1/3) |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604042707/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Exhibits (2/3) |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604044008/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Merkin Exhibits (3/3) |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604042648/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf |archivedate=June 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the complaint accused Merkin of improperly commingling his personal funds with his hedge fund accounts and using some of the money to buy artwork worth more than $91 million. Mr. Cuomo's office is seeking restitution and unspecified damages from Mr. Merkin.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/07/business/07madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Cuomo Sues Over Madoff Investments | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=April 7, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616172623/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/07/business/07madoff.html | archivedate=June 16, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2009, Madoff Bankruptcy Trustee, [[Irving Picard]] filed a lawsuit<ref>{{cite news |url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf |work=The New York Times |title=Madoff_Complaint |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616181923/http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf |archivedate=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against Merkin seeking to recover almost $500 million withdrawn from Madoff accounts in the last six years. The complaint alleges that since 1995, Merkin steered more than $1 billion to Madoff through three private hedge funds, Ascot Partners, Ariel Fund and Gabriel Capital. Since 2002, the funds withdrew at least $494 million from Madoff \u2014 returns that Merkin \"knew or should have known\" were fraudulent.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/08/business/08madoff.html | work=The New York Times | title=Trustee Sues Madoff Hedge Fund Investor | first=Diana B. | last=Henriques | date=May 8, 2009 | accessdate=May 21, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616072434/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/08/business/08madoff.html | archivedate=June 16, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of May 18, 2009, Merkin's control of Ascot, Gabriel and Ariel hedge funds are to be placed into [[receivership]] for [[liquidation]] by Guidepost Partners. One receiver will be responsible for managing the remaining money, nearly $1 billion, in the Gabriel and Ariel funds, and another will be responsible for overseeing Ascot, whose entire $1.8 billion in assets was lost to Madoff's Ponzi scheme.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124274106281334617 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Merkin to Put Funds in Receivership | date=May 20, 2009 | first=Liz | last=Rappaport | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217111859/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124274106281334617 | archivedate=December 17, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Cohmad Securities Corp.==\n[[Cohmad Securities]], whose name combines \"Cohn\" and \"Madoff,\" founded in 1985 by Madoff and Cohn, Madoff's friend and former neighbor.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=amvc1G6COZes | work=Bloomberg | title=Madoff Bankruptcy Trustee Sues Cohmad Securities (Update2) | date=June 22, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 | archivedate=June 13, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn owned 48% of Cohmad, and his daughter  Marcia, who served as president and chief compliance officer owned 25%.  Madoff owned 15%. Mr. Madoff's brother, Peter owned 9%, and Mr. Cohn's brother owned 1%, and another unnamed Cohmad employee owned 1%.\n<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124568875235837661#articleTabs%3Darticle |title=SEC Files Fraud Charges Against Cohmad, Co-Founder in Madoff Case |last1=Scannell |first1=Kara |last2=Frank |first2=Robert |date=June 23, 2009 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032737/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124568875235837661#articleTabs%3Darticle |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe brokerage firm lists its address as Madoff's firm's address in New York City. Cohmad employs [[Robert Jaffe (stockbroker)|Robert Jaffe]], as vice president.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123189380284379481?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Cohmad, Jaffe Draw Closer Look - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=January 14, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first1=Robert |last1=Frank |first2=Tom |last2=Lauricella |first3=Aaron |last3=Lucchetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206185751/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123189380284379481?mod=googlenews_wsj |archivedate=February 6, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Jaffe is married to Ellen Shapiro, daughter of Boston philanthropist [[Carl J. Shapiro]], the founder and former chairman of apparel company Kay Windsor Inc., and an early investor and close friend of Madoff.  Jaffe reportedly convinced the elder Shapiro to invest $250 million with Madoff just 10 days before Madoff's arrest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/localnews/content/local_news/epaper/2008/12/20/a1a_jaffe_1221.html |title=Scandal sullies Robert Jaffe as feds probe ties to Bernard Madoff |last=Musgrave |first=Jane |date=December 20, 2008 |website=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110617003417/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/localnews/content/local_news/epaper/2008/12/20/a1a_jaffe_1221.html |archivedate=June 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nJaffe, a philanthropist, \"worked the [[Palm Beach, Florida]] circuit, and attracted many Palm Beach Country Club members as investors.\"<ref name=\"Vics1\">{{cite news | last =Frank | first =Robert | author2 =Peter Lattman | author3 =Dionne Searcey | author4 =Aaron Lucucchetti | title =Fund Fraud Hits Big Names; Madoff's Clients Included Mets Owner, GMAC Chairman, Country-Club Recruits | work =[[Wall Street Journal]] | date =December 13, 2008 | url =https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122914169719104017?mod=djemalertNEWS | accessdate =December 13, 2008 | url-status =live | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170806062445/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122914169719104017?mod=djemalertNEWS | archivedate =August 6, 2017 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> Jaffe brought in 150 accounts and more than $1 billion to Madoff.  Madoff paid Jaffe directly through accounts he kept with Madoff at much higher returns than earned by other investors. Between 1996 and 2008, Jaffe withdrew at least $150 million, and the SEC claims he was aware Madoff was engaged in fictitious trading.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>  Jaffe has said he received a commission of 1% to 2% from an investor's first profit, and he paid commissions to financial advisers who steered cash to Madoff's fund.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5562935.ece |title=Madoff associate skips court hearing \u2013 Times Online |publisher=Business.timesonline.co.uk |date=January 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=London |first=Christine |last=Seib |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612101142/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5562935.ece |archivedate=June 12, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.muckety.com/2009/01/15/cohmad-securities-robert-jaffe-face-tough-questions-about-madoff-ties/10151 |title=Cohmad Securities, Robert Jaffe face tough questions about Madoff ties &#124; Muckety.com \u2013 See the news |publisher=News.muckety.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430120644/http://news.muckety.com/2009/01/15/cohmad-securities-robert-jaffe-face-tough-questions-about-madoff-ties/10151 |archivedate=April 30, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRichard Spring, of [[Boca Raton, Florida]], received payments from Cohmad for many years in exchange for bringing investors and investment ideas to Madoff.\n\nAlvin J. \"Sonny\" Delaire, Jr. of [[Far Hills, New Jersey]] also recruited clients for Madoff's advisory business.  Delaire has been sued by Dr. Martin and Suzanne Schulman of [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]], New York, claiming they were induced by Delaire to make investments with Madoff \"based on fraudulent misrepresentations by Delaire and his omissions to disclose material facts.\"  The lawsuit seeks a minimum of $9.6 million in damages since 2002 from Delaire.\nThe case is Martin Schulman, M.D. and Suzanne Schulman v Alvin J. Delaire, Jr. 09-3871[[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York]] (Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/managementIssues/idUSN1746032320090417 |title=U.S. investors sue Madoff-linked broker for fraud |publisher=Reuters |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009215352/http://www.reuters.com/article/managementIssues/idUSN1746032320090417 |archivedate=October 9, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCohmad had fewer than 650 client accounts, and made 99.7% of its sales from brokerage services to Madoff's larger broker-dealer.  In its audited financial statements for the 12 months ending June 30, 2008, Cohmad said revenue from Madoff Securities totaled $3,736,829.  Its total sales for the same period were $3,748,397.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muckety.com/Cohmad-Securities/5058711.muckety|title=Cohmad Securities at Muckety.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321100955/http://www.muckety.com/Cohmad-Securities/5058711.muckety|archivedate=March 21, 2009|df=mdy-all|access-date=April 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2009, [[William F. Galvin]], [[Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts]], who is in charge of the state's securities issues, filed suit against Jaffe, who promoted Madoff's funds to wealthy investors in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/general/view/2009_01_15_William_Galvin_sues_salesman_Robert_Jaffe:_Demands_testimony/srvc=business&position=recent_bullet |title=William Galvin Sues Salesman Robert Jaffe \u2013 Demands Testimony |date=January 15, 2009 |website=[[Boston Herald]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224010342/http://bostonherald.com/business/general/view/2009_01_15_William_Galvin_sues_salesman_Robert_Jaffe%3A_Demands_testimony/srvc%3Dbusiness%26position%3Drecent_bullet |archivedate=February 24, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On February 4, compelled to testify, Jaffe invoked his [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] right.  Marcia Cohn, Maurice Cohn, and Alvin Delaire, Jr. failed to appear. On February 11, 2009, Galvin filed a complaint<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf |title=Cohmand Securities Complaint |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211040/http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |website=William Francis Galvin, Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts}}</ref> seeking to revoke the Massachusetts license of Cohmad Securities Corp., an accounting of all Massachusetts investors Cohmad referred to Madoff's company, all the fees it earned doing so (more than $67 million), and a fine.  It cited $526,000 in referral fees paid from Madoff Investments, to Cohmad, to Vienna [[Bank Medici]] majority owner, [[Sonja Kohn]], which she subsequently denied.<ref name=\"business1\"/><ref name=\"marketsnews1\"/> On May 28, 2009, Bank Medici lost its Austrian banking license. Kohn and the Bank are under investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124351941925862619 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Madoff-Hit Bank Medici Loses License | date=May 28, 2009 | first=Flemming E. | last=Hansen | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127064946/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124351941925862619 | archivedate=January 27, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2009, the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] found the firm to be in \"default\" for not assisting regulators.  Cohmad's securities registration has been revoked, and they must provide an accounting of all fees the company or its agents earned for referring Massachusetts investors to Mr. Madoff's firm as well as, pay a $100,000 fine for failing to cooperate with the state securities investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124179163909400903 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Madoff-Tied Brokerage Loses Its Registration | date=May 9, 2009 | first=Robert | last=Frank | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311063346/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124179163909400903 | archivedate=March 11, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2009, Federal prosecutors filed a notice in federal court declaring its intent to seek the forfeiture of the Madoffs' interests in Cohmad Securities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/16/government-files-notice-seeking-madoff-assets/ |title=Government Files Notice Seeking Madoff Assets - DealBook Blog - NYTimes.com |publisher=Dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523193646/http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/16/government-files-notice-seeking-madoff-assets/ |archivedate=May 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, Madoff Trustee, [[Irving Picard]] filed a claim against Cohmad, founder Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn, daughter Marcia Cohn, and Robert Jaffe, among more than two dozen individuals and trusts in [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]] in New York. The lawsuit claims that up to 90 percent of Cohmad's income came from referring clients and that the firm had a \"symbiotic\" relationship with Madoff, having earned hundreds of millions of dollars from the fraud.  The lawsuit seeks more than $100 million paid to Cohmad six years prior to Madoff's firm declaring bankruptcy, and more than $105 million in profits Cohmad employees and their families withdrew from the investment accounts they held with Madoff.\n<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/><ref name=\"bloomberg3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a81_r.GbN1_4 | work=Bloomberg | title=Cohmad's Jaffe Seeks Dismissal of SEC, Picard Counts (Update1) | date=August 21, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224028/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103 | archivedate=January 22, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) also filed civil fraud charges\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Cohmad Complaint 2009-06-22 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109112821/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> against co-founder Maurice \"Sonny\" Cohn, president Marcia Cohn, and Robert Jaffe. The lawsuit alleges the company was Madoff's \"in-house marketing arm\" and critical to Madoff's scam. Cohmad representatives were paid for funds they brought into the firm but not for any increase in the investments' value. Withdrawals were treated as a loss, which \"suggested that profits generated by Madoff were fictitious\", although  Madoff changed the arrangement for Maurice Cohn in 2002, to pay him a flat $2 million a year.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nJaffe has filed requests with the Courts to dismiss the SEC and the Picard cases.  The cases are Picard v. Cohmad Securities Corp., 09-AP- 1305, [[U.S. Bankruptcy Court]], [[Southern District of New York]] (Manhattan), and SEC v. Cohmad, 09-cv-5680, U.S. District Court, (Southern District of New York.).<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/><ref name=\"bloomberg3\"/>\n\n==Stanley Chais, the Brighton Company==\n[[Stanley Chais]] was a wealthy investment advisor from [[Beverly Hills, California]], who was accused of steering money to private interests, including Madoff, through Chais's Brighton Co., a [[limited partnership]] formed to manage money.  He took about 3.8% of the profits as management fees.  His Chais Family Foundation, which in 2007 reported assets of $178 million and charitable contributions of nearly $8.2 million, was wiped out and has shut down.  He had a home in Beverly Hills, and an apartment in New York.\n\nOn May 1, 2009, [[Irving Picard]], bankruptcy trustee, filed a lawsuit against Stanley Chais, 82.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 |work=The New York Times |title=Madoff: Lawsuit Against Stanley Chais |accessdate=May 21, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708012138/http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 |archivedate=July 8, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The complaint alleged Chais \"knew or should have known\" he was deep in a Ponzi scheme when his family investments with Madoff averaged 40% and sometimes soared as high as 300%. It also claimed Chais was a primary beneficiary of the scheme for at least 30 years, allowing his family to withdraw more than $1 billion from their accounts since 1995 \u2013 money that belonged to Madoff victims.<ref>{{cite news |last=Standora |first=Leo |date=2 May 2009 |title=Los Angeles investment manager Stanley Chais sued for funneling cash to Bernie Madoff fund |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/los-angeles-investment-manager-stanley-chais-sued-funneling-cash-bernie-madoff-fund-article-1.409647 |work=New York Daily News |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> The case number is ''Picard v. Chais'', 09-01172. When Chais claimed to be broke, Picard told a judge that Chais should sell his [[Fifth Avenue]] New York apartment to pay his legal fees.<ref>[http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2016/oct/28/bernie-madoff-friends-estate-agrees-to-pay-277-mil/ \"Bernie Madoff friend\u2019s estate agrees to pay $277 million to end lawsuit,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Spokesman-Review''.</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2009, the SEC filed civil fraud charges against Chais. According to the complaint, Chais told Madoff he didn't want to see any losses on the funds' trades.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Chais Complaint 2009-06-22 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109113101/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> On September 23, 2009, California Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]] filed a lawsuit against Chais seeking $25 million in penalties and restitution for victims.<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite news |\nwork=The Los Angeles Times |\ntitle=Financial advisor Stanley Chais sued in Bernard Madoff scheme |\nurl=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-chais23-2009sep23,0,3042092.story |\ndate=September 23, 2009 |\nauthor=Pfeifer, Stuart}}</ref> Federal prosecutors had opened a criminal probe into him, but he died in September 2010 before they filed charges against him.<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.reuters.com/article/madoff-chais/update-2-accused-madoff-middleman-stanley-chais-dies-idUSN2725688920100927?dbk \"Accused Madoff middleman Stanley Chais dies,\"] Reuters.</ref> His lawyer denied that Chais committed any wrongdoing.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nMichael Chaleff, a former [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] lawyer, was part of a 50-member investment group named CMG that lost $75 million to $80 million it gave to Chais' Brighton Co.  Chaleff filed a $250-million [[class action]] federal lawsuit against Chais in Los Angeles, as did [[screenwriter]] [[Eric Roth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2008/12/26/2008-12-26_forrest_gump_eric_roth_screenwriter_sues.html |title='Forrest Gump' Eric Roth screenwriter sues over Madoff losses |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=December 27, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |location=New York |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208001811/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2008/12/26/2008-12-26_forrest_gump_eric_roth_screenwriter_sues.html |archivedate=February 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christensen |first=Kim |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/front/la-fi-madoff-chais21-2008dec21,0,7052710.story |title=A Beverly Hills investor's ties to Madoff sink many \u2013 Los Angeles Times |publisher=Latimes.com |date=December 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130040353/http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/front/la-fi-madoff-chais21-2008dec21,0,7052710.story |archivedate=January 30, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[New Jersey]] State Senator [[Loretta Weinberg]] lost her entire life savings in Chais' \"Arbitrage Partnerships\" fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politickernj.com/max/26238/weinberg-loses-life-savings-ponzi-scheme |title=Weinberg loses life savings in Madoff Ponzi scheme &#124; Politicker NJ &#124; New Jersey Politics News, Reaction, and Analysis |publisher=Politicker NJ |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422063847/http://www.politickernj.com/max/26238/weinberg-loses-life-savings-ponzi-scheme |archivedate=April 22, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/nyregion/new-jersey/18weinbergnj.html |work=The New York Times |title=In Madoff Case, Politicians Current and Former Feel the Loss |first=Jacqueline |last=Mroz |date=January 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 21, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425135604/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/nyregion/new-jersey/18weinbergnj.html |archivedate=April 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nChais died on September 26, 2010 at age 84, in [[Manhattan]], where he and his wife had moved to further the treatment of a [[blood disorder]] that eventually took his life.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-me-stanley-chais-death,0,3602441.story | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Stanley Chais dies at 84; money manager invested with Bernard Madoff | first1=Stuart | last1=Pfeifer | first2=David | last2=Sarno | date=September 26, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007054718/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-me-stanley-chais-death,0,3602441.story | archivedate=October 7, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe widow, children, family, and estate of Chais settled with Picard in 2016 for $277 million.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-chais-idUSKCN12S1Y1 \"Madoff trustee reaches $277 million accord with money manager's family,\"] Reuters.</ref> On November 19, 2016, the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]] approved a global settlement \u2013 made in cooperation with the California Attorney General - with the defendants in ''Picard v. the Estate of Stanley Chais, et al''. The agreement was made with the Stanley Chais estate, Chais\u2019s widow, children, and a number of other Chais family members, investment funds, trusts, companies, and other entities associated with Chais. Under the terms of the agreement, the BLMIS Customer Fund received $277 million, including a cash payment of $258.47 million, as well as the assignment of other assets that would be liquidated over time.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> All proceeds of the settlement were to go to the BLMIS Customer Fund for the benefit of BLMIS customers with allowed claims.<ref>[https://www.madofftrustee.com/document/dockets/007385-chaisorder09-01172docket157.pdf \"ORDER PURSUANT TO SECTION 105(a) OF THE BANKRUPTCY CODE AND RULES 2002 AND 9019 OF THE FEDERAL RULES OF BANKRUPTCY PROCEDURE APPROVING AN AGREEMENT BY AND AMONG THE TRUSTEE AND THE ESTATE OF STANLEY CHAIS AND OTHER DEFENDANTS,\"] November 18, 2016.</ref> Picard\u2019s lawyers said the settlement covered all of Chais\u2019 estate and substantially all of his widow\u2019s assets, and represented \u201ca good faith, complete and total compromise.\u201d<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Tremont Group Holdings==\n{{Main|Tremont Group}}\n\n[[Tremont Group Holdings]], a division of [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company|MassMutual]],<ref name=\"MassMutualTremontSettlement\">{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/07/29/massmutual_unit_to_pay_1b_to_fund_for_madoff_clients/ |title=Madoff clients get $1b in deal |first=Beth |last=Healy |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 29, 2011 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023033248/http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/07/29/massmutual_unit_to_pay_1b_to_fund_for_madoff_clients/ |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> started its first Madoff-only fund in 1997. That group managed several funds marketed under the Rye Select Broad Market Fund,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aCT_aoIRYqRg&refer=home |title=Tremont Group Funds Invested $3.3 Billion With Madoff (Update1) |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123033802/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=January 23, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> which charged a 1% management fee and a 0.5% administration fee. The fund held $2.3 billion on Sep 30, 2008, collecting $34 million in fees a year. Tremont also offered the Rye Select Broad Market Portfolio Ltd., which charged total fees of 1.95% of assets and held $1.2 billion on Sep 30, 2008, with annual fees of $23.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/madoff-feeder-funds-reaped-huge |title=Madoff feeder funds reaped big fees |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 April 2009 |website=MarketWatch.com |access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>  For investing $3.3 billion, Tremont was scheduled to receive over $30 million in fees in 2008. The town of [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]], Conn., is seeking the recovery of fees, and the assets of Robert Schulman, who once ran Tremont Group Holdings have been temporarily frozen.\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123940737747310069 |title=Feeder Fees Topped $790 Million - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=Tom |last=Lauricella |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126190017/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123940737747310069 |archivedate=January 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/12872951/Town-of-Fairfield-suit-against-NEPC-and-KPMG |title=Town of Fairfield suit against NEPC and KPMG |publisher=Scribd.com |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306181226/http://www.scribd.com/doc/12872951/Town-of-Fairfield-suit-against-NEPC-and-KPMG |archivedate=March 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMassachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. has agreed to pay more than $1 billion to customers of the now-imprisoned Bernard Madoff in July 2011. The bankruptcy trustee sued Tremont, a group of hedge funds owned by Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co, as well as, its parent companies in December 2010, seeking more than $2 billion and alleging that company executives ignored \"obvious warning signs'' that Madoff was running a fraud. Picard alleged that Tremont failed to do any meaningful review of Madoff's operations or purported investment results, blindly allowing Rye to turn over half its $6 billion in client assets to Madoff and losing half that money when the scheme finally collapsed. The payment of $1 billion to the Madoff truste, provided by Massachusetts Mutual Life as a loan to Tremont, may have protected the reputation and financial interest of Massachusetts Mutual Life, as well as, saved  Tremont's customers with net gains from Madoff from [[clawback]]s. Some investors of Tremont had a net gains and could have been subject to clawbacks from the bankruptcy attorney if Tremont was forced into insolvency and the bankruptcy attorney could then examine the books of Tremont to see the actual investors' net Madoff gains.\n  \nLawsuits filed have been consolidated into three categories: federal security laws, insurance actions, and state law actions. They are: Lange, et al. v. Mass. Mutual Life Ins. Co., et al. (08 CV 11117, S.D. N.Y.); Finkelstein v. Tremont Group Holdings, Inc. (08 CV 11141, S.D. N.Y.); Peshkin v. Tremont Group Holdings, et al. (08 CV 11183, S.D.N.Y.).; Arthur M. Brainson IRA R/O v. Rye Select Broad Market Fund, L.P., et al. (No. 08 CV 11212, S.D.N.Y.); and Group Defined Pension Plan & Trust v. Tremont Market Neutral Fund, L.P., et al. (No. 08 CV 11359, S.D.N.Y.). The plaintiffs are all investors in hedge funds with assets that they entrusted to Madoff for investment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.lexisnexis.com/practiceareas/Focus-on-Madoff/Securities-Law/Tremont-Group-Moves-To-Consolidate-Madoff-Cases |title=Mealey's Emerging Securities Litigation Report: Tremont Group Moves To Consolidate Madoff Cases |date=March 12, 2009 |website=[[LexisNexis]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120712131834/http://www.lexisnexis.com/community/corpsec/blogs/sec-law-alerts/archive/2012/06/04/mealey_1920_s-emerging-securities-litigation-report_3a00_-tremont-group-moves-to-consolidate-madoff-cases.aspx |archivedate=July 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nFour state law cases have been consolidated with [[Hagens Berman Sobol Shapiro]] as co-lead counsel. They initially filed a class-action lawsuit on behalf of investors and groups that invested capital with [[Tremont Group Holdings]], alleging the company and others grossly neglected fiduciary duties and lost a total of $3.3 billion in assets, $3.1 billion from the Rye Funds invested with Bernard Madoff Investment Securities, relinquishing management to Madoff while continuing to receive client management fees.  The complaint names Tremont Group Holdings, its Rye Investment Funds, Oppenheimer Acquisition Corporation, [[OppenheimerFunds]], which owns Tremont, [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company]], a majority owner of OppenheimerFunds and [[KPMG LLP]], Tremont's auditor, as defendants.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hbsslaw.com/cases/tremont |title=Tremont Group Holdings Lawsuit |date=December 22, 2008 |website=Hagens Berman Sobol Shapiro |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033836/https://www.hbsslaw.com/cases/tremont |archivedate=October 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing assets, in exchange for a pledge of $2.5 million in total from Tremont Entities and Robert Shulman and $500,000 from Oppenheimer Acquisition Corporation. The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nThe Tremont Group is represented by Michael Gruenglas of [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom]] in New York.\n\n===Maxam Capital===\nMadoff was the investment adviser over all the $300 million Maxam Absolute Return Fund's assets. Maxam was scheduled to receive $2.8 million for investing $280 million in 2008. The Town of [[Fairfield, Connecticut]] invested in Madoff through the Return Fund created by Maxam Capital Management LLC, based in [[Darien, Connecticut]]. The Maxam fund in turn invested in Madoff through Tremont. Sandra L. Manzke, the founder of Maxam Capital, has had her assets temporarily frozen by the same Connecticut court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/03/31/madoff-connecticut-ponzi-personal-finance_fairfield.html |title=Judge Freezes Madoff Assets |publisher=Forbes.com |date=March 31, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |first=David |last=Randall}}</ref>\n\nMaxam Absolute Return Fund LP has filed a lawsuit in [[Connecticut Superior Court]] in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]] against auditors Goldstein Golub Kessler LLP and McGladrey & Pullen LLP to recover losses, claiming they relied on the auditors for their expertise in examining Madoff's firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-maxam/maxam-hedge-fund-sues-auditors-over-madoff-losses-idUSTRE50U06V20090131 |title=Maxam hedge fund sues auditors over Madoff losses |last=Giannone |first=Joseph A. |date=January 30, 2009 |editor-last=Hill |editor-first=Gary |website=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2009, Judge Arthur Hiller in [[Bridgeport]], Connecticut, dissolved the temporary order he imposed March 30 freezing assets, and ordered Sandra Manzke, to provide a $2.5 million mortgage on a piece of property she owns in Vermont.<ref>{{cite web |last=Quinn |first=Brigid |url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1653&dept_id=686445&newsid=20299234&PAG=461&rfi=9 |title=Fairfield Minuteman \u2013 Town secures pledges of $25M in Madoff scandal |publisher=Zwire.com |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706213401/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1653&dept_id=686445&newsid=20299234&PAG=461&rfi=9 |archivedate=July 6, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Maxam's attorney, Jonathan D. Cogan said,\"The Town of Fairfield's suit is an outrageous publicity stunt to divert attention from the town's own decision to invest in Madoff, which was made long before it did business with Maxam.\" The pension fund case is Retirement Program for Employees of the Town of Fairfield v. Madoff, FBT-CV-09-5023735-S, Superior Court of Connecticut (Bridgeport)<ref name=\"bloomberg5\"/>\n\nOn July 28, 2011, [[Irving Picard]], the receiver assigned to Madoff's Ponzi scheme, extracted a settlement from Tremont worth over one billion dollars.<ref name=\"MassMutualTremontSettlement\" />\n\n==Defender==\n[[Defender Limited]] acted as a [[feeder fund]], by funneling clients' funds to Bernard Madoff's firm, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities (BLMIS), as part of the Ponzi scheme run by Madoff.{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-settlement-idUSKBN0MJ2F720150323|title=Madoff feeder fund settles; victims' recovery tops $10.6 billion|date=23 March 2015|work=Reuters}}</ref> In December 2013, Defender sued HSBC Institutional Trust Services Incorporated, an Irish subsidiary of [[HSBC Bank]] with registered offices in [[Dublin]], in an Irish court for $539 million.<ref name=\"bvibeacon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://bvibeacon.com/vi-feeder-fund-sues-bank-to-recover-madoff-monies/|title=VI 'feeder fund' sues bank to recover Madoff monies|date=4 December 2013|website=The BVI Beacon}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=f2616787-5f11-4eb0-8af8-dce3a3003fcf|title=Hard to Gain, Easy to Lose? - Lexology|first1=William Fry-Paul|last1=Convery|first2=Derek|last2=Hegarty|website=lexology.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20110321/BUSINESS02/703219913|title=HSBC warned about Madoff 'fraud and operational risks' in two KPMG reports - The Royal Gazette:Bermuda International Business|first=Boris|last=Groendahl|website=The Royal Gazette}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/financial-services/ruling-casts-doubt-on-141m-case-against-hsbc-s-irish-arm-1.3722911|title=Ruling casts doubt on $141m case against HSBC's Irish arm|first=Mary|last=Carolan|website=The Irish Times}}</ref> Defender alleged that the bank failed to conduct adequate [[due diligence]] on Madoff, and failed to warn Defender that HSBC was not able to confirm the existence of Defender's assets.<ref name=\"bvibeacon.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-arm-of-hsbc-bank-being-sued-over-madoff-scheme-29802611.html|title=Irish arm of HSBC bank being sued over Madoff scheme|website=The Irish Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bvi-grey-area.offshore-journals.com/bvi-investment-fund-sues-hsbcs-arm-over-madoff-polzi-scheme-806.html|title=BVI investment fund sues HSBC's arm over Madoff Ponzi scheme - BVI Offshore Business: Grey Area|last=Mike}}</ref>  In December 2018, the [[High Court of Ireland]] ruled that Defender's claim against HSBC was reduced by 100% due to Defender's earlier settlement with BLMIS.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Defender appealed that decision to the Irish [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]], where the appeal is pending.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/judge-says-recusal-hearing-in-madoff-case-would-be-waste-of-court-time-1.3739795|title=Judge says recusal hearing in Madoff case would be 'waste of court time'|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2015, the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]] approved an agreement between Picard on the one hand, and Defender and related entities on the other hand.<ref name=\"madofftrustee.com\">[https://www.madofftrustee.com/recoveries-25.html \"Defender\"]</ref>  The BLMIS Customer Fund benefited by $93 million.<ref name=\"madofftrustee.com\"/>  Defender received a $522.8 million claim in the BLMIS liquidation, because Defender had deposited more with BLMIS than Defender withdrew.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-madoff-settlement-idUSKBN0MJ2F720150323|title=Madoff feeder fund settles; victims' recovery tops $10.6 billion|date=23 March 2015|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n==Fiserv Inc.==\nA $1\u2002billion class-action federal lawsuit was filed in Colorado against [[Fiserv]], Inc. of [[Brookfield, Wisconsin]], whose subsidiaries were custodians for [[pension]] or [[Individual Retirement Account|IRA]] accounts and invested with Madoff. The complaint alleges Fiserv failed \"to hold and safeguard assets entrusted to it\" by about 800 Madoff customers who had been told to hire Fiserv to handle their accounts with him.  Fiserv is accused of breach of [[fiduciary]] duty, [[fraud]], [[negligence]], and aiding and abetting breach of fiduciary. Fiserv sold its investment account administration business in 2007 to [[TD Ameritrade]], also a defendant.  The lawsuit estimates Fiserv generated at least $25\u2002million annually from Madoff investors, and claims it wasn't diligent because \"Fiserv had too much revenue at stake to risk upsetting Madoff.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Gores |first=Paul |url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/43208047.html |title=Fiserv faces suit in Madoff case |publisher=JSOnline |date=April 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424104045/http://www.jsonline.com/business/43208047.html |archivedate=April 24, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Judge Christine M. Arguello ruled in favor of Fiserv Inc. and its co-defendants. Arguello found that the investors bore responsibility for the investment decisions, and that the funds transferred to Madoff were done so at the direction of the investors. Although Madoff was included among Fiserv's investment options, Arguello noted that the IRA agreements provided to Fiserv's investors clearly indemnified the defendants, and that Fiserv \"had no obligation to verify or audit.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Gores |first=Paul |url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/123773989.html |title=Fiserv not responsible for losses in Madoff scheme, judge rules |publisher=JSOnline |date=June 13, 2011 |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206151327/http://www.jsonline.com/business/123773989.html |archivedate=February 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==David and Craig Kugel==\nOn November 16, 2011, longtime Madoff trader David Kugel pleaded guilty to backdating trades for Madoff. Kugel joined the firm in 1970, eventually becoming a supervisor with Madoff's legitimate [[proprietary trading]] operation. In his allocution, he admitted creating bogus trading records as early as the 1970s\u2013further undermining Madoff's claim that he only began his fraud in 1991. He made greater than $10 million in profits from investments with Madoff, and his salary was as high as $588,000 a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/former-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/2011/11/21/gIQATSFLjN_story.html|title=Former Madoff trader David Kugel pleads guilty to fraud|author1=David S. Hilzenrath|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-21/ex-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-bank-fraud-dating-to-1970s |title=Ex-Madoff Trader Kugel Admits to Creating Records of Fake Trades |last=Hurtado |first=Patricia |date=November 21, 2011 |website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720161918/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-21/ex-madoff-trader-david-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-bank-fraud-dating-to-1970s |archivedate=July 20, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He told prosecutors that after the main backoffice secretary on the 17th floor\u2013Annette Bongiorno in the 1970s and 1980s, and Judi Crupi from the 1980s onward\u2013told him how much money should be \"invested\" for a client, he would note how much volume actually occurred so the \"trades\" looked real. He faced up to 85 years in prison.<ref name=WizardofLies>{{cite book|title=The Wizard of Lies|last=Henriques|first=Diana|authorlink=Diana B. Henriques|publisher=[[Times Books]]|date=2011|isbn=978-0805091342}}</ref> However, after testifying at Bongiorno, Crupi, Bonventre and Perez' trial, he was sentenced to 10 months' house arrest and 200 hours community service in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-crime-madoff-kugel-idUSL1N0YI1C720150527|title=Ex-Madoff trader turned prosecution witness avoids prison time|author1=Joseph Ax|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=May 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCraig Kugel pleaded guilty to tax fraud; he arranged salaries for non-employees.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-06-05/ex-madoff-employee-craig-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-tax-scheme |title=Ex-Madoff Employee Craig Kugel Pleads Guilty to Scheme |last=Hurtado |first=Patricia |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |date=June 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130118165232/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-06-05/ex-madoff-employee-craig-kugel-pleads-guilty-to-tax-scheme |archivedate=January 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090416035906/http://www.rightpundits.com/?p=3299 Ruth Madoff Biography] Ruth Madoff biography and photos.\n* [http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/nys/madoff/20090811dipascaliinformationsigned.pdf Frank DiPascali DOJ Information/Plea Agreement] (August 2009)\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/27/serious-fraud-office-bernard-madoff-feeder-funds Serious Fraud Office broadens investigation to Madoff feeders] ''[[The Guardian]]'', March 27, 2009, British government's investigation into the London activities of certain feeder funds that channeled investments to Madoff\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/WSJ-20090406-MerkinComplaint.pdf Merkin Civil Fraud Complaint], State of New York (April 6, 2009)\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkin.exhibitsone0407.pdf#  Exhibits 1\u201320 to Civil Fraud Complaint]\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibitstwo0407.pdf Exhibits 21\u201326 to Civil Fraud Complaint]\n:*[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Merkinexhibits30407.pdf# Exhibits 27\u201348 from Civil Fraud Complaint]\n* [http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/business/0507madoff_Complaint.pdf Bankruptcy Complaint against J. Ezra Merkin] (May 7, 2009)\n* [https://www.scribd.com/doc/15274382/Madoff-Trustee-Suit-Against-Harley Complaint against Harley International (Cayman) Limited] (May 12, 2009)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211040/http://www.sec.state.ma.us/sct/sctcohmad/cohmad_complaint.pdf Commonwealth of Massachusetts Secretary of State Complaint] (January 14, 2009)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091229223951/http://www.nylj.com/nylawyer/adgifs/decisions/062309cohmad.pdf Picard v. Cohmad Securities Corp. 09-AP-1305] (June 22, 2009)\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/cohmadcomplaint20090622.pdf, SEC v. Cohmad Securities Corp., 09 Civ. 5680] (June 22, 2009)\n* [http://documents.nytimes.com/madoff-lawsuit-againt-stanley-chais#p=1 Picard v. Chais et al. 08-01789] (May 1, 2009)\n* [https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/chaiscomplaint20090622.pdf SEC v. Stanley Chais, 09 CIV 5681] (June 22, 2009)\n\n{{Madoff investment scandal}}\n{{2008 economic crisis}}\n\n[[Category:Madoff investment scandal]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Madoff investment scandal| ]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Participants_in_the_Madoff_investment_scandal"}
